.............................................................................. 24</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.6.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan disbursement................................................................................................................................................. 24</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.6.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan documentation............................................................................................................................................... 24</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.6.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grace Period............................................................................................................................................................. 24</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.6.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan repayment Pattern......................................................................................................................................... 24</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk Management............................................................................................................................................................. 25</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.7.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Portfolio distribution and Concentration.............................................................................................................. 25</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.7.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Operational risk management measures........................................................................................................... 25</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Social Performance Management Policy................................................................................................... 27</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>6.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction......................................................................................................................................................................... 27</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Musoni Social Goals......................................................................................................................................................... 27</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Social Performance Dashboard.................................................................................................................................... 27</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reporting............................................................................................................................................................................. 27</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Social Performance management................................................................................................................................ 27</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Environmental Management Policy............................................................................................................... 28</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>7.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Organization and responsibilities................................................................................................................................. 28</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Procedure for environmental scanning.............................................................................................................. 28</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Resources and capabilities............................................................................................................................................ 29</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appendix...................................................................................................................................................................................... 30</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appendix 1: Group Loan Products.......................................................................................................................................... 30</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appendix 2: Agric Loan Products............................................................................................................................................ 31</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appendix 3: Individual Loan Approval and Limits................................................................................................................ 31</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appendix 4: Stawi Loan Approval and Limits....................................................................................................................... 31</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ANNEX: Flow Diagrams of Musoni Credit Procedures................................................................................... 34</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 1: Group and Client Registration (Manual Registration)....................................................................................... 34</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 2: Group and Client Registration (Automated Registration)................................................................................ 35</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 3: Loan Application (Automated)................................................................................................................................. 36</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 4: Loan Application (Manual)........................................................................................................................................ 37</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 5: First Access Credit Scoring process................................................................................................................... 38</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 6: Collateral Refund Process...................................................................................................................................... 39</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 7: Portfolio Handover process.................................................................................................................................... 41</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 8: Agricultural Loan approval process...................................................................................................................... 42</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 9: Individual Loan application &ndash; CRB Check............................................................................................................ 43</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 10: Individual Loan application &ndash; HOCC.................................................................................................................... 44</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 10: Client Exit................................................................................................................................................................... 45</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436151\"></a>1.&nbsp;&nbsp; General Overview</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436152\"></a>1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This purpose of this manual is to provide a framework for the management of credit risk throughout the Institution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It outlines the credit practices throughout Musoni to assure sound credit risk underwriting standards, a thorough credit approval process, thoughtful credit administration procedures and a strong comprehensive credit review process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The manual has seven sections, the first is an overall introduction of the manual, the second contains the policies that are applicable to all the Musoni products, the third section contains the credit policies that will guide in group lending methodology, while the fourth section has the individual lending policies. The fifth section has policies that are applicable to the Agricultural lending, where for this product the group and individual lending methodologies will apply with deviation being the loan appraisal process. The sixth and seventh sections cover Musoni, Social Performance management and environmental policies.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436153\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405750\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405893\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406108\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406329\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406545\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405751\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405894\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406109\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406330\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406546\"></a>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Definition</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>For the purpose of this Manual, Credit Risk is the risk to Earnings and/or Capital, arising from the borrower&rsquo;s failure to meet the terms of any credit contract or otherwise fail to perform as agreed. Credit Risk can also be defined as the risk of loss arising from counter party default.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Credit Risk management is a process. It begins with identification of the markets to which the Musoni desires to lend and proceeds through a series of stages, appraisal, approval, documentation, disbursement, portfolio management and loan repayment. All these stages must be properly managed if Musoni&rsquo;s exposure to credit risk is to be optimized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Credit Policy Manual sets objective standards and parameters that guide Musoni officers in the granting of loans and management of the loan portfolio.&nbsp; This Policy is set to establish a framework within which the Credit Risk arising from lending will be originated and managed in order to minimize the risk of financial loss.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A separate Credit Procedures Manual has been prepared to cover the day-to-day processes and operational procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A number of the procedures presented in the Credit Procedures Manual have been summarized into Workflow Charts to help WCOs with the more common processes. These are included as an Annex to this Manual for ease of use by WCOs.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436154\"></a>1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use and Adherence</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Manual is to be used throughout Musoni and adhered to by all staff. All employees shall be accountable for such adherence.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436155\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405754\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405897\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406112\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406333\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406549\"></a>1.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Responsibility and Approval</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Manual and all subsequent revisions and amendments will be reviewed by the RALCO members and approved by the Board of Directors. The Manual will be reviewed at least once every two years to ensure that the guidelines are kept up to date and properly reflect market conditions and practices. The overall responsibility of the manual lies with the Chief Operations Officer of Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436156\"></a>1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Confidentiality</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual is only to be used by Musoni staff. Neither it, nor any parts are to be copied or distributed to anyone or organization outside of Musoni without written permission from the Chief Executive Officer.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436157\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591943\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591629\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612599\"></a>2.&nbsp;&nbsp; Musoni Universal Policies<a name=\"_Toc441591944\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591630\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430747\"></a></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436158\"></a>2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; About Musoni</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni is the world&rsquo;s first cash-free microfinance Institution. It is a Next Generation Microfinance Institution whose aim is to use technology to deliver more efficient, lower cost microfinance services to the financially excluded.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436159\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591945\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591631\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430748\"></a>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Musoni Vision, Mission and Core values<a name=\"_Toc441591632\"></a></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Our vision</strong>&nbsp;is to be the most efficient microfinance institution in Kenya by being cash free, paperless and data driven, offering the best value, most flexible, and most customer oriented financial services in the market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Our Mission</strong>&nbsp;is to grow, build and maximize the potential of the businesses of the low income and unbanked of Kenya through the provision of affordable, flexible and customer &ndash;oriented financial services<a name=\"_Toc385430749\"></a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni&nbsp;<strong>Core Values</strong>&nbsp;are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I</strong><strong>nnovation:&nbsp;</strong>Develop new ideas to enable us be the most efficient microfinance institution in Kenya, delivering innovative and competitive financial services by using the latest technology and data analytics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Integrity:&nbsp;</strong>Do what is right, treat clients, partners and each other with utmost respect, honesty and uphold the highest ethical standards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Customer Focus:&nbsp;</strong>Delivering process oriented and quality driven services aligned with our customer needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Excellence:&nbsp;</strong>Strive to deliver first class service through best talent and continuous personal and professional development aiming to great value to our staff, clients and shareholders.<a name=\"_Toc385430750\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436160\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591946\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591635\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455140\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405760\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405903\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406118\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406339\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406555\"></a>2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Trading prohibitions compliance</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>To ensure total compliance with Local and International legislation governing the business our operations, Musoni shall not deal with and/or trading in the following areas of business:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in any product or activity deemed illegal under the law or regulations of the Republic of Kenya or international conventions and agreements.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or activities involving harmful or exploitative forms, forced labor/ harmful child labor.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or activities that impinge on the lands owned, or claimed under adjudication, by Indigenous Peoples, without full documented consent of such peoples.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in wood or other forestry products from unmanaged forests</li>\r\n	<li>Drift net fishing in the marine environment using nets in excess of 2.5 km in length.</li>\r\n	<li>Fishing using explosives or other methods harmful to the environment</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in ozone depleting substances subject to international phase out.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in pharmaceuticals subject to international phase outs or bans.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in pesticides/herbicides subject to international phase out or bans.</li>\r\n	<li>Commercial logging operations for use in primary tropical moist forest.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in products containing PCBs<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn1\" name=\"_ftnref1\">[1]</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Production, trade, storage, or transport of significant volumes of hazardous chemicals, or commercial scale usage of hazardous chemicals.</li>\r\n	<li>Trade in wildlife or wildlife products regulated under Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES)<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn2\" name=\"_ftnref2\">[2]</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in radioactive materials.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in or use of unbounded asbestos fibers.</li>\r\n	<li>Purchase of logging equipment for use in primary tropical moist forest.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in weapons and munitions.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in tobacco.</li>\r\n	<li>Gambling, casinos and equivalent enterprises.</li>\r\n	<li>Production or trade in alcoholic beverages (excluding beer and wine).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436161\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405762\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405905\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406120\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406341\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406557\"></a>2.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Industry, Sector or Sub-Sector Surveys</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya shall classify its credit portfolio according to internationally and regulatory accepted Sector Industrial Codes as defined in Appendix 5 of this manual. Musoni shall conduct annual sector surveys in order to determine performance of sectors and define risk appetites within the sectors and markets of operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441591947\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591636\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436162\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405764\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405907\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406122\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406343\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406559\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405766\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405909\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406124\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406345\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406561\"></a>2.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Securities and Security Perfection</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436163\"></a>2.5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Acceptable Securities/Collateral</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni will accept the following forms of collateral:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Personal Guarantees backed by tangible collateral</li>\r\n	<li>Chattels mortgage over personal assets</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Chattels mortgage over business assets</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Legal mortgage for land and buildings with Title</li>\r\n	<li>Equitable mortgage over land/landed property including certificate of ownership for untitled property</li>\r\n	<li>Cash collateral which includes Lien on bank balances, fixed deposit receipts with Musoni or other banks.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Cash collateral is compulsory for all the group loans but will be mobilized on a case-by-case basis for individual loans depending with sufficiency of collateral. In all the cases the securities value must cover loan plus interest to a minimum of 100%. In addition, all individual loans and group Stawi loan will require an external guarantor who must be undertaking a legal income generating activity with ability to pay the applicants loan installments, if and when called upon to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni shall establish a panel of reputable firms to carry out valuation for Plant Machines, Motor vehicles and land</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Loan Amount</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Acceptable Collateral</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Type of Perfection</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Current Value discounted by 50%</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>5,000 &ndash; 100,000</td>\r\n			<td>Group guarantee, House hold and business assets</td>\r\n			<td>Members signature,</td>\r\n			<td>50%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>100,000 &ndash; 300,000</td>\r\n			<td>House hold and business assets</td>\r\n			<td>Chattel mortgage form duly executed</td>\r\n			<td>50%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>300,001 &ndash; 500,000</td>\r\n			<td>Car Log books/Land title deed.</td>\r\n			<td>Log book transfer and charge on title.</td>\r\n			<td>80% of Forced Sale Value</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>500,001 &ndash; 1,000,000</td>\r\n			<td>Land Title deed</td>\r\n			<td>Charge on the title</td>\r\n			<td>100% of Forced sale Value for leaseholds and urban land and 70% for agricultural and rural lands</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The client, spouse and Guarantors shall sign Letter of Offers and Chattel Mortgage form, listing all securities/collaterals prior to loan disbursement.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436164\"></a>2.5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Security perfection</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Original security documents will only be obtained from customers after loan approval. All security documents will undergo security perfection before loan disbursement is done. Credit Administration department will keep records of all security documents undergoing the perfection process.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436165\"></a>2.5.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Movement and Storage of Collateral</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All collateral documents will be stored in a fireproof safe at the head office. Access to the safe will be under dual control. Records of security documents stored in the safe will be maintained and their movement to and from the safe will be tracked. Every branch office shall maintain a security documents tracking register.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc446436166\"></a>2.5.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use of collateral belonging to third parties</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>WCO&rsquo;s will ensure thorough due diligence is done to verify ownership of the asset. In addition, the person under whose name the asset has been registered will provide a duly executed affidavit on the same.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436167\"></a>2.5.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Collection of Perfected Security Documents</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon receipt of a security collection notice, Musoni shall process the security documents within 24 hours of receipt of such notice. The notices will be documented in a register and stored in the security documents safe. Release letter will be issued to the customer and a copy filed by Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436168\"></a>2.5.6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Withdrawal of security/Collateral</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Individual loan customers will only be allowed to withdraw their collateral after their loan facilities have been fully serviced. The customer will make a written request to the BM and the return of the collateral will be made upon the BM&rsquo;s approval after h/she has confirmed that all loans and obligations have been paid in full.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436169\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405768\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405917\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406132\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406353\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406569\"></a>2.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Code of Conduct</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All Musoni staff are expected to uphold the Musoni Code of Conduct as communicated in the HR policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436170\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591949\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591638\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430752\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405919\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406134\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406355\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406571\"></a>2.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Conflict of Interest</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>No loan, other than employee staff loan, shall be granted to an employee of Musoni. No employee should have or appear to have personal interests or relationships that conflict with the best interest of Musoni. A non-exhaustive list of conflict of interest examples include the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Employee has directly or indirectly a financial or non-financial interest in a business/company with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction</li>\r\n	<li>Employee has a partner, child, parent or relative<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn3\" name=\"_ftnref3\">[3]</a>&nbsp;with a financial or non-financial interest in a business/company with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Employee is a member of the Board, Managing Board or Supervisory Board or has a similar status with a company/business with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Where a conflict of interest exists, the employee is required to provide full disclosure. More importantly, the client/business or company for which Musoni intends to enter a transaction with must disclose this relationship. In such a case, the employee shall not be involved in the processing or decision-making process of the loan application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No employee shall influence the lending process to third parties with an objective, direct or indirect, of obtaining preferred personal, financial or other benefit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In case any employee suspects they or one of their colleagues has a conflict of interest this should be reported to their supervisor and / or the hotline (Refer to whistle blowing process).&nbsp; The Musoni management is responsible to investigate and take actions to prevent any negative impacts of conflict of interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436171\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591950\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591639\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405772\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405921\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406136\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406357\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406573\"></a>2.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unethical Conduct</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All staff shall at all times use professional methods to appraise loan applications at all times avoiding a relationship with a borrower that may be of personal gain to the extent of compromising acceptable work ethics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taking gifts or favors from applicants in return for more favorable treatment of customer request constitutes direct conflict of interest and such gifts or favors shall be treated as bribes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this respect, a Musoni staff shall never:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Accept any material gifts of any value from a potential borrower;</li>\r\n	<li>Accept a bribe or a loan from a customer;</li>\r\n	<li>Undertake an investment in / or together with a (potential) borrower&#39;s business;</li>\r\n	<li>Acquire a loan through a borrower&#39;s application and / or account.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Violation of this policy will be tantamount to gross misconduct and may lead to the employee&rsquo;s instant dismissal.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436172\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591951\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591640\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430753\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405774\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405923\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406138\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406359\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406575\"></a>2.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Confidentiality of Information</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>No employee shall disclose any confidential information<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn4\" name=\"_ftnref4\">[4]</a>&nbsp;about Musoni, any of its partners or its clients unless authorized by the CEO and they shall not use such confidential information for their personal gain. Confidential information pertaining to a client may only be released with the written authorization of the client or may be released to the Central Bank of Kenya including auditors appointed by them, in accordance with the law. Confidential information pertaining to a client may also be released to the representatives or appointees of International partners where needed to implement the cooperation of Musoni with these institutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441591952\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591641\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430754\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436173\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405776\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405925\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406140\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406361\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406577\"></a>2.10 Credit Decisions</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436174\"></a>2.10.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Four eye Principle</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The lending process of Musoni requires more than one person to take decisions and to sign documents no matter the hierarchical level of the staff. In the MIS, this is managed by assigning unique user roles and credentials to the staff. Staff must not share their System credentials at all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To effectively implement this principle, Credit decisions will be taken by various credit committee based at different levels as in the table below.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Credit Committee</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Composition</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Mashinani Branch Credit Committee</td>\r\n			<td>A Mashinani (Satellite branch) is the smallest operational unit and report to the branch. Senior WCO (SWCO) supervises the staff in this branch.</td>\r\n			<td>Mashinani SWCO, At least two WCOs, as well as &nbsp;the WCO submitting &nbsp;the loan Application</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Branch Credit Committee</td>\r\n			<td>One or More Mashinani form the branch with the SWCOs&rsquo; all reporting to the BM.</td>\r\n			<td>The Branch Manager as the Chair, with either 2 SWCOs or two WCOS or 1 SWCO and 1 WCO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Regional Credit Committee</td>\r\n			<td>Two or more branches form a region with the BMs reporting to the RGM who heads the region.</td>\r\n			<td>RGM as the Chair, with at least two BMs, including the BM of the branch from where the loan is originated</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Head Office Credit Committee</td>\r\n			<td>The RGMs report to the Chief Operations officer, COO who leads the operations strategy.</td>\r\n			<td>COO as the chair, with the CAM, RGM and the CAO. CFO stands inn when either COO/CAM are on leave.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc441591953\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591642\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430755\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436175\"></a>2.10.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Credit Scoring</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Following recommendation from management, the RALCO committee shall from time to time approve loan products that shall be subjected to credit scoring and will specifically articulate the credit score risk brackets for such loans that shall not be subject to Credit Committee Decision process.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436176\"></a>2.11 Exposure Limits</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The RALCO will from time to time approve sector and product exposure limits as recommended by management.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436177\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591954\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591643\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405779\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405930\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406145\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406366\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406582\"></a>2.12 Limits for Risk, Assets and Liabilities Committee</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board shall constitute a Risk Assets and Liabilities (RALCO) Committee that will manage credit risks of all loan products. Management will from time to time review, improve and recommend changes to the set risk appetite to the RALCO for approval for all products. The RALCO has the responsibility to set and revise loan approval limits for Chief Operations Officer, BMs and SWCOs based in satellite offices and any other management staff who may be involved in lending. The committee shall also approve loans that are above the ceiling set for Head Office credit committee.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436178\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591955\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591644\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405781\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405932\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406147\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406368\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406584\"></a>2.13 Regulatory Loan Portfolio Limits as Percentage of Core Capital</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board, through the RALCO shall also set the single borrower&rsquo;s limit as well as maximum industry limits of loan portfolio as a percentage of the core capital. These limits will be along the lines of prudential requirements of the Central Bank of Kenya for credit concentration and single borrower&rsquo;s limit.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436179\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591956\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591645\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405783\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405934\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406149\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406370\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406586\"></a>2.14 Loan Tracking System Reports</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni will use its operating system to track transactions, process and report performance of all loans alongside and operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436180\"></a>2.15 Loan Restructuring</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni loans shall be restructured only on very special circumstances beyond the control of the borrower and the business being financed. A non-exhaustive example of scenarios that may require loan restricting include political violence, fire, floods all of which have affected the business cash flows. The WCO and Supervisor may propose the restructuring of a loan to the HOCC, who will review and recommend to RALCO for approval.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441591957\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591646\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436181\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405786\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405937\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406152\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406373\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406589\"></a>2.16 Loan Classification and Provisioning</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni management and Board will set up a policy on the loan classification and provisioning that is in line with the prudential guidelines as provided by Central Bank of Kenya and defined in the accounting policy manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436182\"></a>2.17 Additional Administrative fee on arrears and default</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>During loan repayment, any late loan installment will attract additional administrative fee.<a name=\"_Toc446405789\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405940\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406155\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406376\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406592\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405790\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405941\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406156\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406377\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406593\"></a>&nbsp;In the event that a defaulted account is handed over to external recovery agents to enforce recovery, the cost incurred by Musoni together with the accrued additional administrative fee will be borne by the borrower.<a name=\"_Toc446405791\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405942\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406157\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406378\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406594\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436183\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405792\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405943\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406158\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406379\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406595\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405794\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405945\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406160\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406381\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406597\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405795\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405946\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406161\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406382\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406598\"></a>2.18 Write-Off</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436184\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591647\"></a>2.18.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Credit exclusion List</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Loans with payments past due 120 days or more or with more than four installments in arrears will be placed on the Musoni&rsquo;s Credit Exclusion List. Musoni will continue efforts to collect these loans and may use the services of a collection agency or request the assistance of the Recovery department at head office. Until these loans are formally written-off, Musoni will receive credit for any recoveries and the outstanding balance of these loans will be included in the calculation of Portfolio at Risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436185\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591648\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405949\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406164\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406385\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406601\"></a>2.18.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Write Off</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Management shall write off loans above 120 days in arrears on a monthly basis following internal audit review. The RALCO at every sitting shall review the previous quarters write off and recommend the amount to the Board for approval.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436186\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591649\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405951\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406166\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406387\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406603\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405952\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406167\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406388\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406604\"></a>2.18.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Post Write Off: Collection and Legal Action</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All borrowers with loans that have been written off will remain on the Exclusion List. A borrower should never be advised that his/her loan has been written off. Such loans shall be assigned to an authorized collection agency or auctioneer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Difficult cases shall be referred to external legal counsel for advice and appropriate legal action. Management shall conduct a cost and benefit analysis prior to assigning the loans to legal counsel.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436187\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591959\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591651\"></a>3.&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Lending Policy</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436188\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591960\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591652\"></a>3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Loan Policy Objectives</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy has been developed to provide guidelines for Musoni&rsquo;s group loans operation while abiding by the requirements of the microfinance Act of 2006 and regulations of 2008.The overall objectives are to provide guidelines in the administration of the group loan product ensuring timely, efficient and convenient service delivery through use of state-of-the-art technology without sacrificing quality of loans. The policy provides guidelines to assess risks within informal setting and limited financial business data.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436189\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591961\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591653\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430756\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405800\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405958\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406173\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406394\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406610\"></a>3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Target Market</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The group loan product targets those entrepreneurs who operate micro-businesses and are looking for micro loans to help grow their businesses to create more jobs and create more income for the owner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni&rsquo;s group loans shall be directed towards micro economic commercial activities that have been operating for a minimum period of 6 Months in urban or rural locations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436190\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591962\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591654\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430757\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405802\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405960\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406175\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406396\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406612\"></a>3.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lending Authority Limits</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Authority to approve group loans of value KSh 250,000 and Ksh 200,000 below will be decentralized at the branch and satellite office (Mashinani) level respectively. The Board of Directors shall authorize the maximum loan sizes for group loans that shall be approved at Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436191\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591968\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591660\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430761\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405804\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405962\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406177\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406398\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406614\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612623\"></a>3.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Terms and Conditions</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436192\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591661\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430762\"></a>3.4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Formation and Registration</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The following are the guiding policies for Group formation and registration</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Clients s must be Kenyan citizens aged between 18 and 75 years old.</li>\r\n	<li>Clients must be in active business operating for a minimum of 6 months</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Minimum group membership is 5 members and maximum is 30 members, groups registered with five members will be encouraged to add more members to 10 and 15 by second and 30 loan cycle respectively.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All groups will be required to acquire registration certificates before they are financed, in the case that they are in taken at 5 members then they must have the certificate before they are advanced 2nd cycle loans.</li>\r\n	<li>Registration of groups will precede registration of the members. Under no circumstances, should there be group customers who are not attached to any group.</li>\r\n	<li>Group and client registration will be done by WCOs and approved by BMs or SWCO&rsquo;s, who shall validate KYC documents prior to their approval.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>BMs, SWCO&rsquo;s or their designate must conduct physical assessment of all new groups and document their recommendation for financing of such groups.</li>\r\n	<li>No group shall have family members in one group and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Not more that 60% of members shall be in the same business.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436193\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591662\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430763\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405965\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406180\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406401\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406617\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405966\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406181\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406402\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406618\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405967\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406182\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406403\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406619\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405968\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406183\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406404\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406620\"></a>3.4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Meetings</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All Groups must have an agreed upon schedule of meetings. The WCO is responsible for enforcing this discipline and attending the meetings. The meetings shall be scheduled on a Fortnightly or Monthly frequency in line with the client&rsquo;s repayment dates. Group meeting discussions will include but not limited to arrears, loan applications, cash collateral, new members and training on financial literacy, entrepreneurship and public health.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc385430764\"></a>The BM shall visit at least 60% of the groups in their portfolio per quarter. For every visit, the BM shall document their observations and areas for WCO improvement and discuss with the respective WCO after the group meeting</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436194\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591663\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405970\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406185\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406406\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406622\"></a>3.4.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Client Transfers</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Transfer of clients from one group to another has to be done with the approval of both groups and the BM/SWCO. The BM/SWCO shall originate group transfers across branches for the COO&rsquo;s approval.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436195\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591664\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430765\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405972\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406187\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406408\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406624\"></a>3.4.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Client Exits</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Customer exits will either be voluntary, involuntary or in cases of death. In no circumstances shall a client be allowed to exit if the group is in arrears. Where the departing customer has co-guaranteed other loans, the affected customers will be required to jointly increase their cash collateral to the equivalent of the cash collateral of the leaving customer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Customer exit requests will be accompanied by written documentation approved by all group members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BM or SWCO shall conduct client exit interviews and document the responses in the exit form.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436196\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405974\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406189\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406410\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406626\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405975\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406190\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406411\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406627\"></a>3.4.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group split</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Where a group expresses interest to split, due diligence must be conducted by the BM/SWCO to determine if the reasons for split are valid. Upon validation by the BM/SWCO, the group shall provide minutes detailing the reasons for split and the composition in the respective groups formed. Minimum membership in the formed groups should be seven members.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436197\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591969\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591665\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430766\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405806\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405977\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406192\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406413\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406629\"></a>3.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Terms and Conditions</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436198\"></a>3.5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Loan Products</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The clients in groups will be advanced loans individually; the group members will co-guarantee all the loans in the group. Clients in the group set up can access different types of loans including Nawiri, Stawi, Tuelimike, and Wepesi as described below and whose terms are summarized in appendix I of this manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nawiri:&nbsp;</strong>This the very first business loan for the group client. The loan is 100% guaranteed by the group members. The branch credit committee shall approve all Nawiri loans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stawi:&nbsp;</strong>This is business loans for clients who either have history with Musoni through the Nawiri product or have history as a group with other financial institution hence have proven history of good repayment. Since the loan is relatively large, the WCO is required to conduct financial analysis for this loan and the credit decision is based on both the analysis and group guarantee. The analysis is the same as that done in the Individual loan product as defined in Chapter 4 of the Manual.&nbsp; The regional Credit Committee shall approve loan decisions above limits as set out in Appendix 4.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tuelimike Loan:&nbsp;</strong>This Is a loan for group clients who have school fees financing needs for themselves, their children or relatives. It is desirable that the loan be disbursed directly into the schools account.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Wepesi Loan:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;This is an emergency loan whose purpose is to help existing clients meet unforeseen financial needs that arise when they are already servicing either Nawiri or Stawi loans. Only clients with 100% TRP qualify for the loan.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436199\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591666\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430767\"></a>3.5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Application</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All loan applications shall be captured via tablets during group meetings. For every loan application, business and home visits will be done to verify customer location and collateral pledged. All group loan applications shall be done during group meetings and approved by the respective group leaders.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436200\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591667\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430768\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405981\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406196\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406417\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406633\"></a>3.5.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Eligibility</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Loan applications shall be considered from group members if they meet the following eligibility criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Must be in active business and in a Musoni group.</li>\r\n	<li>The business to be financed should have been in operation for at least 6 months.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be Kenyans aged between 18 and 75 years who are holders of national identity card.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have a good reputation in the community, be honest, hardworking and financially reliable.</li>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have a minimum cash collateral of 20% of the loan amount.</li>\r\n	<li>The group in which the applicant is a member must not be in arrears.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436201\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591669\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405983\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406198\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406419\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406635\"></a>3.5.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan purpose</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The group loan shall be advanced for a specific or multiple purposes within the enterprise including Working Capital, purchasing of assets and enterprise diversification.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436202\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591970\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591671\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430771\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612626\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612627\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612628\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612629\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612630\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612631\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612632\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612633\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612634\"></a>3.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Types of Businesses to be financed</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The types of businesses to be financed shall be classified within the international standard industrial as listed in Appendix 5 of this manual:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436203\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591972\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591673\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430772\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612636\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612637\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612638\"></a>3.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Approval</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The BCC or Mashinani Credit Committee will approve group loans. Where the Branch Credit Committee decides to approve a lesser amount, communication shall be made to the customer to establish whether the customer is in agreement with the approved amount. For an application to be approved, no group member should be in arrears.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Approval and disbursement of group loans should be within 72 hours of loan application. BM&rsquo;s/SWCO&rsquo;s will make call backs randomly on a daily basis to verify the authenticity of the loan applications. The CSA shall make call backs to all loan applications, calling at least one member in the Group.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436204\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591973\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591674\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430773\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405810\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405987\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406202\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406423\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406639\"></a>3.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Tenure</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>For loan tenures, refer to the table in appendix 1. Group Loan Products</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436205\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591974\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591675\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430774\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405812\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405989\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406204\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406425\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406641\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612641\"></a>3.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Installments Repayment Frequency</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Group Loan are repaid on Fortnightly/Monthly frequency via mobile money transfer technology. Customers will make repayments using their mobile phone numbers. However, under unavoidable circumstances, third parties can make the repayments on the customer&rsquo;s behalf.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Loan Officers should not make repayments on behalf of customers unless approval from the BM has been obtained beforehand. This will be limited to cases of bad debt recovery, not simply late payments or slow collections. Under such circumstances, the money will be handed over to the CSA who will make the deposit on behalf of the customer, and maintain documented evidence of such payments.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436206\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591975\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591676\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430775\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405814\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405991\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406206\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406427\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406643\"></a>3.10 Grace Period</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The type of loan advanced will determine whether grace period is granted or not. A grace period shall be granted for a period not exceeding two weeks for business loans and not exceeding six months for Agricultural loans, as recommended by the WCO upon analysis of the cash flow calendar and depending on the agricultural activity that will be generating the income for the loan repayment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Customers need to be advised that the grace period is a consideration for their preparation time to invest the loan proceeds and not an incentive to be enjoyed. It is a cost to the business through additional interest payment, therefore it is in the borrower&rsquo;s interest to reduce the cost of borrowing by starting to pay their loans promptly as soon as the business can support the loan installment.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436207\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591976\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591677\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430776\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405816\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405993\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406208\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406429\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406645\"></a>3.11 Loan Disbursements</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All approved loans shall be disbursed via mobile money except where the amount is more than the stipulated limit set by the mobile service providers. In this case, the loans will be disbursed via direct bank transfer. There will be no cash transaction at Musoni offices at any time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For loans disbursed via mobile money transfer, Mpesa Validation &nbsp;will be done to ensure that the mobile numbers provided by the customers have been registered and belong to them. BMs should be keen enough to ensure that loan disbursements are done correctly. In case the amount disbursed is more than the approved amount, customers will be advised to refund the excess amount to Musoni via Musoni&rsquo;s Pay Bill number. No refunds will be made through staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446405818\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405995\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406210\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406431\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406647\"></a>3.12 &nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc446436208\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591977\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591678\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430777\"></a>Interest Rate</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board RALCO will recommend changes in interest rates according to changes in the market rates and cost of loan capital funds. Interest rates for Group Loans are defined in appendix 1 of this document.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436209\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591978\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591679\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430778\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405820\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405997\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406212\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406433\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406649\"></a>3.13 Loan Application Fees</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Loan processing (upfront) fees shall be charged at a rate of 3% of the loan amount approved to the borrower for purposes of loan application processing costs. This fee will be deducted from the approved loan amount.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436210\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591979\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591680\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430779\"></a>3.14 Legal Fees and other Charges</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Applicants whose loans are approved and may require perfection of the loan securities will be asked to meet these costs directly. Such fees include loan insurance premium fee, RTGS fees, registration of chattels where they are executed through a legal counsel/ advocate. All fees shall be paid before disbursement of any loan. Musoni shall charge an administrative fee on late repayment at a rate of 1% of the late instalment.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436211\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591980\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591681\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430780\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405823\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406000\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406215\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406436\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406652\"></a>3.15 Subsequent Loans</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni shall grant repeat loans based on borrower performance in repaying the first or previous loans, on demonstrating that part of the profits obtained using the previous loan has been retained for growth of the business and on the level of group cohesion. Loan sizes for subsequent loans will be subjected to graduation limits.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436212\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591981\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591682\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430781\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405825\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406002\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406217\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406438\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406654\"></a>3.16 Cash Collateral</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All group loans will require 20% of cash collateral, it is imperative that the clients build the cash collateral consistently without lump sum deposits since the collateral trend is indicative of the business cash flows.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Full and partial collateral refunds will be made in cases of voluntary exits, involuntary exits and death on condition that the customer is not servicing any loan, the group is not in arrears and the whole group has consented to the withdrawal. In such cases, proper documentation should be availed and the rest of the group members should increase their cash collateral to the equivalent of the amount being withdrawn.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436213\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591983\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591686\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430785\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405827\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406004\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406219\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406440\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406656\"></a>3.17 Delinquency Management and Loan Recovery</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Once a payment is not made on the due date, it will be considered delinquent. The arrears shall be recorded and used for determination of borrower classification into risk categories. Such delinquency if numerous, shall deny the customer a repeat loan even after paying off the current loan.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436214\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591984\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591687\"></a><a name=\"_Toc385430786\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405829\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406006\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406221\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406442\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406658\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612653\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612654\"></a>3.18 Borrower&rsquo;s Follow Up</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>When one installment payment is missed, the WCO shall inform the group members and visit the borrower within the following five days. Group members, through the power of the co-guarantee agreement signed on the loan application form, have the responsibility to cover for the installment missed by any member. Loan delinquency is unacceptable; therefore, WCOs should ensure on-time loan repayments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc441591992\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591696\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612656\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612657\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612658\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612659\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612660\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612661\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612662\"></a><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436215\"></a>4.&nbsp;&nbsp; Individual Loan Policy</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436216\"></a>4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy has been developed to provide guidelines for Musoni&rsquo;s individual loans operations while abiding by the requirements of the Microfinance Act of 2006 and Central Bank Regulations of 2008.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The overall objective is to provide guidelines in the administration of the individual loan product ensuring timely, efficient and convenient service delivery through use of state of-the-art technology without sacrificing quality of loans. In particular, the policy provides guidelines into credit analysis to assess risks within informal setting and limited financial business data.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436217\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405833\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406010\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406225\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406446\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406662\"></a>4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Target market</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The individual loan product targets those entrepreneurs whose businesses have grown beyond micro and have potential of growing faster to create more jobs and create more income for the owner. It provides a growth path for group loan customers who would like to graduate to larger loan sizes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni individual loans are directed towards legally licensed small economic commercial activities in urban and rural locations operating it for at least one year. The loan use shall include: working capital diversification or purchase of asset.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436218\"></a>4.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Condition</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Minimum loan is KSh 100,000 and maximum is KSh 1,000,000 while minimum loan term is 3 months and maximum 36 months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individual loan Clients in their second and subsequent loan cycles clients can as well be advanced school fee and emergency loans. For these loans, two guarantors who are Musoni Clients and 20% cash collateral is mandatory.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436219\"></a>4.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Types of businesses to be financed</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The types of businesses to be financed shall be classified within the international standard industrial as listed in Appendix 5 of this manual:</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436220\"></a>4.3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Client Intake</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Loan applications shall be considered from qualified business persons either from the existing group based borrowers whose needs outgrow the group structure or new customers seeking credit for expansion of their business if they meet the following eligibility criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Must be in active business and such business to be financed should have been operating for at least 1 year,</li>\r\n	<li>Be Kenyans aged between 18 and 75 years who are holders of a valid national identity card,</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have the relevant business license and permits as required by the respective Government authorities,</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have a good reputation in the community, be honest, hardworking and financially reliable and</li>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have adequate collateral to secure the loan with business assets or personal assets.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436221\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406030\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406245\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406466\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406682\"></a>4.3.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan purpose</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The individual loan shall be advanced for a specific earmarked purpose or multiple purposes within the enterprise.&nbsp; Qualifying customers can use the loan funds for the following purposes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Working capital to be used for utilities, purchase of inventory, wages and other expenses, which are associated with operating a microenterprise.</li>\r\n	<li>Fixed assets purchases including tools, equipment and machinery. Customers shall be advised to invest in equipment or machinery that will quickly begin to produce and generate cash.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436222\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406032\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406247\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406468\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406684\"></a>4.3.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Appraisal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>For all loan applications, the WCO and BM/SWCO will conduct due diligence on the client KYC documents including the client ID, the Mpesa number, and the PIN certificate e.tc. The WCO will be required to conduct site visits both at home and at the business premise to ascertain the existence and validity of the business and the assets. WCO will be required to re-generate the client&rsquo;s business financial position as well as the balance sheet, from which financial ratios will be derived to establish the ability of the client to repay the loan.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436223\"></a>4.3.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Analysis</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Analysis of the loan applied will entail the WCO generating the following financial ratios: Liquidity, Leverage, Cash Flow, Profitability and activity.&nbsp; These shall be weighted and the average of the weighed ratios will inform the credit decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436224\"></a>4.3.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Decisions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The regional Credit Committee and HOCC shall approve loan decisions above limits as set out in Appendix 7.3.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436225\"></a>4.3.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Charges</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The charges on the loan will include the following: upfront fee 3%, enhance credit life insurance premium at 1%, Interest at 18% P.a. Other fees include RTGS, Credit Reference Bureau charge and Chattels perfection fee. For repayments that fall in arrears, additional credit administration fee shall be levied. All these are borne by the client.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436226\"></a>4.3.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grace period</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Individual Loans will not attract any grace period.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436227\"></a>4.3.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Disbursements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All loans below KSh 140,000 will be disbursed through Mpesa, while loans above KSh 140,000 will be disbursed directly to the client&rsquo;s bank account through RTGS within 12 hours of the full perfection of the securities.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436228\"></a>4.3.10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Documentation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each branch shall maintain credit files for all business loans and electronic backup kept externally and at MIS/IT department at head office. Each credit file shall have all relevant credit documents including loan application (if hard copies were used), signed loan agreement and all copies of collateral documents. All original security documents shall be kept in the head office under safe custody</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436229\"></a>4.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Monitoring</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>WCO will monitor to see that loan funds are used for the purpose identified in the loan application. The WCO and BM will however be expected to follow up with the client immediately the loan is disbursed and ensure that the loan is used for the intended purpose.&nbsp; During the loan tenure, WCO will be conduct client business visits to monitor the business progress.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436230\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592006\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591716\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612668\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612669\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612670\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612671\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612672\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612673\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612674\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612675\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612676\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612677\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612678\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612679\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612680\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612681\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612682\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612683\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612684\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612687\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612689\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612690\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612691\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612692\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612693\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612694\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612695\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612696\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612697\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612698\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612699\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612700\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612701\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612702\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612703\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612704\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612705\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612706\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612707\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612708\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612709\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612710\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612711\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612712\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612713\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612714\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612715\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612716\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612717\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612718\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612719\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612720\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612721\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612722\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612723\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612724\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612725\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612726\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612727\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612728\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612729\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612730\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612731\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612732\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612733\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612734\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612735\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612736\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612737\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612738\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612739\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612740\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612741\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612742\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612743\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612744\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612745\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612746\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612747\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612748\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612749\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612750\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612751\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612752\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612753\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612754\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612755\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612756\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612757\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612758\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612759\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612760\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612761\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612762\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612763\"></a>4.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Subsequent Loans</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni shall grant repeat loans based on borrower performance in repaying the first or previous loans and on demonstrating that part of the profits obtained by the previous loan has been retained for use in the growth of the business. A detailed business analysis shall be conducted at all loan cycles and financial ratios generated will inform the loan decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436231\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592012\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591731\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612765\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612766\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612767\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612768\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612769\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612779\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612780\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612781\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612782\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612783\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612784\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612785\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612786\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612787\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612788\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612789\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612790\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612791\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612792\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612793\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612794\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612795\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612796\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612797\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612798\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612799\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612800\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612801\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612802\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612803\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612804\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612805\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612806\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612807\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612808\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612809\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612810\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612811\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612812\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612813\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612814\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612815\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612816\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612817\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612818\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612819\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612820\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612821\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612822\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612823\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612824\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612825\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612826\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612827\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612828\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612829\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612830\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612831\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612832\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612833\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612834\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612835\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612836\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612837\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612838\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612839\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612840\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612841\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612842\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612843\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612844\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612845\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612846\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612847\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612848\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612849\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612850\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612851\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612852\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612853\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612854\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612855\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612856\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612857\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612858\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612859\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612860\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612861\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612862\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612863\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612864\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612865\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612866\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612867\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612868\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612869\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612870\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612871\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612872\"></a>4.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Classification and Provisioning</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni management and Board will set up a policy on the loan classification and provisioning that is in line with the prudential guidelines as provided by Central Bank of Kenya.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436232\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592013\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591732\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612874\"></a>4.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Delinquency Management and Loan Recovery</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Once a payment is not made on the due date, the loan will be considered delinquent. The arrears shall be recorded and used for determination of borrower classification into risk categories. Such delinquency if numerous, shall deny the customer a repeat loan even after paying off the current loan.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436233\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591733\"></a>4.7.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Borrowers Follow Up</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>When one installment payment is missed, the WCO shall visit the borrower within the following five days. The WCO should discuss the reasons for delay and agree with the borrower on the exact date when the missed installment shall be paid. The client must commit in writing the agreed date of repayment. The WCO will inform the Supervisor of the status after the visit.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436234\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591734\"></a>4.7.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First Demand Notice</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In even that, the borrower does not make a payment by the agreed date and such follow-ups have been for more than one month, a formal demand notice shall be written by the CAM or designated Credit Supervisor. This letter will give the borrower 14 days&rsquo; notice to clear the arrears.&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc441591735\"></a>If the payments are not made good, a Second Demand Notice shall be issued.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436235\"></a>4.7.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Second Demand Notice</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If after the First Demand Notice the installment remains unpaid for the next 14 business days, the Recovery Officer will issue the Second Demand Notice.&nbsp; This notice shall inform the client to pay the missed installments (both principal and interest) plus any installment that may fall due by the time of payment, within 14 days, effectively to make the loan current.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436236\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591736\"></a>4.7.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Third and Final Demand Notice</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If the borrower fails to make repayment within the said 14 days after the Second Demand Notice and no agreement is reached for the borrower to pay the total missed installments plus interest due, the entire outstanding loan plus interest and costs thereof, will become due and payable immediately.&nbsp; The Third and, Final Notice shall be sent to the client stating the intent to collect the entire debt plus costs thereof.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc444612876\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612877\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612878\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612879\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612880\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612881\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612882\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612883\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612884\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612885\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612886\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612887\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612888\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612889\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612890\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612891\"></a><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436237\"></a>5.&nbsp;&nbsp; Agricultural Loan Policy</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436238\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592017\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591743\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612894\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612895\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612896\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612897\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612898\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612899\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612900\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612901\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612902\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612903\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612904\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612905\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612906\"></a>5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436239\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591744\"></a>5.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Background and Rationale</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Agriculture is the mainstay of Kenya&rsquo;s economy and currently accounting for 26 % of the GDP directly and 25 % indirectly. It contributes for 65 % of Kenya&rsquo;s total exports and provides more than 18 % of formal employment and more than 70 % of informal employment especially in the rural areas. It has however continued to get the least share of private funding, 4.5% of financial sector financing as indicated by the Kenya Central Bank Annual Report 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This lack of supporting to agriculture finance is a key limiting factor to the development of many smallholder farmers in Kenya. With the Mobile Phone financing model and the Agricultural Loan (Kilimo Booster), Musoni has positioned itself to be the driver of change in the rural/agricultural finance landscape.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436240\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591745\"></a>5.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Musoni Agricultural Lending Objectives</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The overall objective of Musoni agricultural lending, referred to as&nbsp;<strong>Kilimo Booster</strong>&nbsp;is to accelerate the growth of Musoni lending while the specific objectives are at three levels Business, Social and corporate Image.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Increase market share by taking advantage of opportunities that exist within the Agricultural sector</li>\r\n	<li>Improve on institutional profitability</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Increase outreach in rural areas targeting excluded segments</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The social objective is to economically empower smallholder farmers by enabling them access credit facilities to support expansion, diversification and growth of their Agricultural Livelihoods.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436241\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591746\"></a>5.1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Strategy to Support the Realization of Objectives</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of Musoni Agricultural Lending Policies is to serve as a guide for building a quality and sustainable Agricultural Loan Portfolio. This is by facilitating the mitigation of the risks associated with Agricultural lending such as but are not limited to:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Volatility of production and incomes of agricultural producers.</li>\r\n	<li>Seasonality of farm incomes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Unresponsive products and poor delivery mechanisms</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Lack of effective collateral or equivalent loan security.</li>\r\n	<li>Moral hazard</li>\r\n	<li>Lack of a working support structure for agricultural marketing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436242\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592022\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591751\"></a>5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Target Market</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Musoni Kenya agricultural loan product shall be accessed by any Kenyans who are involved in small scale agricultural related income generating activities at any level of the value chain and meet the legibility criteria as per section of this manual. In determining the eligibility, all income generating activities/enterprises that the applicant is engaging inn shall be considered when building the cash flow calendar upon which the lending decision will be made. Priority shall be given to customers with regular monthly incomes to support the repayments. The analysis will be done on the agriculture based activity and any other economic activity the customer is involved in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this manual, the levels of value chain shall include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Input supply:</strong>&nbsp;This market category shall include all input suppliers/Agro-Vet dealers</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Agricultural Production:</strong>&nbsp;This market category shall include those involved in crop and livestock production, aquaculture and apiculture.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Produce Dealers or Traders:</strong>&nbsp;This market category shall include all those involved in trading in different agricultural produce</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a name=\"_Toc245790111\"></a>&nbsp;<strong>Processors</strong><strong>:</strong>&nbsp;This category shall include those involved in value addition to the agricultural produce. Processors shall include a wide range of merchants who are involved in storage, sorting and grading, processing both food and non-food items.<a name=\"_Toc245790114\"></a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436243\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592023\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591752\"></a>5.2.1. Categories of target subsectors</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Agricultural enterprises to be funded are that fall under these four subsectors as listed in appendix 5, and shall be under two broad product categories as below:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Kilimo Booster:&nbsp;</strong>these include</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Food Crops</strong>: These are the crops whose harvested produce will be sold and used mainly as food. The enterprise here falls under three main categories:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Cereals:&nbsp;</strong>these include maize, wheat, sorghum, rice, millet, rise, Wheat</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Pulses</strong>&nbsp;namely beans, pigeon pea, beans, cowpea, chickpea, green grams,</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Roots and tubers</strong>&nbsp;including sweet potato, Irish potato, cassava, arrow root and yam.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Horticulture</strong>: These crops whose harvested produce is mainly for export and enterprise here include cut flowers, vegetables, fruits, nuts, herbs and spices</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Livestock</strong>: this subsector will include enterprise such as dairy and beef, poultry, piggery</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Kilimo Biashara (Business):&nbsp;</strong>Are Agribusiness enterprises and include smallholder farmer support services providers and the enterprises include Input suppliers, Agric produce Transporters, Agriculture produce processors, Agriculture Produce Retailers and wholesalers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436244\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405849\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406060\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406275\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406496\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406712\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405850\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406061\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406276\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406497\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406713\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405851\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406062\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406277\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406498\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406714\"></a>5.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lending Methodology</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Agriculture loan will be delivered using both group and individual lending Methodology as defined in this manual, hence the intake process will be defined as in section 3.5 (group terms and conditions). While for Individual loan of Agriculture nature, the intake and management will be as defined in section 4.3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For both the lending methodologies, the point of diversion from group and Individual policy is on the loan appraisal and analysis, the loan repayment pattern and the allowed grace period. WCO will generate a cash flow calendar for the applicant taking into consideration, farm activities example crop production or rearing of livestock, as well as off farm activity example an Mpesa outlet, extension services etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436245\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405853\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406064\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406279\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406500\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406716\"></a>5.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additional Loans</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Agriculture loan Clients in their second and subsequent loan cycles will be eligible to be advanced school fee and emergency loans. For these additional loans, 2 guarantors who are Musoni Clients and 20% cash collateral is mandatory for both individual and Group Agric Clients</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436246\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446405855\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406066\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406281\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406502\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446406718\"></a>5.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Conditions</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436247\"></a>5.5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Product Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Kilimo Booster loan product terms are listed in Appendix 2 of this document.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436248\"></a>5.5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Purpose</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of Kilimo Booster loan is to enhance the productivity of Smallholder farm business by enabling smallholder farmers diversify income sources, expand current operations, grow, and consolidate their Agricultural activities/enterprises. The loan use includes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em>Asset financing;</em></strong>&nbsp;for the acquisitions of Productivity enhancement, Direct Productive Assets, Post-harvest handling facilities, Value addition Assets that improve the quality and shelf life of farm products and increase farm income.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em>Working Capital;</em></strong>&nbsp;in terms of Farm Inputs E.g. Seeds, fertilizers and chemicals, veterinary drugs, livestock and poultry feeds; Farm Operations E.g. Field preparation, ploughing, Planting, Weeding, Harvesting, Post-harvest handling; Marketing costs namely Packaging and Transport</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436249\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592024\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591753\"></a>5.5.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eligibility criteria</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The applicant for Kilimo Booster Loan Must meet the following criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Be a Kenyan citizen.</li>\r\n	<li>Be at least 18 year of age and not above 70 years of age.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be engaged in Income generating Agricultural activities and have been involved in any stage of the agricultural value chain for at least two consecutive cycles preceding the application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Have appropriate collateral requirement for either the group or individual methodology</li>\r\n	<li>For asset, financing the borrower must be willing to contribute at least 10% of the asset to be financed.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc441592026\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591758\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436250\"></a>5.5.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Appraisal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Business and Home Visit:</strong>&nbsp;For all loan applications, the WCO will conduct due diligence on the client KYC documents including the client ID, the Mobile Money number, and the PIN certificate e.tc. The WCO will be required to conduct site visits both at home and at the business premise to ascertain the existence and validity of the Agribusiness Activities and the assets. &nbsp;The information to be collected include, Production and Income, Farm Business and House hold expenditure, Farm assets and Liabilities, Past and present credit history and the Guarantors of the credit. Using this information WCO will generate the client&rsquo;s Cash flow calendar based on both the historical performance of the enterprises and projected performance for the season to be financed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Credit analysis</strong><strong>:&nbsp;</strong>The purpose of credit analysis is to establish the repayment capacity of the enterprise. Using the information from the loan appraisal, the WCO conducts a credit analysis as by constructing a projected cash flow calendar and the balance sheet. WCO then proceed to calculate the financial ratios, which will inform the final credit decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Constructing the Cash Flow Calendar</strong><strong>:&nbsp;</strong>The WCO will prepare the cash flow calendar by consolidating on a monthly basis all the cash inflow streams from the different enterprise and subtracting the consolidated cash outflows from both agribusiness and home. The Cash flow calendar will thus be the financial projection for the period that the client is expected to repay the loan facility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Calculate Financial Indicators:&nbsp;</strong>For purpose of the Loan application the following ratios shall be used for credit decisions;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Repayment capacity<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn5\" name=\"_ftnref5\">[5]</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Loan amount applied + Total interest Payablex100%</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accumulated Net cash flow in the period</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Determining instalment Size<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn6\" name=\"_ftnref6\">[6]</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Proposed Loan instalment (Principal +interest) x100%</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accumulated monthly Net cash flow (borrower surplus)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Level of Indebtedness<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftn7\" name=\"_ftnref7\">[7]</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; = &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total Liabilities+ New Loan&nbsp;X100%</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Total Assets</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436251\"></a>5.5.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan Charges</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Other charges on the group Agric Loans include, upfront fee at 3%, enhance credit life insurance premium at 0.7% for loans above KSh 70,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For loans above KSh 100,000 and where the enterprise to be financed contributes over 60% of the net cash inflow, Crop insurance fee of 5%, Livestock insurance fee 4% on the loan phase value. The client shall pay all these charges upfront.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436252\"></a>5.5.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan disbursement</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All loans up to KSh 140,000 will be disbursed to the client mobile numbers while those above KSh 140,000 will be disbursed to the client&rsquo;s bank account through RTGS. Asset finance loans will be disbursed to the selling agents account.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436253\"></a>5.5.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan documentation.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each branch shall maintain credit files for all business loans and electronic backup kept in a dedicate Cloud hosting service. Each credit file shall have all relevant credit documents including loan application (if hard copies were used), signed loan agreement and all copies of collateral documents. All original security documents shall be kept in the head office under safe custody</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436254\"></a>5.5.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grace Period</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Based on the outcome of the projected cash flow calendar, the credit committee can recommend either a loan grace period or Zero grace period. The grace period will not exceed Six Months.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436255\"></a>5.5.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loan repayment Pattern</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The repayment pattern of Kilimo Booster loans can be regular with no grace period, irregular with up to six months&rsquo; grace period or Balloon. The cash flow calendar will inform the kind of repayment Pattern that will be recommended by WCO and approved by the credit committee. Maximum tenure of balloon pattern of repayment shall be 8 months.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Regular repayment pattern without grace period</strong>: Where the cash flow calendar projects positive cash flows in all the months when the loan is to be serviced and the financial indicators above are not breached</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Irregular repayment pattern with one to six months&rsquo; grace period</strong>: Where the cash flow calendar projects negative net cash flows in the first months thereafter positive cash flows in the following months and the financial indicators above are not breached</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Balloon repayment pattern</strong>: Where the cash flow calendar projects negative cash flows in the months when the loan is to be serviced with lump sum revenue at the end of the season.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436256\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592029\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591763\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612913\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612914\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612915\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612916\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612917\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612918\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612919\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612920\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612921\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612922\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612923\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612924\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612925\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612926\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612927\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612928\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612929\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612930\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612931\"></a><a name=\"_Toc444612947\"></a>5.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk Management</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The risk exposure within the agricultural loan portfolio will be managed by employing both individual credit risk and portfolio credit risk measures. The individual credit risk exposure will be reduced through proper management of the lending process as detailed under section 4.6.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436257\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591764\"></a>5.6.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Portfolio distribution and Concentration</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to maintain covariance and risk interdependencies at a minimum the agricultural loan portfolio will be diversified by having a larger number of clients with different risk profiles. In order to achieve this:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Maximum loan amount to a borrower shall not exceed KES 500,000 for group and KES 1,000,000 for individual</li>\r\n	<li>Total agricultural loan portfolio shall not exceed 30% of the total Musoni loan portfolio by value, the same limit shall apply for branch portfolio contribution.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>No more than 40% of the branch total agricultural loan portfolio shall be maintained under one subsector (Cash Crop, Food crop, Horticulture, Livestock and Poultry, Agribusiness Support Services)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>No more than 10% of the branch total agricultural loan portfolio shall be maintained under one enterprise (commodity or value chain) such as maize, dairy, poultry, etc.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc446436258\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591766\"></a>5.6.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Operational risk management measures</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>In situations where investments will be required at different stages of the farming cycle, single disbursement of approved loan amount but the WCO shall be vigilant in regard to monitoring to prevent misapplication of loans.</li>\r\n	<li>Through strategic partnerships farmer borrowers shall be supported to have access to Supplementary support services such as of access to improved varieties, modern farming techniques, inputs, market information and marketing channels to ensure adequate utilize borrowed amounts as well as earning adequate returns on their efforts.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To ensure that borrowers utilize borrowed funds as intended the WCOs shall visit the borrowers at their enterprise quarterly</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Risk department shall conduct Quarterly of Sector / Regional distribution of value of loans disbursed and Loan Portfolio at Risk will be conducted to determine the risk exposure.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc441591767\"></a><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A risk transfer strategy through an insurance cover will be employed to deal with catastrophic risks and events as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All individual Kilimo Booster Loans shall be having a minimum of enhanced credit life insurance cover.</li>\r\n	<li>For the Group Kilimo loans, all the loans under the balloon repayment plan shall be insured.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Kilimo Booster loans over KSh. 100,000 will be subjected to a risk evaluation to determine the total enterprise exposure to the clients&rsquo; cash flows. The loan shall be subject to insurance if the financed enterprise is contributing to over 60% of the total business cash flows. Insurance premium at an agreed rate of the loan amount shall be paid by the borrower to provide a catastrophe cover for crop failure due to drought or floods, livestock mortality, credit life for the principal borrower and all assets at risk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All asset-financing loans above KSh 100,000 shall be subject to all risk asset insurance cover.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc441592030\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591768\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455167\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142217\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377454065\"></a><a name=\"_Toc375505523\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436259\"></a>6.&nbsp;&nbsp; Social Performance Management Policy.</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436260\"></a>6.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni will adopt a double bottom line approach in its operations hence use various tools to monitor both its financial and social goals. The Social Performance Management will entail Social goals, performance target and indicators for each social goal, source of information, SPM reporting system and the users of the SPM report.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436261\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592032\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142219\"></a>6.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Musoni Social Goals</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>To grow, build and maximize the potential of the businesses of the low income and under banked of Kenya through the provision of affordable, flexible and customer &ndash;oriented financial services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the mission statement, the following will be Musoni&rsquo;s social goals:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Focus on reaching more micro businesses</li>\r\n	<li>Develop sustainable tailor made product and services for the rural client</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Improve social- economic well-being for the clients.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Maintain client satisfaction rate of 85%</li>\r\n	<li>Establish Partnerships with organizations offering environmental friendly products</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436262\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592033\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591771\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455169\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142220\"></a>6.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Social Performance Dashboard</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Social aspects that Musoni will endeavour to measure are Progress out of poverty index, Client Outreach, Range of services, Client Protection, Client Satisfaction, Client Transformation, Environmental preservation, SPM Implementation, SPM monitoring and reporting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The PPI set of questions will be embedded in the site visit forms for all the loan types and administered for every loan application. PPI reports will thereafter be generated by the MIS.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441591772\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455170\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436263\"></a>6.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reporting</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the Cerise tool, Musoni will conduct regular Social Audits and evaluate the social goals while the Progress out of Poverty Index tool (PPI) will be used to collect data and monitor client&rsquo;s growth, improvement and transformation through Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441591773\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455171\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142221\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436264\"></a>6.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Social Performance management</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni&rsquo;s social performance will be managed as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The COO will oversee the inclusion and Implementation of SPM in the institutions corporate strategy.</li>\r\n	<li>The SPM committee that comprises of COO, A RGM, Training Officer, a BM, an SWCO/ WCO and a finance rep (Admin Officer), will meet on a regular basis to deliberate and evaluate the monthly/ quarterly SPM achievements vs targets.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Each branch will appoint its SPM Champion who will be responsible for coordinating and reporting on the branch SPM activities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Management shall prepare Quarterly reports showing progress to achieving the Social Performance Goals.The board shall review and approve the Social targets as recommended by management during the Annual Operational Planning and Budget process.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc441592034\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591774\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455172\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436265\"></a>7.&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmental Management Policy.</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436266\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592035\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591775\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142223\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377454067\"></a>7.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Organization and responsibilities</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Environmental Coordinator is responsible for environmental issues. The COO shall be the companies nominated Environmental Coordinator. His responsibilities include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Reporting to Musoni management on environmental issues;</li>\r\n	<li>Reviewing Musoni&rsquo;s environmental management policy and procedures on a periodic basis;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Ensuring that the environmental policy and procedures are implemented;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Providing assistance to WCOs where required;</li>\r\n	<li>Ensuring that copies of this Environmental Management Policy are widely available at Musoni;</li>\r\n	<li>Ensuring that records or data on environmental reviews and supervision are maintained;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Preparing and submitting an annual environmental performance report to the Board of Directors and shareholders.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The HOCC will ensure that lending decisions are based on appropriate information concerning the environmental situation of the business financed. &nbsp;Legal Counsel will ensure that appropriate environmental covenants are incorporated into all loan contracts in excess of KSh 100,000 equivalent and to all loans in the high-risk category.&nbsp; In addition, supplemental or rider language is included for loans whose disbursement is made conditional on customer improvement with respect to environmental, health, safety, or social aspects.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436267\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592036\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591776\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377455174\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142224\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377454068\"></a>7.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Procedure for environmental scanning.</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The environmental policy is implemented according to the procedure outlined below. The following three principles are key elements of the procedure:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Applying Musoni&rsquo;s Environmental Exclusion List as an eligibility screen for all lending;</li>\r\n	<li>Ensuring that all borrowers comply with the applicable environmental, health and safety requirements of Musoni;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Directing borrowers, when appropriate, to organizations that can help them improve environmental performance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The WCO is responsible for enforcing the Environmental Policy. Prior to loan application, the WCO shall inform the client of Musoni&rsquo;s environmental exclusion list. Any potential customer who contravenes this policy shall not be financed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As part of the application and appraisal process, the WCO shall make an evaluation of the environmental and social risks associated with the business. As part of this evaluation process, the WCO assigns the borrower&rsquo;s economic activities to one of the following environmental risk categories: low risk, limited risk, medium risk or high risk. This risk categorization is based on the classification of environmental risk by main economic activity. Loans greater than KSh 100,000 and falling in limited and medium risk categories shall undergo additional environmental assessments. Additional assessment shall also apply to all loans in the high-risk category, regardless of amount.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No additional environmental assessment is carried out on loans in the low risk category, or on loans in the limited and medium categories, whose amounts are less than KSh 100,000 equivalent.&nbsp; Based on the results of the assessment, a brief environmental information memo is prepared.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During the environmental and social risk evaluation, the WCO will explain to the customer that he/she is expected to comply with the environmental, health and safety requirements of Musoni relevant to the activity being financed.&nbsp; If there appears to be an inconsistency with these requirements, the loan is either rejected or corrective action is agreed as a condition of the loan.&nbsp; If a loan is rejected due to environmental grounds or corrective action is agreed, the Environmental Coordinator must be informed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni&rsquo;s loan agreements contain a general clause stating that the customer is familiar with the environmental exclusion list of Musoni and that the customer affirms that he/she does not pursue any of the economic activities enumerated in the exclusion list. The loan agreements also contain a clause stating that the customer, to the best of their knowledge, is familiar with the applicable environmental, health and safety requirements of Musoni and that he/she assures that his/her enterprise is operated in compliance with these requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During supervision visits, the WCO observes the borrower&#39;s activities with an eye toward identifying poor environmental or social performance, opportunities for improvement, or improvements made since the last visit.&nbsp; Performance and opportunities are discussed with the borrower as appropriate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni evaluates its environmental and social performance on an annual basis.&nbsp; The institution provides an annual report on environmental and social performance and compliance to the Board of Directors and to shareholders.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436268\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592037\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591777\"></a><a name=\"_Toc440142225\"></a><a name=\"_Toc377454069\"></a>7.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Resources and capabilities</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Management and the Environmental Coordinator will ensure that sufficient internal resources have been committed to allow for the effective implementation of the policy and procedure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Management will ensure that the Environmental Coordinator and a back-up staff member participate in appropriate environmental management system training oriented towards microfinance institutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Environmental Coordinator will conduct internal staff training sessions and briefings on environmental issues and procedures as warranted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Environmental Coordinator will maintain a file of environmental organizations or qualified environmental consultants who can be called upon as needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc446436269\"></a>Appendix</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436270\"></a>Appendix 1: Group Loan Products</h2>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>Loan Type</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Loan Name</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Upfront fee</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Loan Cycle</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Amount</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Interest Rate</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Maximum loan Term</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\">Starting Group Business Loan</td>\r\n			<td rowspan=\"3\">Nawiri</td>\r\n			<td rowspan=\"3\">3%</td>\r\n			<td>1st</td>\r\n			<td>5 to 50K</td>\r\n			<td>22% p.a.</td>\r\n			<td>12 Months</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2nd</td>\r\n			<td>5 to 100K</td>\r\n			<td>21% P.a