ant &amp; Hotels</td>\r\n			<td>Tourism, Restaurant &amp; Hotels</td>\r\n			<td>Hotel, Rest house, Accommodations, Bar, Rest, Prepared Food Vendor</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.1</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Barber &amp; Beauty Salon</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.2</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Cyber Cafe/printing/photocopy</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.3</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Photo Lab, Studio, Videography, Events Planner/manager</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.5</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Clinics, Health Care</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.6</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Recycling (Scrap metal, plastic etc.)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.7</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>School, Education</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.8</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Tailoring</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>13.9</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Services</td>\r\n			<td>Repair &amp; Maintenance (Carpentry, Welding, Plumbing, Electricals etc.)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>14.1</td>\r\n			<td>Transport &amp; Communications</td>\r\n			<td>Transport &amp; Communications</td>\r\n			<td>Transport - Taxi, Boda Boda, Bus, Matatus</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc441592038\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591778\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436274\"></a>ANNEX: Flow Diagrams of Musoni Credit Procedures</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc446436275\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592040\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591780\"></a>Annex 1: Group and Client Registration (Manual Registration)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc446436276\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592041\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591781\"></a>Annex 2: Group and Client Registration (Automated Registration)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc441592042\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591782\"></a><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436277\"></a>Annex 3: Loan Application (Automated)</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436278\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592043\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591783\"></a>Annex 4: Loan Application (Manual)</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc441592044\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591784\"></a><a name=\"_Toc446436279\"></a>Annex 5: First Access Credit Scoring process</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436280\"></a>Annex 6: Collateral Refund Process</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc446436281\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592045\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591785\"></a>Annex 7: Portfolio Handover process</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436282\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441592046\"></a><a name=\"_Toc441591786\"></a>Annex 8: Agricultural Loan approval process</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436283\"></a>Annex 9: Individual Loan application &ndash; CRB Check</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436284\"></a>Annex 10: Individual Loan application &ndash; HOCC</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc446436285\"></a>Annex 10: Client Exit</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref1\" name=\"_ftn1\">[1]</a>A family of highly toxic chemical compounds consisting of two benzene rings in which chlorine takes the place of two or more hydrogen atoms: known to cause skin diseases and suspected of causing birth defects and cancer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref2\" name=\"_ftn2\">[2]</a>&nbsp;CITES (the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora) is an international agreement between governments. Its aim is to ensure that international trade in specimens of wild animals and plants does not threaten their survival.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref3\" name=\"_ftn3\">[3]</a>&nbsp;For the purpose of this Credit Policy Manual, a relative is defined as an individual having a relationship to or connection with another because of blood, marriage or commonality of interests in which a necessary dependence upon one another can be implied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref4\" name=\"_ftn4\">[4]</a>&nbsp;shall mean all information that is not known to the public regarding the business of the company relating to research and development, processes, trade secrets, customers, suppliers, finances and business plans and strategies</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref5\" name=\"_ftn5\">[5]</a>&nbsp;<em>Recommended ratio is 30 to 40% for new clients, and less than or equal to 60% for repeat clients</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref6\" name=\"_ftn6\">[6]</a>&nbsp;<em>Recommended ratio is 30 to 40% for new clients, and less than or equal to 70% for repeat clients</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=8&amp;action=edit#_ftnref7\" name=\"_ftn7\">[7]</a>&nbsp;<em>Recommended ratio is less than or equal to 80%</em></p>\r\n','','2017-03-30 06:44:30','2017-03-30 06:44:30'),(4,1,1,5,2,'Tablet usage policy','tablet-usage-policy-1490867400','<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Introduction</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy is meant to be used as a governing policy on how Musoni Kenya tablets are handled. This usage policy contains the procedure of procurement, responsibilities of the different parties involved in handling or managing of the devices and the procedures of handling the devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Procurement, custody and issuance of tablets</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Procurement of tablets&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The IT Manager &ldquo;ITM&rdquo; is responsible for the requisition of tablet procurements. The ITM specifications of the tablets to be procured and shall receive and sign off on the conformity of the procured tablets to the requisition (as outlined in the Admin manual).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to procure new tablets in the institution, a need analysis shall be carried out by the IT Manager to determine the number of tablets to be procured. The need may arise from:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>New tablets for new staff or projects</li>\r\n	<li>Replacement of non-functioning tablets due to e.g. stolen tablet, failing hardware or physical damage.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>In all of the above cases, the requisition and justification shall be presented for review by the CFO and Approval by the CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Custody of the tablets&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The IT is responsible for holding the tablets and SIM cards in custody until they are delivered to the right branch as guided by the requisition form. The Finance and Administration Officer &ldquo;FAO&rdquo; is responsible for tagging the tablets (both IMEI and serial number of the tablets) and informing the IT Assistant about the tag number so that it can be captured in the IT Asset inventory system &ldquo;the system&rdquo;.</li>\r\n	<li>The IT Assistant is responsible for updating the system regarding the tablet movements.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; 2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Issuance and handling of the tablets&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All tablets shall be issued to new owners by the ITM and the AGREEEMENT OF USAGE OF TABLET (see Annex), henceforth referred to as the agreement, shall be signed by the STAFF and the ITM. The name of the staff together with their base office shall be captured in the system. A copy of the same document shall be kept by the Branch Manager for enforcement.</li>\r\n	<li>All new employees shall be issued with a working tablet within 1 week upon reporting.</li>\r\n	<li>Change of ownership of the tablet shall nullify the agreement signed and a new one shall be signed by both the Musoni Staff and the ITM. These changes shall be updated in the inventory system by the IT Assistant.</li>\r\n	<li>Change of office by the Musoni Staff shall nullify the agreement signed and a new one shall be signed by both the Musoni Staff and the ITM. That Tablet shall be held in custody of the ITM and different one be issued to the Musoni Staff unless otherwise advised.</li>\r\n	<li>It is expected that all tablet owners should take care of the tablet and adhere to the stipulated rules defined in the AGREEEMENT OF USAGE OF TABLET (see Annex),</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Procedure of Handling Tablets</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; General Condition of the Tablet</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All tablet shall be protected by tablet cover and screen guard this shall reduce the like hood of damaging the tablet screen and body casing. It is expected that the minimum Life cycle of the tablet cover is 1 year.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any worn out tablet cover should be reported for replacement. Any case of damage to tablet without a cover shall be construed as negligence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The tablet shall not be left in the charger for an extended period of time e.g. all day or overnight, as it reduces the lifespan of the battery.</li>\r\n	<li>The ITM shall replace all batteries that are more than 2 years.</li>\r\n	<li>In case of damage to the device, the device shall be returned to the ITM for analysis and repair. If the damage is extensive, the user shall be issued with another tablet for temporal duration until their device is repaired. Repair of the device shall take a maximum of 5 working days unless communicated otherwise by the ITM.</li>\r\n	<li>The ITM shall review any mismanagement of the tablet and advice on the extent of the damage. The repair cost shall be borne by the assigned tablet user.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tablet repair is the sole responsibility of the ITM.</li>\r\n	<li>In the case where the cost of repair of the tablet is 75% the cost of purchasing a new device, due to wear and tear, or due to mismanagement, the tablet shall be marked for disposal as guided by the Asset Disposal Policy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Event of Tablet Loss</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event that a tablet is lost due to misplacement or theft, the following procedure shall be followed in reporting this occurrence:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Report the incidence to your immediate supervisor &amp; the ITM</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Supervisor shall within 24 hours circulate an incidence report on the loss to the IT Manager, CFO and COO.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The tablet owner shall require to produce the following document as evidence to the branch manager &ndash; OB number, duly certified statement from the police station where the case has been reported and signed copy of Tablet issuance form. Failure to produce this information within 24 hours then the matter shall be treated as negligence.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Event of Exiting institution</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of a user exiting the institution for any reason, the following procedure shall be followed:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The tablet shall be returned by the assigned user and handed over to the ITM who shall review the state of the tablet.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The IT Assistant shall change the metadata of the tablets on the Inventory System to reflect the new status of the tablet.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The signed tablet usage policy shall be nullified.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The branch manager shall send the report and supporting documents to the IT Manager and CFO within 48 hours to facilitate other activities such as claim from insurance, replacement and repair of the tablets were applicable.</p>\r\n','','2017-03-30 06:50:00','2017-03-30 06:50:00'),(5,1,1,6,2,'AML and KYC Policies and Procedures Manual','aml-and-kyc-policies-and-procedures-manual-1490867557','<p><strong>Version 3.00 dated 03rd&nbsp;September 2015</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prepared Due Process Consulting, David James and Reviewed by James Onyutta and Rosemary Muyeshi</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Approved by Board on 29th&nbsp;October 2015</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Amendments</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Date</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Status: In-progress/</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Complete</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Chapter/Section/</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page Number</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Description of Amendment/Reference Number</td>\r\n			<td>Manual updated by: Rose Mary Muyeshi (RM)</td>\r\n			<td>Head of Dept./ Team Leader&rsquo;s Initials</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>1.4 page 7</td>\r\n			<td>Change from COO to CFO responsible for Manual update</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 2.5</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 15</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Addition of work Kenya to money laundering act, 2009</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 2.8</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 14</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Annual Risk Assessment vs. every 2 years</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 3.1</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 17</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Enhanced definition of Beneficial Owner</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Section 3.2 Page 17</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Amendment to provide for each individual part availing KYC documents and not only one party.</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Section 3.3 Page&nbsp; 18</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Amended to allow for digital storage of KYC information.</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 3.3.2</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 18</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Incorporating Individual Lending selection criteria</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 3.4</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 19</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Addition of EU sanction Lists, Federal Republic of Germany Lists, update of IFC exclusion list and OFAC List. And Amendment to carry semi-annual reviews of prohibited businesses.</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Completed</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 3.5</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 20</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Definition and examples of a person of High Risk Persons</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Section 3.10 page 22</td>\r\n			<td>Amending transaction limit from 140,000 to 200,000 Kenya shillings, equivalent to maximum transaction for all disbursements and</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Section 3.12 page 23</td>\r\n			<td>Inclusion of Risk Manager in SATR reporting.</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Section 3.16 page 25</td>\r\n			<td>Change from Employee identification cards to restricted access in order to cater for use of Key controlled areas, password and Biometrics.</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>03/09/2015</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Section 3.16</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Page 24</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Expansion of controls on KYE designed to deter internal fraud and abuse, insertion of Semi-Annual review of Employee performance and reliability.</td>\r\n			<td>RM</td>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Table of Contents</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063767\"><strong>1 Introduction</strong>. 6</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063768\">1.1 Background. 6</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063769\">1.2 Scope. 6</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063770\">1.3 Compliance. 6</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063771\">1.4 Amendments 7</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063772\">1.5 Confidentiality. 7</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063773\">1.6 Abbreviations 7</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063774\">1.7 AML Compliance Officer 8</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063775\">1.8 Definitions 8</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063776\">1.9 Key Responsibilities 10</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063777\"><strong>2 Anti-Money Laundering</strong>. 12</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063778\">2.1 Introduction. 12</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063779\">2.2 Stages of Money Laundering. 12</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063780\">2.3 Vulnerabilities 13</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063781\">2.4 The Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009. 13</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063782\">2.5 Musoni&rsquo;s AML Obligations 14</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063783\">2.6 Money Laundering Offences 14</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063784\">2.7 The United Nations Sanctions List 15</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063785\">2.8 Risk Assessment 15</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063786\">2.9 New Innovations/Technology. 16</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063787\">2.10 Training and Accreditation. 16</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063788\">2.11 Reporting. 16</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063789\">2.12 Confidentiality of Information. 16</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063790\"><strong>3 Know Your Customer [KYC]</strong>&nbsp;17</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063791\">3.1 When Identity Must be Verified. 17</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063792\">3.2 Customer Due Diligence. 17</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063793\">3.3&nbsp; Lending Methodology. 18</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063794\">3.3.1 Introduction. 18</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063795\">3.3.2 Client Criteria. 18</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063796\">3.3.3 KYC Documentation. 19</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063797\">3.4 Prohibited Business 19</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063798\">3.5 Enhanced Customer Due Diligence. 20</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063799\">3.6 Telephone, Mobile and Internet Banking. 20</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063800\">3.7 Anonymous Accounts and Numbered Accounts 21</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063801\">3.8 Legitimacy of Funds and Transactions 21</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063802\">3.9 Publicly Exposed Persons [PEPs] 21</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063803\">3.10 On-going Monitoring of Transactions 22</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063804\">3.11&nbsp;&nbsp; Identifying Suspicious Transactions 22</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063805\">3.12 Reporting Suspicious Activities or Transactions 23</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063806\">3.13 Termination of Business Relationship Following Disclosure. 23</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063807\">3.14 Cash Transaction Report 23</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063808\">3.15 Record Keeping. 23</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063809\">3.16 Know Your Employee [KYE] Requirements 24</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063810\"><strong>APPENDIX</strong>. 26</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063811\">Examples of Suspicious Transactions 26</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063812\">Internal Suspicious Activity or Transactions Report [SATR] 28</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063813\">Suspicious Transaction Report 29</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063814\">Quarterly Review Of Al-Qaida Sanctions List 31</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063815\">Cash Transaction Report 32</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit#_Toc429063816\">IFC Exclusion List 33</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc429063767\"></a><strong>1 Introduction</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063768\"></a>1.1 Background</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In response to various worldwide terrorist and other criminal activities, the international community through bodies such as the Financial Action Task Force [FATF] has sought to ensure that the global financial network is not used to facilitate criminal activity. In this regard, the FATF has issued a number of recommendations that are now widely recognized as standards for combating money laundering and financing of terrorism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The FATF has 5 FATF-style regional bodies [FSRB] and more than 15 other international organizations or bodies. Kenya is a member of one of the FSRB i.e. Eastern and Southern Africa Anti-Money Laundering Group [ESAAMLG]. Kenya also happens to be a signatory to the major international protocols relating to anti-money laundering [AML], corruption, trans-national crime and combating terrorism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Kenya, the Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009 is the key legislation on AML and KYC matters. The Central Bank of Kenya also issues various guidelines and regulatory requirements that all financial services organizations in Kenya should comply with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni, being a responsible player in the Kenya financial services sector, strives to comply with all laws and regulatory guidelines and adhere to sound financial service practices, both locally and internationally. It must also be noted that failure to comply with any of the laws or regulations relating to money laundering and KYC by any of our staff constitutes a criminal offence, whether or not money laundering has taken place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition to penalties for breaches, any involvement in money laundering activities would cause severe damage to our Company&rsquo;s reputation and substantially jeopardize the future of our business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063769\"></a>1.2 Scope</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual contains policies and procedures for prudent customer identification, record keeping, identification of suspicious activities and the process for reporting such activities both internally and externally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These policies and procedures apply to all functions, departments, branches and employees of Musoni as well as to all transactions entered into by Musoni with any customer, regardless of whether that person is an account holder at Musoni or not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063770\"></a>1.3 Compliance</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual explains policies and procedures relating to AML and KYC matters that all Musoni employees must comply with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where the policies/procedures explained in this document are found to be in conflict or inconsistent with any other previously written internal policies/procedures, the content of this manual will prevail to the extent of the inconsistency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While this manual assigns responsibilities to various roles e.g. Wealth Creation Officer and AML Compliance Officer, such responsibilities can also be undertaken by any official legitimately holding such a role in an acting capacity. The responsibilities may also be performed by any official specifically designated by the CEO/COO to perform such duties at any one time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the responsibility of the respective Branch Managers and Heads of Departments in Head Office to ensure that these policies and procedures are fully complied with in their respective areas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Should you encounter any challenges in complying with a requirement contained in this manual, please refer to your up-line manager who should in turn refer the matter to the CFO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Any dispensation to deviate from laid down policies and procedures must be authorized by the CFO in writing.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>The manual does not replace the need for each employee to use his/her own judgment/intuition guided by all relevant Musoni policies and procedures [written or otherwise], towards the prevention of money laundering.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063771\"></a>1.4 Amendments</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any amendments necessary to these policies and procedures should be communicated by the CFO in writing and must be read and acted upon by all concerned officials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The manual should be reviewed in its entirety and updated at least once every two years and a new version issued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any recommendations for amendments or changes to be made to the manual should be sent to the CFO in writing detailing the required changes/amendments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CFO is responsible for ensuring the manual remains up-to-date at all times.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063772\"></a>1.5 Confidentiality</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual is confidential and is only to be used by Musoni staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Neither the manual, nor any parts of it are to be copied or distributed to anyone outside of Musoni without permission from the CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063773\"></a>1.6 Abbreviations</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following abbreviations have been used in this manual with the meaning explained below under each abbreviation:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Abbreviation</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Meaning</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>AML</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Anti-Money Laundering</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Branch Manager</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>CBK</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Central Bank of Kenya</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>CEO</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Chief Executive Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>CFO</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Chief Financial Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>COO</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Chief Operating Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>DEO</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Data Entry Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>FATF</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Financial Action Task Force</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>FSRB</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>FATF-style Regional Bodies</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Abbreviation</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Meaning</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>KYC</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Know Your Customer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>SATR</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Suspicious Activity or Transaction Report</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>UN</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>United Nations</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>WCO</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Wealth Creation Officer</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063774\"></a>1.7 AML Compliance Officer</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chief Financial Officer [CFO] has been designated by management to play the role of AML Compliance Officer as explained in this manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063775\"></a>1.8 Definitions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Money Laundering</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The act of a person who:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Engages directly or indirectly, in a transaction that involves proceeds of any unlawful activity; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Acquires, receives, possesses, disguises, transfers, converts, exchanges, carries, disposes, uses, removes from or brings into Kenya proceeds of any unlawful activity; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Conceals, disguises or impedes the establishment of the true nature, origin, location, movement, deposition, title of, rights with respect to, or ownership of, proceeds of any unlawful activity where:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>as may be inferred from objective factual circumstances, the person knows or has reason to believe, that the property is proceeds from any unlawful activity; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>In respect of the conduct of a natural person, the person without reasonable excuse fails to take reasonable steps to ascertain whether or not the property is proceeds from any unlawful activity.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Money Laundering Predicate Offence</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the underlying criminal activity that generates proceeds, which when laundered, results in the offense of money laundering.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples of predicate offences include human trafficking, robbery, fraud, corruption, bribery, insider trading and counterfeiting of goods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Proceeds of Crime</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any property or economic advantage derived or realized, directly or indirectly, as a result of or in connection with an offence, irrespective of the identity of the offender and includes, on a proportional basis, property into which any property derived or realized directly from the offence was later successively converted, transformed or intermingled, as well as income, capital or other economic gains derived or realized from such property from the time the offence was committed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Person</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any natural or legal entity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Customer</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the purposes of this manual, a customer is any person or entity:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who maintains an account; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establishes a business relationship; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On whose behalf an account is maintained; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who benefits from accounts maintained by intermediaries such as stockbrokers, accountants and lawyers; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who carries potential risk through a one-off transaction; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who is otherwise connected with a financial transaction.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Business Relationship</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any arrangement between Musoni and a customer, the purpose of which is to facilitate the carrying out of transactions between the parties on a frequent, habitual or regular basis and where the monetary value of dealings in the course of the arrangement is not known or capable of being ascertained at the outset. Opening of an account for a customer in Musoni therefore entails forming a &lsquo;business relationship&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>One-off Transaction</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any transaction carried out other than in the course of a business relationship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, a single money transfer transaction for a customer who does not have an account with Musoni constitutes a one-off transaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Suspicious Transaction</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A transaction, whether or not made in cash, which to a person acting in good faith:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Gives rise to reasonable ground of suspicion that it may involve the proceeds of crime; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Appears to be made under circumstances of unusual or unjustified complexity; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Appears to have no economic rationale or bonafide purpose.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Know Your Customer</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Obtaining full particulars of the customer&rsquo;s identity [which may need to be verified in certain circumstances] and a sound knowledge of the purpose for which the customer is seeking to establish a business relationship with Musoni. This knowledge needs to be applied to all dealings initiated by the customer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The extent to which such dealings appear not to &lsquo;fit&rsquo; this knowledge base should form the basis of our suspicion about the customer, which should then be reported to the CBK through the AML Compliance Officer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other terms used within this manual are as defined in the Banking Act.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063776\"></a>1.9 Key Responsibilities</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Person[s]</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Key Responsibilities</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Management Team</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Establish and implement appropriate policies and procedures to guard against money laundering and terrorism financing.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Establish adequate internal control measures, which will assist in the prevention and detection of money laundering activities.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Appoint an AML Compliance Officer with the necessary authority to carry out the functions of the role.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide the AML Compliance Officer with the necessary access to systems and records to enable the Officer fulfill his responsibilities.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide for adequate screening policies and procedures to ensure high ethical and professional standards when hiring staff.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that all employees are trained on a regular basis in the prevention, detection and control of money laundering and the identification of suspicious transactions.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure timely reporting to the CBK of any suspicious transactions or activities that may indicate money laundering or other attempts to conceal the true identity of customers or ownership of assets.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cooperate with national law enforcement agencies by taking appropriate measures which are consistent with the law, where there are reasonable grounds for suspecting money laundering.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Arrange for independent testing/audit, to measure compliance with the relevant AML laws and regulations.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>AML Compliance Officer</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Advice management on appropriate AML policies.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coordinate the development, implementation and review of AML policies and procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Promote compliance to AML policies throughout the Company.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coordinate the development and delivery of appropriate AML training to all Musoni employees.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Act as Musoni&rsquo;s central point of contact with CBK for anti-money laundering purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Receive and vet reports of suspicious transactions from Musoni staff and in turn make the necessary reports and returns to CBK.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Periodically circulate to all staff a list of persons appearing on the UN and other relevant sanctions lists.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide effective linkage between Musoni and external AML authorities/agencies.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Take necessary action to ensure that thorough investigations are conducted internally into any reported suspicious activities/transactions.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>10. Participate in relevant AML events.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Person[s]</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Key Responsibilities</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>All Musoni Employees</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Undergo periodic training and keep abreast of the latest AML measures.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adhere to the policies and procedures explained in this manual and other relevant Musoni Manuals.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Immediately report to the AML Compliance Officer, any transactions suspected to be related to drugs, terrorism and other forms of crime or the detection of a person appearing on the UN Sanctions List.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Not to in any way reveal to anyone that a customer is being investigated or that they are principal suspects in any such investigation, but to immediately forward any such information to the AML Compliance Officer.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Obtain and retain certified copies of proper identification documents of customers wishing to open accounts or make any other transactions with Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Establish whether any person wishing to open an account or make any other transaction with Musoni is acting on behalf of another person and take necessary measures to establish the true identity of the proxy or the ultimate beneficiaries of such transactions, be they trustees, nominees or agents.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In accordance with Musoni&#39;s operating procedures, obtain adequate records regarding the sources of funds and details of transactions and maintain such records for a minimum of seven&nbsp; [7] years.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Not to open or maintain any anonymous account or an account in an obviously fictitious name.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The responsibility of detecting, preventing and reporting money-laundering activities rests squarely on each individual member of staff.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc429063777\"></a><strong>2 Anti-Money Laundering</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063778\"></a>2.1 Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Money Laundering is the process through which criminals attempt to conceal the illegal origin and illegitimate ownership of the property and assets that are the fruits or proceeds of their criminal activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If undertaken successfully, it also allows the criminals to impliedly represent the proceeds of their crime as having originated from legitimate sources, thereby allowing them to maintain control over those proceeds and to dispose of them without hindrance, which ultimately is the goal of crime committed for profit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Money laundering is a global phenomenon that affects all countries to varying degrees. By its very nature, it is a hidden activity. However, failure to prevent the laundering of the proceeds of crime permits criminals to benefit from their actions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063779\"></a>2.2 Stages of Money Laundering</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the variety of methods employed, the laundering process is accomplished in three stages. These stages, described below, may comprise numerous transactions by the launderers that could alert an institution of the criminal activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Stage</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Description</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Placement</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>This refers to the physical disposal of the initial proceeds of an illegal activity into a financial system. This may happen in one of several ways such as:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Direct deposit in a financial institution. This could take the form of a single deposit or several small deposits into one or several accounts, made by one or more individuals.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Purchase of goods/services.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Smuggling the funds out of the country.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Use of cash to purchase banking instruments such as drafts, traveler&rsquo;s cheques, international money orders, foreign currency etc.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Layering</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>During this stage, criminals seek to separate the illicit proceeds from their source by creating complex layers of financial transactions aimed at disguising the origin of the funds and the identity of the true owner while concealing the audit trail.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Layering can be achieved through several means including:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Purchase of valuables such as jewelry, real estate etc.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Early repayment of debt obligations inconsistent with the person&rsquo;s genuine regular income.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Buying and selling of bonds, shares and other money market instruments.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Dealing in banking instruments such as drafts, traveler&rsquo;s cheques, international money orders, and foreign currency.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Stage</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Description</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Integration</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>If the layering process succeeds, the criminals then craft an integration scheme whereby the laundered proceeds are placed back into the economy.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This is done in such a way that the proceeds re-enter the financial system appearing as legitimate business funds. The criminals are then able to withdraw or otherwise transact with the money without attracting suspicion.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Integration can be achieved in various ways such as:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Making withdrawals from bank accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Disposal of items initially purchased through the illicit money.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Repayment of debt obligations such as mortgages etc.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The three basic steps may occur as separate and distinct phases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alternatively, they may occur simultaneously or, more commonly, they may overlap. How the basic steps are used depends on the requirements of the criminal organizations and the available mechanisms and loopholes in the financial system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It must be noted that criminals are constantly coming up with new and sophisticated ways of laundering their ill-gotten gains. This therefore calls for constant alertness and due diligence on the part of all Musoni employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063780\"></a>2.3 Vulnerabilities</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Certain points of vulnerability have been identified in the laundering process, which the money launderer finds difficult to avoid and where his activities are more susceptible to being recognized. Specifically these are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Entry of cash into the financial system;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cross-border flows of cash; and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Transfers within and from the financial system.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063781\"></a>2.4 The Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009 came into effect on June 28, 2010. The Act:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Criminalizes money laundering;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Provides for both criminal and civil restraint, seizures and forfeiture;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Places an obligation on financial institutions to:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Monitor and report suspected money laundering activity;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verify customer identity [KYC];</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establish and maintain internal reporting procedures.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establishes the Financial Reporting Centre [Financial Intelligence Unit], the Asset Recovery Centre and the Criminal Assets Recovery Fund.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Provides for procedures that facilitate international assistance with investigations and proceedings related to money laundering offences.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063782\"></a>2.5 Musoni&rsquo;s AML Obligations</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni as an institution is obligated by sections 44, 45, 46 and 47 of the Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009 of Kenya to:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Monitor and report suspected money laundering activity;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verify customer identity;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establish and maintain customer records; and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establish and maintain reporting procedures.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Act accords immunity or protection to institutions and officers in respect of obligations done under the Act in good faith, such as reporting of suspicious transactions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063783\"></a>2.6 Money Laundering Offences</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009 makes it an offence for any person to enter into an agreement or engage in any arrangement or transaction with anyone in connection with property that forms part of the proceeds of crime, whether that agreement, arrangement or transaction is legally enforceable or not and whose effect is to:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Conceal or disguise the nature, source, location, disposition, movement or ownership of the said property; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Enable or assist any person who has committed or commits an offence, whether in Kenya or elsewhere to avoid prosecution; or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Remove or diminish any property acquired directly or indirectly, as a result of the commission of an offence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Acquisition</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Acquisition, use and possession of proceeds of crime knowing that such property forms part of the proceeds is an offence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tipping-off</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is also an offence for anyone who knows or suspects that an investigation into money laundering has been, is being, or is about to be conducted to inform someone else of that fact, thereby prejudicing the investigation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These offences are punishable by law as set out in the Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009. Internal disciplinary measures within Musoni also apply to employees who contravene the policies and procedures explained in this manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employees must immediately report their suspicions to the AML Compliance Officer as outlined in&nbsp;<strong>Section 3.12</strong>&nbsp;of this manual. It is a defense that the employee has reported his/her knowledge or suspicion.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063784\"></a>2.7 The United Nations Sanctions List</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The United Nations [UN] was the first international organization to undertake significant action to fight money laundering on a global basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UN has the ability to adopt international treaties or conventions that have the effect of law in a country once that country has signed, ratified and implemented the convention, depending upon the country&rsquo;s constitution and legal structure. In certain cases, the UN Security Council has the authority to bind all member countries through a Security Council Resolution, regardless of other action on the part of an individual country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UN Security Council Sanction Committee designates and periodically issues lists of individuals or entities suspected to be linked to terrorism. The cornerstone of the regime is a consolidated list of persons maintained by the Security Council. All nations are obliged to freeze bank accounts and other financial instruments controlled by, or used for the benefit of anyone on the list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please find the current list at:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.un.org/sc/committees/1267/aq_sanctions_list.shtml\">http://www.un.org/sc/committees/1267/aq_sanctions_list.shtml</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer must on a quarterly basis circulate the most up-to-date sanctions list to all Musoni staff, who must evidence having read the list by signing the accompanying schedule. Each member of staff must be on the lookout for persons included in the list and must immediately report to the AML Compliance Officer by telephone/in-person any attempts by any such listed person to transact with Musoni in any way, followed by written confirmation on e-mail.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer must submit the&nbsp;<strong>1267 Return CBK/IF 9</strong>&nbsp;<strong>[see Appendix 4]</strong>&nbsp;on a quarterly basis to CBK in the prescribed format.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063785\"></a>2.8 Risk Assessment</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni shall undertake a Money Laundering and Financing of Terrorism Risk Assessment&nbsp;<strong>every year</strong>&nbsp;in order to take into account changes such as entry into new markets and introduction of new products and services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Assessment shall provide the means for identifying the degree of potential money laundering and financing of terrorism risks associated with specific customers and transactions, thereby allowing Musoni to focus on customers and transactions that potentially pose a great risk of money laundering and terrorism financing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The risk assessment shall take into consideration the findings of the country&#39;s National Money Laundering and Terrorism Risk Assessment and consider factors such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The number and volume of transactions per customer;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nature of the customer relationships and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Whether, for example, Musoni&rsquo;s interaction with customers is face-to-face or non-face-to-face such as electronic banking [for example, internet banking and mobile banking] etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063786\"></a>2.9 New Innovations/Technology</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni shall conduct a money laundering and terrorist financing risk assessment so as to assess money laundering and terrorist financing risks in relation to:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>New products and new business practices, including new delivery mechanisms and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>New or developing technologies for both new and pre-existing products.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A money laundering and terrorist financing risk assessment shall be conducted prior to the introduction of a new product, new business practice or new technology for both new and pre-existing products.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063787\"></a>2.10 Training and Accreditation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every Musoni member of staff must undergo training on anti-money laundering measures. The training must be refreshed at least&nbsp;<strong>once every year</strong>&nbsp;with staff being accredited after passing a compulsory test on AML measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer is charged with the responsibility of organizing the training/accreditation and keeping proper records evidencing this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063788\"></a>2.11 Reporting</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Branch Managers must monitor customer&rsquo;s accounts and transactions on an ongoing basis and promptly report all AML and KYC related issues to the AML Compliance Officer in writing as and when they are detected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer must on a&nbsp;<strong>quarterly basis</strong>&nbsp;submit summary reports regarding suspicious transactions, KYC issues and staff training and accreditation on anti-money laundering to the Board Risk Management Committee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer must also report suspicious transactions to CBK as explained under&nbsp;<strong>Section 3.12</strong>&nbsp;of this manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063789\"></a>2.12 Confidentiality of Information</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All information relating to any suspicious activities or transactions must be treated with strict confidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Members of staff who become aware of such activities or transactions must not disclose such information, other than to report the matter to the AML Compliance Officer, who will take any necessary further action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc429063790\"></a><strong>3 Know Your Customer [KYC]</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063791\"></a>3.1 When Identity Must be Verified</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In all transactions, Musoni employees must always satisfy themselves that they are dealing with a person that actually exists and identify those persons that are authorized to undertake the transactions whether on their own behalf or on behalf of others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where a person has requested to enter into any transaction with Musoni on behalf of another person, staff must take necessary measures to establish the true identity of the person on whose behalf or for whose benefit the applicant may be acting in the proposed transaction, whether as a trustee, nominee, agent or otherwise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The staff must also identify the beneficial owner of the transaction, a beneficial owner refers to the natural person(s) who ultimately owns or controls a customer and/or the natural person on whose behalf a transaction is being conducted. It also includes those persons who exercise ultimate effective control over a legal person or arrangement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In dealing with incorporated entities a risk based approach shall be taken to identify and verify any individual who owns or controls, whether through direct or indirect ownership or control, more than 15% of the shares or voting rights in the body or who otherwise exercises control over the management of the body.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimate effective control in this case shall refer to situations in which ownership/control is exercised through a chain of ownership or by means of control other than direct control.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff must obtain and verify the genuineness of suitable identity documents (See section 3.15) whenever:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Any person seeks to open an account with Musoni.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Any person seeks to undertake an occasional or one-off transaction with Musoni.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>There is cause to be suspicious.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>There is doubt about the veracity or adequacy of previously obtained customer identification information.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063792\"></a>3.2 Customer Due Diligence</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All Musoni staff must take measures to satisfy themselves as to the true identity of any applicant seeking to enter into a business relationship or to carry out a transaction or series of transactions with Musoni by requiring the applicant to produce an official record for the purposes of establishing the true identity of the applicant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Individual Customers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individual customers must produce a valid national identity card [police abstracts must not be accepted].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additional measures that may be used to verify the identity of the customer include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Address of current residence verified by a referee, utility bill i.e. electricity or water bill etc. or by a visit by the WCO for all clients about to take a Loan.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verified employment and/or source[s] of income.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Minors [Persons Below 18 Years of Age]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The nationality and date of birth must be evidenced by a valid birth certificate of the minor, at a minimum, plus valid national identity card of legal parent or guardian [police abstracts must not be accepted].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additional measures that may be used to verify the identity of the customer include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verified address of current residence of minor and also of legal parent or guardian. The verification should be done by a referee or via the production of utility bills i.e. electricity and water bills etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Declaration of source of funds or income from the parent/guardian.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>For accounts with more than one party each individual party shall provide relevant identification documents.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>In all cases, certified copies of the identification document[s] relied upon must be taken by the concerned WCO and retained in Musoni&rsquo;s records.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063793\"></a>3.3 &nbsp;Lending Methodology</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc429063794\"></a>3.3.1 Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Lending methodology involves visiting of clients&#39; homes and businesses by fellow group members and Musoni staff with appropriate Site Visit Reports generated and maintained as part of Musoni&#39;s KYC documentation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For a detailed explanation of Musoni&#39;s group formation and client vetting process, please refer to the Lending and Credit Manual.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc429063795\"></a>3.3.2 Client Criteria</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All clients wishing to join a Musoni Group or borrow a loan as an individual must:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be at least 18 years of age;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Have a National Identification Card;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Have a good reputation in their community where they work and reside;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be a Kenyan Citizen;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Own an on-going business in Kenya for at least six months for Group lending and 2 years for individual lending;</li>\r\n	<li>The applicant must have a business license and permits as required by the respective Government authorities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be registered at Safaricom&rsquo;s M-PESA [in due course other mobile payment networks will be added];</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Not have any relatives in the same Musoni Credit Group;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Not be related to any Musoni staff;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Not appear in the Musoni blacklist;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>For individual loans the applicant must provide bank statements for previous six months if the savings account at the time of loan application is maintained with a bank and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Not engage in any prohibited business activity.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc429063796\"></a>3.3.3 KYC Documentation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During the client registration process, WCOs must collect and verify copies of client identification documents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only identification document acceptable to Musoni is an official national identification card [police abstracts must not be accepted].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BM must confirm presence of the KYC document and that the WCO has signed off on its accuracy. Copies of the clients KYC documents must be stored digitally or in hard copy in the client section of the group/client file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For a detailed explanation of Musoni&#39;s group formation and client vetting process, please refer to the Lending and Credit Manual.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063797\"></a>3.4 Prohibited Business</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni does not finance projects or deal with persons or organizations listed in the:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>UN Sanctions List &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>Please refer to&nbsp;<strong>Section 2.7</strong>&nbsp;for further details.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>EU Sanctions List - http://eeas.europa.eu/cfsp/sanctions/consol-list/index_en.htm</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Sanction list of the Federal Republic of Germany -</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>IFC Exclusion List [See Appendix 6]</strong>&nbsp;- IFC refers to the International Finance Corporation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please refer to IFC&#39;s Website for the most current Exclusion List:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>http://www.ifc.org/wps/wcm/connect/corp_ext_content/ifc_external_corporate_site/ifc+projects+database/projects/aips+added+value/ifc_project_exclusion_list</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>&ldquo;OFAC List&rdquo;</strong>&nbsp;- means Specially Designated Nationals [SDN] List, published by Office of Foreign Assets Control [&ldquo;OFAC&rdquo;], an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury, which lists individuals and organizations with whom United States citizens and permanent residents are prohibited from doing business.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>OFAC List:&nbsp;</strong><a href=\"http://sdnsearch.ofac.treas.gov/\"><strong>http://sdnsearch.ofac.treas.gov/</strong></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please refer US Department of Treasury&rsquo;s Website for a copy of the current list:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.treasury.gov/ofac/downloads/t11sdn.pdf\"><strong>http://www.treasury.gov/ofac/downloads/t11sdn.pdf</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>&ldquo;OPIC Environmental Handbook&rdquo;</strong>&nbsp;- the OPIC Environmental Handbook. &ldquo;OPIC&rdquo; means Overseas Private Investment Corporation, an agency of the United States Government.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please refer to OPIC&#39;s Website for a copy of the current handbook:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.opic.gov/sites/default/files/docs/opic_env_handbook.pdf\"><strong>http://www.opic.gov/sites/default/files/docs/opic_env_handbook.pdf</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya will carry out semi-annual reviews of the prohibited businesses or clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063798\"></a>3.5 Enhanced Customer Due Diligence</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enhanced due diligence measures shall be applied to persons that are deemed to present a higher risk to Musoni. Through its annual risk Assessment Musoni Kenya shall identify and communicate persons deemed to be high risk, therefore requiring enhanced due diligence. Examples of customers who will be classified as high risk may include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Customers listed in the Credit Reference Bureau reports</li>\r\n	<li>Customers who have financial obligations with multiple institutions</li>\r\n	<li>Non-resident Kenyan Nationals</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This shall broadly be addressed with the following measures:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Obtaining further information to establish the customer&#39;s identity.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verifying documents with their originators.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Applying extra measures to check documents supplied by a credit or financial</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Visiting client&#39;s business premises and/or home as appropriate to independently verify information provided by the client.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Obtaining senior management approval for the new business relationship or transaction.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Establishing the person&rsquo;s source of funds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Carrying out ongoing monitoring of the business relationship.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063799\"></a>3.6 Telephone, Mobile and Internet Banking</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rapid growth in telephone, mobile and internet banking has added new risks to financial institutions including the verification of identity, unlicensed deposit taking and tax evasion and opens up new mechanisms for fraud and money laundering because its use is unregulated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any mechanism which avoids face-to-face contact between Musoni and the customer inevitably poses challenges for customer identification and can provide additional opportunities for criminals to gain access to our systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>As a matter of policy, Musoni does not open any accounts without face-to-face contact with the customer.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063800\"></a>3.7 Anonymous Accounts and Numbered Accounts</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni does not open and/or maintain anonymous accounts or accounts in fictitious names.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All numbered accounts shall undergo the same identification and verification process as regular accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063801\"></a>3.8 Legitimacy of Funds and Transactions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following types of information are the minimum acceptable for determining the legitimacy of funds and transactions:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td><strong>Activity/Transaction</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Minimum Acceptable Supporting Information</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1.</td>\r\n			<td>Large, Frequent or Unusual Cash Deposits or Withdrawals</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Written statement from the customer confirming that the nature of his/her business activities normally and reasonably generate substantial amounts of cash.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2.</td>\r\n			<td>Large, Frequent or Unusual Transfers or Payments of Funds</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Appropriate documentation as to the identity of the recipient [or sender] of the transferred or paid funds, and the reason underlying the transfer or payment.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3.</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Large or Unusual Investments or Requests for Advice or Services</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Written statement from the customer confirming that the investments or advice or services being requested are bona fide and consistent with the goals and objectives of the customer&#39;s reasonable and normal business activities.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB: Musoni does not handle cash transactions of any kind with its customers.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063802\"></a>3.9 Publicly Exposed Persons [PEPs]</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Publicly Exposed Person means a person who has been entrusted with a prominent public function in a country/jurisdiction other than Kenya including:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Members of the cabinet;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Senior executives of state owned corporations;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Important political party officials;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Senior military officials and other members of the disciplined forces;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Members of the Judiciary;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Senior state officers,</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Senior public officers and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any immediate family member or close business associate of a person referred to under the categories listed above.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>As a matter of policy, Musoni does not open accounts for or transact any business with non-Kenya residents.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063803\"></a>3.10 On-going Monitoring of Transactions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On-going monitoring of account activity and transactions shall be conducted on a risk-sensitive basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni can only effectively control and reduce its risk by having an understanding of normal and reasonable activity of its customers. This will provide us with the means of identifying transactions which fall outside the regular pattern of an account&rsquo;s activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this regard, all transactions for an individual customer exceeding&nbsp;<strong>KES 200,000.00</strong>&nbsp;within&nbsp;<strong>3 consecutive days</strong>&nbsp;must be reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Branch Manager must interview the customer and obtain documentary evidence of the source of funds. He/she must then forward a large transaction report to the AML Compliance Officer via e-mail, attaching all relevant documents relating to the transaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer should evaluate all reported transactions from a KYC and AML perspective and determine whether further investigation and/or escalation is required. Where appropriate, the AML Compliance Officer should escalate large transaction reports to the COO and CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063804\"></a>3.11&nbsp;&nbsp; Identifying Suspicious Transactions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To determine whether a transaction is suspicious or not, it is necessary to have a clear understanding of the pattern of the concerned customer&rsquo;s nature of business/occupation and their prior account conduct.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suspicious transactions may arise at any stage and frequently occur within an established business relationship rather than at the outset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is a list of some key questions that each member of staff should always consider whenever handling customers and their transactions:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Is there anything unusual about the customer&rsquo;s behaviour or mannerisms?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Has the customer shown any reluctance or difficulty in providing information or details?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Has the pattern of the customer&rsquo;s transactions recently changed?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Is the size and nature of the transaction consistent with the client&rsquo;s source of income and prior account conduct?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Are any of the customer&rsquo;s transactions linked to high-risk regions of the World?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Are any foreign currency transactions consistent with the customer&rsquo;s occupation, business dealings etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please refer to Appendix 1 for examples of suspicious activities to watch out for.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063805\"></a>3.12 Reporting Suspicious Activities or Transactions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any member of staff who becomes aware of suspicious activities or transactions, which indicate possible money laundering activities, must immediately report the matter to the AML Compliance Officer and to the Branch manager who will refer to a member of the Management Team through the telephone and email.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After reporting the matter through telephone, the concerned staff must complete an internal&nbsp;<strong>Suspicious Activity or Transaction Report [SATR] &ndash; [see Appendix 2]</strong>&nbsp;and have the report signed off by the Branch/Department Manager. The Branch/Department Manager must ensure that a scanned copy of the SATR is e-mailed to the AML Compliance Officer and the original forwarded through internal mail.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer, in consultation with the CEO and Risk Manager, must in turn immediately report the matter to the Director &ndash; Financial Institutions Supervision, CBK on form&nbsp;<strong>CBK/IF 8</strong>&nbsp;<strong>[see Appendix 3]</strong>&nbsp;providing sufficient details regarding the activities or transactions to enable CBK investigate and take appropriate action. The report must be submitted&nbsp;<strong>within seven days</strong>&nbsp;of the date of the transaction or activity that is considered suspicious.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sufficient information should be disclosed indicating the nature of and reason for the suspicion. Where additional supporting documentation is available, it should be forwarded to CBK with the report.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NB:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Failure to report suspicious transactions may lead to remedial action by CBK and/or prosecution of the concerned individuals under the Proceeds of Crime and Anti-Money Laundering Act, 2009.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>All records relating to a suspicious transaction must be securely retained for a minimum of 7 years or as advised by CBK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063806\"></a>3.13 Termination of Business Relationship Following Disclosure</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If, following a disclosure, Musoni, in exercise of its commercial judgment wishes to terminate the relationship with the customer; CBK must be consulted to ensure that the termination does not in any way &lsquo;tip-off&rsquo; the customer or prejudice possible investigation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063807\"></a>3.14 Cash Transaction Report</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AML Compliance Officer must file reports with CBK on all cash transactions exceeding&nbsp;<strong>USD 10,000</strong>&nbsp;or its equivalent in any other currency carried out with any Musoni Customer, whether or not the transaction appears to be suspicious.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report shall be made electronically on&nbsp;<strong>form IF/10 [see Appendix 5].</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063808\"></a>3.15 Record Keeping</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each customer account in Musoni must be kept in the true name of the account holder as per the national ID.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are required under the law to obtain and maintain adequate records such as; copies or records of official identification documents; statements of accounts, account files and business correspondence including the results of any inquiries to establish the background and purpose of any complex, unusual large transactions, for a minimum of&nbsp;<strong>seven [7] years</strong>, regarding the sources of funds and details of transactions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Such records are vital for:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Enabling the identification of unusual or suspicious transactions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Helping to reconstruct individual transactions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The customer records retained and maintained by Musoni must contain particulars sufficient to identify:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The name, physical and postal address and occupation or where appropriate business or principal activities of each customer who is:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Conducting the transaction or</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On whose behalf the transaction is being conducted;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The nature, time and date of transaction;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The type and amount of currency involved;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The type and identification of every account with Musoni;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If the transaction involves a negotiable instrument other than currency;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The name of the institution on which it is drawn;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The name of the payee [if any] of the instrument and details of any endorsements approving the instrument.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The name of the employee or agent of Musoni who prepared the record.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063809\"></a>3.16 Know Your Employee [KYE] Requirements</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni, being a responsible employer has instituted specific &lsquo;know your employee&rsquo; controls designed to deter internal fraud and abuse of the institution, which require all employees to:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Follow a code of ethics and not get involved in doubtful transactions;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Employee reporting evidence referring to money laundering;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Avoid and disclose conflicts of interest;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Maintain good credit ratings and avoid situations where contractual parties have to subject the employee to alternative courses of redress to make good their committed obligations;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Avoid taking company documents home without proper authorization;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Adhere to policies on rotation of duties and mandatory vacations;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Observe restricted access rules to secure areas and</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To immediately report on suspicious transactions to the compliance officer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As part of the KYE requirements Musoni Kenya carries out a detailed due diligence prior to recruitment of employees and conducts Semi-Annual appraisals to assess employee/staff performance and reliability. This is carried out using standard performance Appraisal forms and includes Key Performance Indicators, Behavioral Ratings &amp; People management skills ratings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However in event that an employee is in gross violation of Musoni Kenya rules and regulations then such actions shall not await for an appraisal process but are handled through a disciplinary process leading to instant dismissal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please refer to the Human Resource Development Manual for further details on Musoni&rsquo;s &lsquo;know your employee&rsquo; policies and procedures.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc429063810\"></a><strong>APPENDIX</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063811\"></a>Examples of Suspicious Transactions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The table below contains a list of activities or transactions that may indicate possible money laundering activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The list is however not exhaustive and does not in any way replace the need for each member of staff to always remain vigilant and exercise sound judgment in all situations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Activity/Transaction</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Account activity [e.g. large, frequent or unusual deposits, withdrawals, payments or exchanges of cash, foreign currency or negotiable instruments], which is not consistent with or reasonably related to the customer&rsquo;s normal business activities or financial standing.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use of multiple or nominee accounts or similar related transactions, which are not consistent with the customer&rsquo;s normal business activities, financial standing or indicated reasons thereof.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Consolidation of multiple smaller accounts at several institutions within the same locality prior to request for onward transmission of funds elsewhere.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reluctance to provide reasonable information and documentation when opening an account or in connection with a requested transaction, investment, advice or service or the providing of information which is unreasonably difficult or expensive to verify.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Transactions or account activity, including transfers of funds abroad or use of foreign travel and trade-related instruments, where the use or involvement of funds is not consistent with the customer&rsquo;s normal business activities, financial standing or indicated reasons thereof or where the destination country is a known or suspected tax haven or drug trafficking country.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Requests by a customer to provide/arrange/participate in credit facilities where the source of the customer&rsquo;s contribution is unclear or not consistent with normal business activities or financial standing or involves real property.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Matching of cash deposits/withdrawals with payments or transfers out/in.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Deposits of large third party cheques endorsed in favour of the customer.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Large or unusual activity in dormant/inactive accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>10. Deposit of cash by means of numbered credit slips so that the total of each deposit is unremarkable but the total of all the credits is large.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>11. Customers who open numerous accounts and pay in amounts of cash to each of them in circumstances under which the total credit would be a large amount.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>12. Company accounts whose transactions, both deposits and withdrawals are dominated by cash rather than the forms of transactions normally associated with commercial operations [e.g. cheques, letters of credit, bills of exchange etc.].</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>13. Customers who wish to maintain a number of trustee or clients&rsquo; accounts which do not appear consistent with the type of business and transactions which involve nominee names.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>14. Matching of cash deposits/withdrawals with payments or transfers out/in.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>15. Deposits of large third party cheques endorsed in favour of the customer.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Activity/Transaction</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>16. Large or unusual activity in dormant/inactive accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>17. Deposit of cash by means of numbered credit slips so that the total of each deposit is unremarkable but the total of all the credits is large.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>18. Customers who open numerous accounts and pay in amounts of cash to each of them in circumstances under which the total credit would be a large amount.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>19. Company accounts whose transactions, both deposits and withdrawals are dominated by cash rather than the forms of transactions normally associated with commercial operations [e.g. cheques, letters of credit, bills of exchange etc.].</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>20. Customers who wish to maintain a number of trustee or clients&rsquo; accounts which do not appear consistent with the type of business and transactions which involve nominee names.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>21. Customers who seek to exchange large quantities or low denomination notes for those of higher denomination.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>22. Request to borrow against assets held by Musoni or a third party where the origin of the assets is not known or inconsistent with the customer&rsquo;s standing.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>23. Use of:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Shell companies;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Parallel accounts;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Non-profit making organisations such as NGOs;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Casinos and gambling establishments;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp; Informal money transfers through Hawalas.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>24. Concealment of funds within Musoni&rsquo;s internal accounts e.g. deposits made into suspense accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>25. Persons using false identities or documents.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>26. Accounts opened by legal entities or organisations where the individuals serving as directors or members are directors or members of other legal entities having the same address or location.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>27. Multiple transactions carried out the same day on the same account.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>28. Multiple wire transfers involving relatively small amounts.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>29. Transfers/deposits into an account with the funds shortly thereafter transferred out to an offshore jurisdiction.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>30. Dealings with foreign political figures.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>31. Employees leading lavish lifestyles that do not match their known income sources.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc429063812\"></a>Internal Suspicious Activity or Transactions Report [SATR]</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:696px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>To:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>AML Compliance Officer [Head Office]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>From:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Branch/Department</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Date:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; [DD/MM/YY]</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"2\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Suspect&rsquo;s Names:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Relationship of Suspect With Musoni:&nbsp;</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>[E.g. Customer, staff, director, shareholder, supplier, agent etc.]</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Account Number:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<table style=\"width:524px\">\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n						<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Account Name[s]:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Postal Address:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Occupation/Nature of Business:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Employer/Business Name:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Date of Birth:</strong></td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; [DD/MM/YY]</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>ID Document:</strong>&nbsp;[e.g. Passport, DL etc.]</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Type:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;