iles</td>\r\n			<td>Back-ups, staff</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Risk matrix</td>\r\n			<td>Quarterly</td>\r\n			<td>PCs and files</td>\r\n			<td>Back-ups, HODs</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Risk assessment reports</td>\r\n			<td>Daily</td>\r\n			<td>PCs and files</td>\r\n			<td>Back-ups, staff</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>RALCO reports</td>\r\n			<td>Quarterly</td>\r\n			<td>PCs and files</td>\r\n			<td>Back-ups, RALCO members</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Credit risk dashboard</td>\r\n			<td>Monthly</td>\r\n			<td>PCs and files</td>\r\n			<td>Back-ups</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc403753617\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923275\"></a>2.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Regulatory &amp; Statutory Reporting Requirements</h2>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:638px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Department</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Finance&amp; Admin.</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Operations</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Credit Admin.</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Human Resource</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Internal Audit</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ICT</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Risk</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Report</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Tax returns, NSSF, NHIF schedules</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Frequency</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Weekly, monthly, quarterly , semi-annual &amp; annually</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Recipients</strong></td>\r\n			<td>KRA, NSSF, NHIF</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Type of penalty</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Fines</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Nature of reports</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Hard copies, soft copies and online.</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n			<td>N/a</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923276\"></a><a name=\"_Toc403753618\"></a>2.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Summary of Key Observations</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Operations, Finance, IT, Credit Admin, Risk &amp; Internal Audit department&rsquo;s work is heavily reliant on the availability of computers, LANs, WAN, email and other communication facilities. Any failure of any of these facilities will render employees unable to work.</li>\r\n	<li>Operations and Credit Administration departments heavily depend on the availability of the MIS. System failure even for a few hours negatively affects loan processing, resulting into loss of revenue.</li>\r\n	<li>Recovery of information that is not backed up is a challenge across all departments and branches.</li>\r\n	<li>Reporting requirements across board (Finance, Operations, Credit Risk and Internal Audit et al) would be impossible if client data on loans and savings isn&rsquo;t accessible. It is also impossible to recover this information unless it is backed up in the computer system.</li>\r\n	<li>E-mail is a central part of the company&rsquo;s communication system, both internally and externally. Losing old emails would deprive the company of vital information and contacts and therefore expect access to all emails after an incident; minor or major.</li>\r\n	<li>Processing of backlogs varies from department to department for every working day lost Credit Admin and Operations would take 4 hours for each day lost, while Finance and Administration would take up to 2 hours. Recovery Human Resources, Risk and Internal Audit will be easier. IT ICT would need up to 12 &ndash; 36 hours to recover from a disaster in case re-installation of PCs &amp; servers is involved.</li>\r\n	<li>Operations and Credit departments require a list of customers, loan and savings balances in the first 24 hours of an incident/ disaster. These are needed so that resources can support critical customer needs.<a name=\"_Toc403753619\"></a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923277\"></a>2.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Conclusion</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Ltd&rsquo;s business is heavily dependent on the functioning of the MIS, including the core operating system (Web Portal), the reporting system (Jasper), the Wide Area Network (WAN) and internal telephone system. The MIS database is hosted by the system vendor in Netherlands. For proper functioning, the disaster recovery and business continuity planning efforts should put emphasis on the infrastructure that supports the Server Rooms, LANs, WAN<a name=\"_Toc403753620\"></a>, the Web Portal and Jasper.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, most departments have critical reports and records that are maintained in hard and soft copies. These records need to be backed up for business continuity purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923278\"></a>2.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BIA Questions</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Business processes</strong>&mdash;What are the business processes for your business unit? Recovery time frames for business unit or process?</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Work backlog</strong>&mdash;For each process above, how long will it take (in hours) to handle the backlog for each day of downtime? Concurrent or sequential backlog processing?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Critical record management</strong>&mdash;Identify critical business records by record name, alternate source (when required), media type.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Regulatory reporting</strong>&mdash;Does business unit have any regulatory reporting requirements? List report name, recipient, frequency, variance, type of penalty (amount, if any).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Outage tolerance</strong>&mdash;Under the worst-case scenario, how long (hours or days) could your business unit be completely idled before it would have a significant impact on the company as a whole, departments, business units, business partners, regulatory compliance?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Operational impact factors</strong>&mdash;for the following operational impacts, define the severity of impact where 0 = no impact, 4 = severe impact. Cash flow, competitive advantage, shareholder confidence, financial reporting, industry image, employee morale, customer service, employee resignations, vendor relations, regulatory, increases in liability.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Reliance on communications</strong>&mdash;Identify reliance on loss of communications, such as telephones, e-mail, etc., where 0 = no impact, 4 = severe impact.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Other issues and concerns</strong>&mdash;Identify any other issues or concerns about recovering your business unit that have not been discussed.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923279\"></a>SECTION 2: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BUSINESS CONTINUITY PLAN</h1>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc358180880\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180427\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387985\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387221\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221306\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214647\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214266\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182065\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178768\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357929043\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357905206\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357902711\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357569256\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357565459\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900363\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899362\"></a><a name=\"_Toc424923280\"></a>1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923281\"></a>1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Purpose</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of this Business Continuity Plan (BCP) is to prepare Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL) in the event of extended service outages caused by factors beyond our control (e.g., natural disasters, IT system failures, electrical power failures, man-made events, etc.), and to restore services to the widest extent possible in a minimum time frame. All Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s branches and offices are expected to implement preventive measures whenever possible to minimise network failure and to recover as rapidly as possible when a failure occurs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plan identifies vulnerabilities and recommends necessary measures to prevent extended service outages. It is a plan that encompasses all Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s system sites and operations facilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc359900366\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899365\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832168\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722629\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396945\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395427\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395043\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387988\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387224\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221309\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214650\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214269\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182067\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357929045\"></a>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc424923282\"></a>Scope</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The scope of this plan is limited to Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s offices and branches. It does not cover clients, service providers or offsite facilities, if those facilities are outsourced. This is a business continuity plan and not a daily problem resolution procedures document.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923283\"></a>1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Plan Objectives</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Serves as a guide for Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s recovery teams.</li>\r\n	<li>References and points to the location of any data that resides outside this document.</li>\r\n	<li>Provides procedures and resources needed to assist in recovery.</li>\r\n	<li>Identifies vendors, service providers and customers that must be notified in the event of a disaster.</li>\r\n	<li>Assists in avoiding confusion experienced during a crisis by documenting, testing and reviewing recovery procedures.</li>\r\n	<li>Identifies emergency alternate sources for supplies, resources and locations.</li>\r\n	<li>Documents storage, safeguarding and retrieval procedures for vital records.</li>\r\n	<li>Detects the threat, reduces on the likelihood of occurrence and minimises the impact of a disaster.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923284\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900369\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899368\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832171\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722632\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396948\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395430\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395046\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387991\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387227\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221312\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214653\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214272\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182070\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178773\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357929047\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357905209\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357902714\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357569259\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357565462\"></a>1.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Assumptions</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Key people (Team Leaders or Alternates) will be available following a disaster.</li>\r\n	<li>This document and all vital records are stored in a secure off-site location and not only survive the disaster but are accessible immediately following the disaster.</li>\r\n	<li>Each support function will have its own plan consisting of unique recovery procedures, critical resource information and procedures.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923285\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900364\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899363\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832166\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722627\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396943\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395425\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395041\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387986\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387222\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221307\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214648\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214267\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358784171\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358783871\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358782473\"></a>1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster definition</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>For purposes of this BCP, Disaster shall be defined as: Any loss of utility service (power, water), burglary, connectivity (leased lines), or catastrophic event (weather, fire, natural disaster, vandalism, office break-in, terrorism activities, bomb or weapon threat, computer intrusion, water leaking/flooding, electrical power failure &amp; outages, earthquakes, loss of workforce, negative publicity, transport disruption and others) that may cause an interruption in the business operations of Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL).&nbsp; The plan identifies vulnerabilities and recommends measures to prevent extended service outages.<a name=\"_Toc359900367\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899366\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832169\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722630\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396946\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395428\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395044\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387989\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387225\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221310\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214651\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214270\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182068\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178771\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923286\"></a>1.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Senior Management team (SMT) Contacts</h2>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:637px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Name</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Designation</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Email</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Telephone</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>James Onyutta</td>\r\n			<td>Chief Executive Officer</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:Jamesonyutta@musoni.eu\">Jamesonyutta@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0716 505179</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Ernest Mbidha</td>\r\n			<td>Ag. Chief Operations Officer</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:ernestmbidha@musoni.eu\">ernestmbidha@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0721 291817</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>James Owino</td>\r\n			<td>Chief Finance Officer</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:jamesowino@musoni.eu\">jamesowino@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0721 610924</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Judy Ndung&rsquo;u</td>\r\n			<td>Chief Human Resource Officer</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:judyndungu@musoni.eu\">judyndungu@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0721112002</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Rosemary Muyeshi</td>\r\n			<td>Risk Manager</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:rosemarymuyeshi@musoni.eu\">rosemarymuyeshi@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0723 721079</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Gregory Makau</td>\r\n			<td>IT Manager</td>\r\n			<td><a href=\"mailto:gregorymakau@musoni.eu\">gregorymakau@musoni.eu</a></td>\r\n			<td>0721 528085</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923287\"></a>1.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster Recovery Teams</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Disaster Recovery Teams for Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL) shall be constituted as summarized in the table1 below: Team member responsibilities are as follows:-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All the members shall maintain an updated contacts list of their work team members in their personal Dairies and Mobile phone Address Books.</li>\r\n	<li>All team members shall keep this a hard copy of this BCP document for reference at home in case the disaster happens after normal work hours.</li>\r\n	<li>All team members shall familiarise themselves with the contents of this plan.</li>\r\n	<li>Where possible, Team members shall maintain a copy of the BCP Document on their personal Smart Phones/Tablets.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923288\"></a>1.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Table1: Summary of Disaster Recovery Teams</h2>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:667px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; No</td>\r\n			<td>Team Name</td>\r\n			<td>Team members</td>\r\n			<td>Roles &amp; responsibilities</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1.</td>\r\n			<td>Disaster Management Team (DMT)</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp; Chief Executive Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp; Chief Operations Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp; Chief Finance Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp; Risk Manager</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp; IT Manager</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Key role:</strong>&nbsp;Responsible for overall coordination of the disaster recovery effort, evaluation and determining disaster declaration, and communications&nbsp; in the company and stakeholders</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp; Evaluate which recovery actions should be invoked and activate the corresponding recovery teams.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp; Evaluate and assess extent of damage as a result of the disaster.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp; Set restoration priority based on the damage assessment reports</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp; Provide appropriate communication to staff, media, Regulator, Board, Customers and other stakeholders.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp; Work with vendors, Disaster Recovery Coordinators DRC) and the Disaster Recovery Team (DRT) to Implement the Disaster Recovery Action Plan.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2.</td>\r\n			<td>Disaster Response Coordinator (DRC)</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Branch managers for each branch.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chief Finance Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Key Role: Responsible for overall coordination of the disaster recovery effort for their branch/office, establishment of the assembly point, and communications with Disaster Management Team (DMT)</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Notify the Disaster Management Team (DMT) and the Disaster Recovery Team (DRT) of any disaster situation.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gather damage assessment information and report it to DMT</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Review the Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s Minimum Acceptable Operational Requirements checklist to determine if sufficient resources are in place to support operations</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Establish command centre and related operations.&nbsp; The command centre is a prearranged meeting facility where DMT/DRC/DRT members meet to coordinate damage assessment and business recovery tasks for the affected operations.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Notify all Disaster Recovery Team Leaders and advise them to activate their plan(s) if applicable, based upon the disaster situation</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If no disaster is declared, then take appropriate action to return to normal operation using regular staff and available facilities.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Determine if vendors, emergency service (police. Fire brigade, medical) and/or other teams are needed to assist with detailed damage assessment.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prepare post-disaster debriefing report</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3.</td>\r\n			<td><a name=\"_Toc404582430\"></a>Disaster Recovery Team (DRT)</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Head Office:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finance Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Administration Assistant</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chief Finance Officer</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk Manager</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Credit Administration Assistants</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Branches</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Branch Manager</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Wealth Creation Officers</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Customer Service Assistants.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Key Role: The Incident Response Team (IRT) is formed to deploy to the disaster location when a disaster is declared.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide recovery support to the affected location and operations</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coordinate resumption of voice and data communications:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>a.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Work with management to re-route telephone and data (WAN) lines, especially when alternate site(s) or alternate work locations are predefined</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>b.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recover telephone and electronic mail systems when requested by DMT.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>c.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Verify telephone and electronic mail is operational at the alternate site.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>d.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Review the Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s Minimum Acceptable Operational Requirements checklist to determine if sufficient resources are in place to support operations</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coordinate resumption of information system operations:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Work with management to recover critical systems e.g. core operating systems, reporting systems and infrastructure at recovery site(s) or alternate work locations</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recover critical data files and related information when requested by DMT</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that network and perimeter security is re-established at alternate location</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>d)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Verify normal, secure operation of systems and servers at alternate site</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>e)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coordinate removal of salvageable equipment, materials and documents at disaster site that may be used for alternate site operations.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923289\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900370\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899369\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832172\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722633\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396949\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395431\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395047\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387992\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387228\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221313\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214654\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214273\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182071\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178774\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357929048\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357905210\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357902715\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357569260\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357565463\"></a>1.9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Instructions for using the plan</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923290\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900371\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899370\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832173\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722634\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396950\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395432\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395048\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387993\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387229\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221314\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214655\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214274\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182072\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358178775\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357929049\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357905211\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357902716\"></a>1.9.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Invoking the plan</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This plan becomes effective when a disaster occurs. Normal problem management procedures will initiate the plan, and remain in effect until operations are resumed at the original location, or a replacement location and control is returned to the appropriate functional management.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923291\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900769\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359820308\"></a>1.9.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster declaration</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In a major disaster situation, the decision to declare a disaster will be determined by the Chief Executive Officer (CEO). The Disaster Management Team/Disaster Response (s) will respond based on the directives specified by CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923292\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900770\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359820309\"></a>1.9.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster Notification</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of the nature of the disaster, or the identity of the person(s) first made aware of the disaster, the members of the Disaster Management Team (DMT) and Disaster Recovery Coordinators (DRC) must be immediately notified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the Responsibility of All Staff of Musoni Kenya Ltd to notify responsible authorities of any actual or impending disaster situation. Outside normal working hours, the Security Personnel Guarding Musoni Kenya Ltd office premises shall be tasked, through their employers, with the responsibility of reporting any disaster Incident. This will be done through reporting to the respective Disaster Recovery Coordinators and their immediate supervisors.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923293\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900771\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359820310\"></a>1.9.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; External communications</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chief Executive Officer is the only designated person as the principal contact with the media (radio, television, and print), regulatory agency, government agencies and other external organisations following a formal disaster declaration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923294\"></a>1.10&nbsp;&nbsp; Minimum Business Continuity standards</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923295\"></a>1.10.1&nbsp; Data backup policy</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>ICT department shall on regular basis carry out Full and incremental/differential backups to preserve the institution&rsquo;s information digital assets. This will be done for audit logs and files that are irreplaceable, have a high replacement cost, or are considered critical.</li>\r\n	<li>Backup media shall be stored in a secure, geographically separate location from the original and isolated from environmental hazards. This stored data will also be encrypted to guarantee extra layer of security for the stored information.</li>\r\n	<li>Each Department shall be availed a shared folder on the file Server where Critical Documents/records shall be saved and backed up in accordance with the back-up policy.</li>\r\n	<li>Information Communication Technology (ICT) department follows the above standards for its data backup and archiving:</li>\r\n	<li>For each of the conducted backups of all Musoni records and software must be retained such that computer operating systems and applications are fully recoverable. This will be achieved through a combination of differential backups, image copies, and transactional backups among others.</li>\r\n	<li>The frequency of data backups is to be determined by the volatility of data; the retention period for the backup copies will also be determined by the criticality of the data. The backup copies must be retained for 30 days.</li>\r\n	<li>At least three (3) versions of Musoni Kenya backup records must be maintained.</li>\r\n	<li>At a minimum, one fully recoverable version of all Musoni data records must be stored in a secure, off-site location. An off-site location may be with an off-site storage vendor that has been approved by Musoni Kenya.</li>\r\n	<li>Derived data should be backed up only if restoration is more efficient than creation in the event of failure.</li>\r\n	<li>All Musoni Kenya information located directly on workstations, laptops, or other portable devices, that is essential for the business continuity may be backed up to an off-site location using networked file server drives or through use of other connection agents.</li>\r\n	<li>Required backup documentation includes identification of all critical data, programs, documentation, and support items that will be necessary to perform essential tasks during a recovery period. The documentation of the restoration process must be inclusive of procedures for the recovery from single-system or application failures, as well as for a total data center scenario, if applicable.</li>\r\n	<li>Backup and recovery documentation must be reviewed and updated regularly to account for new technology, business changes and migration of applications to alternative platforms.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Regular tests must be carried out to establish the effectiveness of the Musoni&rsquo;s backup and restore procedures by restoring data/software from backup copies and analyzing the results. Musoni IT manager should be provided with information relating to any issues with the backup testing of their data</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923296\"></a>1.10.2&nbsp; Backup media storage policy:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc404582439\"></a>Backup media shall be stored at locations that are secure, isolated from environmental hazards, and geographically separate from the location housing the system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copies of backup media must be removed from devices as soon as possible when a backup or restore has been completed</li>\r\n	<li>Backup media which is retained on-site prior to being sent for storage at a remote location must be stored securely in a locked safe and at a sufficient distance away from the original data to ensure both the original and backup copies are not compromised</li>\r\n	<li>Access to the on-site backup location and storage safe must be restricted to authorized personnel only</li>\r\n	<li>All backups identified for long term storage must be stored at a remote secure location with appropriate environmental control and protection to ensure the integrity of all backup media</li>\r\n	<li>Backup media must be protected in accordance with the guidelines provided by Musoni Kenya</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Backup data/media no longer required must be clearly marked and recorded for secure disposal and with due environmental consideration</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923297\"></a>1.10.3&nbsp; Offsite backup facilities</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>An off-site backup facility will be established and integrated into the Management Information System disaster recovery procedures manual. This facility may be internal or outsourced. ICT department will work with management to establish and maintain the same facility.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923298\"></a>1.10.4&nbsp; Storage of Hard copy files and Documents</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Hardcopy Records [loan files, reports, vouchers, slips, etc] are kept within departments and branches. Sensitive documents like Client securities shall be kept in fire-proof filing cabinets. Records that are no longer required on a regular basis and non-active records, which need to be kept for legal reasons or other business needs, shall be transferred to an off-site storage. They will be stored securely for as long as required, retrieved and returned when necessary, and destroyed in accordance with the retention schedule when no longer required.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hard copy paper files containing important information and data should be scanned and stored electronically to ensure digital copies are created which can be backed up by the Council&rsquo;s ICT systems. Where this may not be possible, photocopies of paper files must be made and stored in a secure storage location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Administration department will develop detailed guidelines for the preparation and transfer of records for off-site storage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923299\"></a>1.10.5&nbsp; Cash Management</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each Branch shall at all times maintain sufficient liquidity to sustain its business operations on daily basis in form of:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>End of week petty cash balance of Ksh 10,000.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923300\"></a>1.10.6&nbsp; Stationery Management</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All Branches shall maintain adequate stock levels of critical stationery like cartridge, printing papers, journal vouchers, etc. The level of stationery stock maintained at all times shall be sufficient to run branch operations for at least one Week before replenishment is received.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923301\"></a>1.10.7&nbsp; Custody of keys</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Each branch shall maintain 3 copies of its office keys.</li>\r\n	<li>2 copies will be held at the branch while the third copy shall be maintained at the Administration department. .</li>\r\n	<li>A keys Register Shall be maintained in all Branches and Head office in which details of the Key holders shall be taken.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>1.10.8&nbsp; &nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc424923302\"></a>Insurance policy</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All key Assets of Musoni Kenya Ltd shall be insured. These assets include:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Fixed Assets [Computer Software &amp; Hardware, Furniture, Equipment etc.]</li>\r\n		<li>The individual lending loan portfolio. Once an insurance service provider for Kilimo loans is sourced, the kilimo loan portfolio will be insured as per the terms and conditions of the contract.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Administration Department shall ensure all policies are updated and running at all times.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>1.10.9&nbsp; &nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc424923303\"></a>Succession Planning</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Human Resource department shall maintain an updated succession Plan for key positions and functions at branch and departmental levels.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>1.10.10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc424923304\"></a>Alternative Wide Area Network (WAN) Links</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Alternative Wide Area Network (WAN) Links shall be installed in all Branches to ensure network availability at Branches so as to support business operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923305\"></a>1.10.11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Power Supply</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Computers in all branches will be connected to UPS devices and inverters that will keep them running in the event of power outage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All WCOs will be provided with power banks that will be used to charge their tablets remotely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923306\"></a>1.10.12&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Emergency fire equipment</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Every Branch/Head office shall have functioning Fire Extinguishers that will be serviced every 6 months. All staff shall be trained on use of these equipment.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923307\"></a>1.10.13&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Security Controls</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Security checks: All visitors shall be subjected to security checks by security personnel guarding the office premises.</li>\r\n	<li>Registration of Visitors: All Branches and Head office shall have registers where particulars of all visitors shall be captured. This will include visitors who will be attended to beyond the reception area.</li>\r\n	<li>Security Alarm Systems shall be installed in all Musoni Kenya Ltd&rsquo;s office premises.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923308\"></a>2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster Management Procedures</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The following procedures are to be followed by Disaster Recovery Teams and other designated personnel in the event of an emergency. Where uncertainty exists, the more reactive action should be followed to provide maximum protection and personnel safety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; Any stranger recognised by the Disaster Recovery Team must be challenged by the staff who should then notify security personnel. These procedures are furnished to Musoni Kenya Ltd (MKL)&rsquo;s management Team to take home for reference. Emergency contacts, Addresses and telephone numbers have also been included in this document.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below are summaries of procedures to be followed in the following disaster situations:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923309\"></a>2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Failure to access office premises</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of any situation where access to office premises or system is denied, the Disaster Recovery Coordinator (DRC) shall upon the advice of the DMT direct personnel to report to alternate location with a view to resume business operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Alternate locations</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Branch</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Alternate Location</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Important Note</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Head Office</td>\r\n			<td>Kitengela Branch</td>\r\n			<td rowspan=\"13\">\r\n			<p>Customers shall be directed to be serviced from these alternative sites.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Critical departments of Finance, ICT, Credit Administration &amp; Operations will relocate and operate from Kitengela branch.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>In the short-term (up-to 3days) Other Departments will work from home connecting to the Corporate network through a VPN.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Management shall Identify alternative premises for the rest of the departments to work in in case of a disaster resulting to loss of premises.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Zimmerman branch</td>\r\n			<td>Kiambu office</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Kiambu Office</td>\r\n			<td>Zimmerman branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Gikomba branch</td>\r\n			<td>Kariobangi office</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Kawangware office</td>\r\n			<td>Gikomba branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Kariobangi office</td>\r\n			<td>Gikomba branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Kitengela branch</td>\r\n			<td>Rongai office</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Rongai office</td>\r\n			<td>Kitengela branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Machakos office</td>\r\n			<td>Kitengela branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Thika branch</td>\r\n			<td>Zimmerman branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Murang&rsquo;a office</td>\r\n			<td>Thika branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Naivasha branch</td>\r\n			<td>Narok office</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Nakuru office</td>\r\n			<td>Nakuru branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Narok office</td>\r\n			<td>Naivasha branch</td>\r\n			<td rowspan=\"3\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Kisii branch</td>\r\n			<td>Narok office</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Donholm branch</td>\r\n			<td>Gikomba branch</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company has to weigh the risk versus the cost of creating the contingency plan. This will help the company determine and decide on the risk that can be tolerated and how much it is willing to spend to put in place mitigation measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923310\"></a>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of a fire</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of a fire or smoke in any of the buildings/offices, the guidelines and procedures in this section are to be followed.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If fire or smoke is present in the building/ office/ branch, the Branch Manager will evacuate all personnel from the building, following a pre-defined escape route, then do a staff head count and confirm the ware bouts of staff who are not present.</li>\r\n	<li>The designated fire assembly points for all branches and offices have been listed in Appendix E.</li>\r\n	<li>In case of minor fires (e.g., single hardware component or paper fires), personnel should attempt to extinguish minor fires using hand-held fire extinguishers located throughout all our offices and branches.</li>\r\n	<li>In the event of a major fire, call 999 as soon as possible. To get effective response, please follow the procedures below:</li>\r\n	<li>Do not assume that someone else had already made the call.</li>\r\n	<li>During the Call, Speak slowly and clearly. When the receiver picks the call, state&rdquo;. This is an emergency. I am calling from Musoni Kenya Ltd,&nbsp;<em>branch name or Head office</em>. My name is.......We need emergency police...Fire, medical services as appropriate.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Follow the receivers lead by answering questions about location, nature and severity of incident, status etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Provide to the recipient phone contacts [preferably yours], if you are not in danger.</li>\r\n	<li>Provide support to any rescue team in terms of more information and the team to receive the police on arrival at the scene.</li>\r\n	<li>Notify the Disaster Response Team as soon as possible,</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923311\"></a>2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of M-PESA network outage</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni will obtain the services of another mobile network service provider so that clients will have two options through which their loan facilities, repayments and savings will be channelled. At the moment, Musoni only uses the services of Safaricom Kenya Ltd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In case of M-PESA network outage, the following procedures will apply;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>STEP</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ACTION</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>1</strong></td>\r\n			<td>The branch Manager will notify the DMT of the outage.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n			<td>If outage is greater than one day, clients will during group meetings, show the text messages they received from M-PESA as confirmations after sending their repayments.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923312\"></a>2.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of a network services provider outage</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of a network service provider outage to any facility, the guidelines and procedures in this section are to be followed. Follow the procedure here below to return service to normal operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>STEP</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ACTION</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>1</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Notify Branch Manager of outage who will notify the ICT department of the outage. ICT will determine cause of outage, possible solutions and timeframe for its recovery.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>If outage will be greater than 1 hour, route all calls via wireless (Safaricom CUG) or other service to alternate location.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>If it&rsquo;s a WAN failure, all data, PABX (voice) connections will be automatically routed through the backup links (Orange telecom links) installed at the branches and head office.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>If it is a major outage and all carriers are down and downtime will be greater than 4 hours:-</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp; Revert to manual procedures as provided for in the&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;<strong>Disaster Recovery Procedures Manual</strong>&rdquo;.</em></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp; All database transactions to be completed at the alternate branch as stated in section 2.12.1, if available.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923313\"></a>2.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of a flooding or water Leakage</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of a flood or broken water pipe within any computing facilities, the guidelines and procedures in this section are to be followed. Follow the procedure here below to return service to normal operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>STEP</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ACTION</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>1</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Assess the situation and determine if outside assistance is needed; if this is the case, dial 999 immediately or call on the systems support company as maybe found appropriate.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Immediately notify all other personnel in the facility of the situation and to be prepared to cease operations accordingly.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>3</strong></td>\r\n			<td>If water is originating from above the equipment, power down the individual devices and cover the affected equipment.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>4</strong></td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Water detected below the raised floor may have different causes:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&mdash;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If water is slowly dripping from an air conditioning unit and not endangering equipment, contact repair personnel immediately.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&mdash;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If water is of a major quantity and flooding beneath the floor (water main break), immediately implement power-down procedures. While power-down procedures are in progress, evacuate the area and follow supervisor&rsquo;s instructions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923314\"></a>2.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of Burglary/Office Break-in</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:630px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>STEP</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ACTION</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>1</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Immediately notify the nearest Police Station</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Do not temper with the scene of the incident until when police arrives</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>3</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Notify the DRC and DMT about the incident</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>4</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Recollect the events prior to the last time you left the premises. The police may need to record statements from in-charge of the premises, security guards, staff, neighbours etc as it deems necessary.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>5</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Take stock of all assets/property to ascertain missing items.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>6</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Confirm if critical assets to resume business are intact- e.g., Computers, printers, furniture, internet connectivity, etc.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>7</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Prepare a preliminary report to the DMT with emphasis on what is required to resume operations</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>8</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Ensure staff do not make statements to the press.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923315\"></a>2.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the event of Computer failure, hacking or virus invasion</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:630px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>STEP</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>ACTION</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>1</strong></td>\r\n			<td>All Computer users at Branch and Head Office shall report any unusual/ unfamiliar behaviour/activity/or response on their machines to IT Help Desk</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n			<td>IT Helpdesk will ascertain the nature of the attack whether it&rsquo;s a computer intrusion, computer hacking, virus attack, denial of service (DoS).</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>3</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Notify the IT Manager who will in turn notify the DMT after taking precautionary measures in line with the ICT policies and procedures manual.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>4</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Ascertain the origin and cause of the attack and/or failure then make assessment of the scale and impact of the attack.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>5</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Take corrective measures which include closing out areas of weakness that caused the failure/hacking/virus attack.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>6</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Prepare a preliminary report to the DMT with emphasis on what is required to resume operations where necessary.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>7</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Document the incident clearly stating the nature, cause, impact, action taken to resolve and avoid future occurrences.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>8</strong></td>\r\n			<td>Ensure staff do not make uncoordinated statements to members of the public/press.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923316\"></a>3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BCP Review, Testing and Implementation</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>This plan is intended to be a living document and as such must be reviewed on a regular basis. The plan will be reviewed annually and tested on quarterly basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923317\"></a>3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BCP Testing</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The test may be in the form of a checklist test, walk-through or mock disaster/simulation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Checklist testing:</strong>&nbsp;A checklist test shall be done to determine whether the plan is current, correct telephone numbers are available, minimum business continuity standards are in place, proper documentation is in place and copies of the plan and other additional documents are available to all members. This kind of test will be carried out on a quarterly basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Walk-through testing</strong>: This test shall be performed on departmental or functional basis and involves detailed walk-through of the various components of the plan. The BCP Coordinator will choose the type of disaster and parts of the plan to be tested. This kind of test will be carried out on a bi-annual basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Mock disaster/simulation:</strong>&nbsp;A mock disaster shall be simulated that will require staff to use equipment, facilities and supplies as provided for in the plan, to carry out critical functions in their respective areas. This kind of test will be carried out on an annual basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923318\"></a>3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BCP Implementation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The BCP Coordinator shall be responsible for coordination of implementation of the Business Continuity Plan. This role shall be assigned to Risk Manager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The specific responsibilities of the BCP Coordinator are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Regularly review and update information in the disaster recovery plan (e.g., contact lists, equipment inventories). Updates shall be done on Quarterly basis or when there is a change in personnel</li>\r\n	<li>Communicate with the Disaster Recovery Coordinators to get up-to-date information periodically.</li>\r\n	<li>Ensure every Branch, department has in place the minimal BCP standards (See section 2.11)</li>\r\n	<li>Hold initial team meeting to get team members acquainted with the plan and hold annual/semi-annual meetings to review the plan on an on-going basis</li>\r\n	<li>Carry out sensitization and training for all staff to acquaint themselves with the BCP</li>\r\n	<li>Ensure BCP document is circulated and cascaded to all staff</li>\r\n	<li>Liaise with the DMT &amp; DRC to plan and execute BCP tests.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923319\"></a>4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disaster Incident Management Process:</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>When a disaster happens, restoration of full service provision to customers is expected completed within 72 Hours. The flow diagram below summarises the various action points from the time the incident happened up to when key services are fully restored.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Incident Management Flowchart</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Response and recovery checklists below may be used by DRCs, DRT and DMT as &quot;quick references&quot; when implementing the plan or for training purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923320\"></a><a name=\"_Toc404582462\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900379\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899378\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832181\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722642\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396958\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395440\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395056\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388001\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387237\"></a>4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recovery Plan checklists (To be Filled in the Event of a Disaster)</h2>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Initials</td>\r\n			<td>Task to be completed</td>\r\n			<td>Status</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc359900381\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899380\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832183\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722644\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396960\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395442\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395058\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388003\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387239\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221321\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214662\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214281\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182079\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180887\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180435\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074488\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997196\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995583\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995077\"></a><a name=\"_Toc424923321\"></a>4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Notification of incident</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>During working hours:</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon observation or notification of a potentially serious situation during working hours at a system/facility, ensure that personnel on site have in place standard emergency and evacuation procedures if appropriate<a name=\"_Toc359900383\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899382\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832185\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722646\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396962\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395444\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395060\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388005\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387241\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221323\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214664\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214283\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182081\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180889\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180437\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074490\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997198\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995585\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995079\"></a>&nbsp;and notify the Disaster Response Coordinator.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Outside working hours:</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>External security services personnel guarding the premises shall contact the Disaster Response Coordinator and their supervisor. The DRC will contacts the DMT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Provide status to DMT</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The Disaster Response Coordinator (DRC) will contact the Disaster Management Team (DMT) and provide information on:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Location of disaster</li>\r\n	<li>Type of disaster (e.g., fire, hurricane, flood, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Summarise the damage(e.g., minimal, heavy, total destruction)</li>\r\n	<li>Emergency Coordination Centre location [a meeting location that is close to the situation, but away from the disaster scene] and phone contact number</li>\r\n	<li>An estimated timeframe of when a damage assessment group can enter the facility (if possible)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The DMT will contact and notify the Chief Executive Officer [CEO] about the reported disaster incident.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Declare a disaster</strong>&nbsp;if the situation is not likely to be resolved within predefined time frames, the Chief Executive Officer declare a disaster and all the Disaster Management Teams will be activated to address the situation.</li>\r\n	<li><a name=\"_Toc359900384\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899383\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832186\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722647\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396963\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395445\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395061\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388007\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387243\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221325\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214666\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214285\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182083\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180891\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180439\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074492\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997200\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995587\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995081\"></a>&nbsp;<strong>Decide course of action:</strong>&nbsp;Based on the information obtained, the DMT in consultation with the CEO will decide how to respond to the event: Some of the actions/decisions could include; mobilize the DRT, repair/rebuild/Replace existing site(s) or facilities, or relocate to a new facility.</li>\r\n	<li>Inform the DRC and DRT members of decision reached.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>If a disaster is not declared,</strong>&nbsp;the Disaster Recovery Team will continue to address and manage the situation through its normal resolution and provide periodic status updates to the DMT.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>If a disaster is declared,</strong>&nbsp;the Disaster Recovery Coordinator will notify the Disaster Recovery Team members immediately about the recovery action to be taken and the roles the DRT members will play.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Notification of Customers</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>If need be, the DCR shall upon guidance from the DMT, notify the customers about the incident and advise on the cause of action Management has taken to restore service provision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc359900385\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899384\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832187\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722648\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396964\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395446\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395062\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388008\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387244\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221326\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214667\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214286\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182084\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180892\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180440\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074493\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997201\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995588\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995082\"></a><a name=\"_Toc424923322\"></a>4.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Upon declaration of Disaster:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Mobilise&nbsp;<strong>Disaster Recovery Team Members [See Appendix C]</strong>&nbsp;and Report to Emergency Coordination centre.</li>\r\n	<li>The Disaster Recovery Coordinator will determine the Emergency Coordination centre.</li>\r\n	<li>The DRT will initiate [in consultation with the DMT] and coordinate the implementation of appropriate recovery actions.</li>\r\n	<li>DRT members must assemble at the Emergency Coordination centre as quickly as possible.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Conduct detailed damage assessment&nbsp;</strong>(This may also be performed prior to declaring a disaster).The DRT remains at the affected site to perform a preliminary damage assessment (if permitted). Under the direction of local authorities/Police the DRC/DMT assess the damage to the affected location and/or assets. If need be, include vendors/providers of installed equipment to ensure that their expert opinion regarding the condition of the equipment is determined ASAP.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Participate in a briefing on assessment requirements, reviewing:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Assessment procedures</li>\r\n	<li>Gather requirements</li>\r\n	<li>Safety and security issues</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE: Access to the facility following a fire or potential chemical contamination will likely be denied for 24 hours or longer.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Document assessment results using Assessment and Evaluation Forms contained in Appendix G.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Building access permitting:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Conduct an on-site inspection of affected areas to assess damage to essential hardcopy records (files, manuals, contracts, documentation, etc) and electronic data</li>\r\n	<li>Obtain information regarding damage to the facility (e.g. environmental conditions, physical structure integrity, furniture, and fixtures) from the DRC.</li>\r\n	<li>Develop a Restoration Priority List, identifying facilities, vital records and equipment needed for resumption activities that could be operationally restored and retrieved quickly</li>\r\n	<li>Develop a Salvage Priority List identifying sites and records which could eventually be salvaged</li>\r\n	<li>Recommendations for required resources</li>\r\n	<li>Contact the DMT and decide whether the situation requires the initiation of business recovery plans (long-term disaster months) or if work can return to the primary location (short-term week or so)<strong>.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Contact</strong>&nbsp;<strong>DMT/decide whether to continue to business recovery phase</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The DRC gathers information from the DRT and other sources; contacts the DMT and provides the DMT with detailed damage assessment information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Based on the information obtained from the DRC, the DMT decides whether to continue to the business recovery phase of this plan. If the situation does not warrant this action, continue to address the situation at the affected site(s). Provide periodic status updates to the DMT Leader.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923323\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900407\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899406\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832209\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722670\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396986\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395468\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395083\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388029\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387265\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221347\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214688\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214307\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182105\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180913\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180461\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074514\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997222\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995609\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995103\"></a>4.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Business Recovery Phase (72 hours - full recovery)</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The business recovery phase of this plan will be implemented when resources are required to support full restoration of system and/or facility functionality at an alternate recovery site (e.g., another company office, alternate premises identified by branches, vendor hot site, cold site) that would be used for an extended period of time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;During the Initial Response Phase, service may be shifted to alternate sites to allow operations to begin functioning and provide service to the customers. Initially reduced service may be provided until sites can be fully restored. Within 48 hours, the system and facilities should be functional at 100%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Disaster Recovery Coordinator will work closely with the Disaster Management Team and key departments like ICT, finance and Administration and Operations to coordinate resources to reconstruct business operations at the temporary/permanent alternate location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The initial facilities to be put in place to restore service shall be based on&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc404582466\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900413\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899412\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832215\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722676\"></a>Musoni Kenya Ltd&rsquo;s&nbsp;<strong>Minimal System and facility&nbsp;</strong><strong>requirements</strong>&nbsp;to run business operations (See details in<strong>&nbsp;Appendix F)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923324\"></a><a name=\"_Toc404582467\"></a>4.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Secure funding for relocation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Make arrangements in advance with suitable backup location resources. Make arrangements in advance with the head office, sister branches, local hotels, office equipment/utilities suppliers and others for emergency support. Depending on the incident, its severity and alternate location option selected, contact the appropriate alternate site owner, the local bank branch and other relevant firms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923325\"></a><a name=\"_Toc404582469\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900417\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359899416\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359832219\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359722680\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359396995\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395477\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359395092\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359388038\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359387274\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359221356\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214697\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359214316\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358182114\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180922\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358180470\"></a><a name=\"_Toc358074523\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357997231\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995618\"></a><a name=\"_Toc357995112\"></a>4.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Operations recovered</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Assuming all relevant operations have been recovered to an alternate site, and employees are in place to support operations, the company can declare that it is functioning in a normal manner at the recovery location.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923326\"></a>SECTION 3: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MIS Disaster Recovery Procedures</h1>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923327\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635233\"></a>1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni&rsquo;s core operations rely heavily on computer systems. Unfortunately, computer systems are not always as reliable as we would wish them to be and therefore we need to be prepared for the likelihood that at some stage, systems are either unavailable or not operating as designed. This document attempts to identify scenarios in which this could arise and provides a guide in dealing with the disruptions with minimal effect on operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This document attempts to identify the most likely causes of interruption to service and how the branch and ICT, Operations and Finance departments should respond in each scenario. It looks at loss of power from 2 hours to several days, failure of the server and other hardware as well as MISs failure. Unfortunately it is not always easy to predict what type of things could cause a disruption but hopefully this document will provide a first step reference guide.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923328\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635234\"></a>1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scenario:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Loss of power for 2 hours to 1 day</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923329\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635235\"></a>1.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Description</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A power failure occurs and power is not restored for several hours (between 2 and 8). All branches will have a battery powered inverter system to supply backup power.&nbsp; The recovery steps will differ depending on which is installed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As part of the Standard Operating Environment (SOE), the company has a UPS installed for each computer and that will support graceful shutdown of any system within 10 minutes at a minimum. Any system that does not meet this minimum requirement should be reported to ICT department for remedial action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923330\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635237\"></a>1.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recovery Steps- Inverter</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Every branch will have an inverter that will immediately &lsquo;kick in&rsquo; and act as a battery backup as soon as power is lost. There should be no effect felt by the computers or network during this transition so work can continue as normal. However if after 4 hours the power has not returned then the following steps should be taken:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>Branch Manager (BM)</td>\r\n			<td>Calls the Chief Finance Officer, the Chief Operations Officer, the IT Manager and the Risk Manager and informs them of the length of power outage and any available news regarding when the power will be restored.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>H/O IT</td>\r\n			<td>Assess needs of branch if power is not returned by the end of that day. This includes supply of laptops, generator and additional battery support.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3</td>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>If power is not back by the end of the day, relocate the branch to the alternative branch as stated in this policy.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The BM will give priority to credit committee activities and will therefore hold the meeting in the alternative branch as indicated above. If unable to, the BM together with the credit committee members will go to the nearest branch (as indicated in this manual) to hold a credit committee meeting.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>8</td>\r\n			<td>BM/IT</td>\r\n			<td>Monitor the UPS on the server. As soon as this starts to beep/signal alarm it means that the inverter battery has expired. Inform everyone to finish their current transaction and shut down- if they have not already lost power. Then shut down the server that is based at the branch.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>10</td>\r\n			<td>BM/IT</td>\r\n			<td>Once power is restored the server and networking equipment (routers, switches &amp; WAN devices) should be restarted. Check the default date that appears when you log into the system and ensure that the system has not lost any transactions due to the power outage (would only happen if the connection was lost instantly.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>11</td>\r\n			<td>Branch</td>\r\n			<td>After power is restored all transactions not previously posted will be added to the system.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>14</td>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>Document the failure noting what worked and what didn&rsquo;t. This should be submitted to the IT and Risk Managers so that lessons learnt can be integrated into future plans.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The life of the inverter batteries is approximately 8hrs as long as the batteries are fully charged. The batteries must be serviced every three months to check the voltage level and rid the system of dust, which can seriously affect the performance of the inverter. In most &lsquo;normal&rsquo; situations where power is lost for short period of time (around 1 hour) the batteries will fully recharge overnight. It can therefore be assumed that the following day the batteries will be returned to their full capacity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923331\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635238\"></a>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scenario 2- loss of power for 1 day or longer</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923332\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635239\"></a>1.2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Description</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A power failure occurs and power is not restored for after 1 day (8hrs). Again a branch with a generator installed will not have much issue in this type of scenario however for those branches with inverters, the inverter batteries life will now have expired and no backup power supply is available.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923333\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635241\"></a>1.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recovery Steps- Inverter</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In the initial hours in which power is off the steps 1-10 outlined in Scenario 1 should be followed. These steps will prepare the branch for the possibility that power will not return within that working day. If by the end of the working day power has not be restored, but the inverter batter is still running the following steps should be followed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>Branch Manager (BM)</td>\r\n			<td>Hold a branch credit committee meeting and ensure that all loan applications have been processed.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>CSA</td>\r\n			<td>Ensure that all loan corrections, funds transfers, portfolio transfers, client transfers and items in the suspense accounts have been processed.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4</td>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>Resume branch operations in the morning in an alternative branch as indicated above.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>7</td>\r\n			<td>BM/IT</td>\r\n			<td>Document the failure noting what worked and what didn&rsquo;t. This should be submitted to the ICT Manager so that lessons learnt can be integrated into future plans.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923334\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635242\"></a>1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scenario 3 &ndash;Failure of backup power supply</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>As with any machine the risk of failure is present and should be considered. While inverters may be reliable most of the time it is possible that they fail when we need them most. The following tables outline the procedures that should be followed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923335\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635243\"></a>1.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recovery Steps- Inverter</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where inverters are installed UPSs are generally not required except on the server. This is because the inverter has no lag time in taking over as the main power supply if mains electrical power is lost. However lack of UPS does mean that if the inverter fails all computers will power off immediately. The only exception is the server which will always have a UPS installed. This will allow for proper shutdown of the server and hopefully prevent any loss of data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The inverters installed at the branches will all be under warranty and should be regularly cleaned to ensure they remain in good working order. However if power is lost and the inverter does not immediately come on the following steps should be taken:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>Branch Manager (BM)</td>\r\n			<td>Take a system backup and start printing account balances; this must be done from the server. Again we have UPS battery supply for at least 15 minutes.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>Contact ICT Manager and report the fault.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3</td>\r\n			<td>ICT Manager / Administration department</td>\r\n			<td>Contacts external technical support and logs an emergency call. Sends ICT support to branch if available.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4</td>\r\n			<td>BM</td>\r\n			<td>Prioritize on holding credit committee meetings for approval of loan applications.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>CSA</td>\r\n			<td>Prioritize on processing loan corrections, funds transfers, client transfers, portfolio transfers</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923336\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635245\"></a>1.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scenario 3- Server failure</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923337\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635246\"></a>1.4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Description</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each branch has a specific Local Area Network (LAN) Class C non-routable IP addressing scheme. Network loss can be partial as in affecting a single device or slow unusable network or completely off. In extreme cases, due to fire, floods or some other natural disaster the branch building and contents are lost or no longer functional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In whichever case, the user will report the case to the ICT helpdesk even though the ICT helpdesk does real-time monitoring of the network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923338\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635250\"></a>1.4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Single workstation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>User reports the problem to the ICT helpdesk through phone, email or any means available. The ICT helpdesk troubleshoots the problem and provides a solution. Such a solution could be repair of a data/voice point, replacement of patch codes, or re-installation of a package or making arrangements to deliver the affected PC to head office by courier for repair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923339\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635251\"></a>1.4.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entire Local Area Network at the branch</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Branch manager reports the problem to ICT department, and records in the system register when the system was off. ICT troubleshoots to establish the cause of the problem. If it&rsquo;s a network switch, replacement be sought (always kept in store), transported to branch and installed by a technician.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923340\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635252\"></a>1.4.4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wide Area Network (WAN)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Branch LANs are interconnected into a WAN. A primary connection is provided by Access Kenya through fibre and wireless links while secondary data links are provided by Orange telecom using modem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Service level agreements have been signed with each service provider to guarantee network availability of 99.5%. At the time of updating this DRP, installation has been completed in 80% of the branches. Other branches will be installed in due course. Switching between the primary and secondary links is seamless and the branches should not feel any downtime due failure of one link.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>Branch</td>\r\n			<td>Report connection that is slow or completely off.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Monitor availability and quality of WAN connection.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Troubleshoot cause of poor quality or link downtime.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Liaise with ISP to resolve the problem in the shortest possible time.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>ICT department to work with the service provider and have the service restored.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923341\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635253\"></a>1.4.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Head Office Data Centre</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Head Office data centre is connected on three different connections. Fibre (primary connection) and wireless connection as the backup Access Kenya. Zuku fibre is alternative backup connection</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td><strong>Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS):</strong>&nbsp;Power supply to all servers should be through UPSs that enable graceful shutdown of servers in case required. All network devices should be supplied power through a UPS.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td><strong>Network devices:</strong>&nbsp;Backup devices for switches, routers and WAN devices should be maintained. Configurations for network devices should be maintained and both hard copy and softcopy.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Servers:&nbsp;</strong>All critical servers should have at least 2 PSUs, 2 processors, enough RAM, RAID configuration. All disks and PSUs should be hot swappable to enable replacement without shutdown of the servers.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Power supply to the servers should be from two different UPSs to ensure failure of one UPS does not bring down the entire system.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>5</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td><strong>Backup:</strong>&nbsp;Backups of all servers should be made in accordance with the backup procedures in section 9.2.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>6</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td><strong>Humidity and Temperature Control:&nbsp;</strong>This should at all times be maintained at appropriate levels for the proper operation of the servers. Reference should be made to the BCP in case of failure of the AC.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc424923342\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635254\"></a>1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scenario 5- Loss of building</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923343\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635255\"></a>1.5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Description</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Due to a fire or some other natural disaster the branch building and contents are lost or no longer functional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a name=\"_Toc424923344\"></a><a name=\"_Toc349635256\"></a>1.5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recovery Steps</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Step</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Who</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td>Provide computers and tablets to branch staff at the alternative location that they will be operating at.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>ICT</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Follow procedures as stated in the Business Continuity Plan</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>(BCP) until such a time normal operations are restored.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3</td>\r\n			<td>BM/ICT</td>\r\n			<td>Document the failure noting what worked and what didn&rsquo;t. This should be submitted to the ICT Manager so that lessons learnt can be integrated into future plans.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc424923345\"></a><a name=\"_Toc359900425\"></a><a name=\"_Toc35