nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Oversight............................................................................................................. 7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Self Assessment.................................................................................................. 7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Proceedings at BoD Meetings............................................................................... 7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reporting Obligations to the BoD.......................................................................... 9</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sub-Committees of the Board of Directors............................................................... 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Audit Committee........................................................................................... 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Formation and regularity of meetings................................................................... 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Responsibilities of the AC................................................................................... 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AC&rsquo;s authorities and duties:................................................................................. 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Risk Management Committee (RMC).............................................................. 12</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Formation and regularity of its meetings............................................................... 12</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; RALCO&rsquo;s authorities and duties:........................................................................... 12</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reports to be reviewed by the RALCO................................................................. 13</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The HR Committee (HRC).................................................................................... 13</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HRC&rsquo;s formation and regularity of its meeting....................................................... 13</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HRC Committee&#39;s authorities and duties:.............................................................. 13</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Management Team (MT).................................................................................... 14</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Composition and work distribution of the MT........................................................ 14</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MT Meetings and Items for discussion................................................................. 15</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within the Institution there is one Department that is wholly independent of the MT and which derives its authority directly from a committee of the Board of Directors:............................................................................ 15</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Asset and Liabilities Committee (ALCO)................................................................... 16</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Conflict of Interest.................................................................................................. 16</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Board of Directors.............................................................................................. 16</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management Team.............................................................................................. 17</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other Employees................................................................................................ 17</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 1: Board performance evaluation........................................................................... 18</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc143659248\"></a><a name=\"_Toc162260182\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263143\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210487\"></a>1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Purpose</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>This Governance Manual provides an overview of the organization and the philosophies, structures and methods by which the Institution is governed. It will provide a framework for the management of risk throughout the institution and take a holistic approach to risk management across the whole of the business.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263144\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210488\"></a>2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scope</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The Manual is to be used throughout the Institution and is designed to help Board Directors, the Management Team (MT) as well as all employees as well as all employees. It will be of particular use to the Auditors (Internal and External) and all other stakeholders including lenders and Service Providers who wish to understand the Institutions governance structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263145\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210489\"></a>3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Introduction</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263146\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210490\"></a><a name=\"_Toc162260183\"></a>3.1&nbsp; Definition</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>For the purpose of this manual, Institution is defined as Musoni DTM Limited and its subsidiary Musoni Kenya limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Governance</strong>&nbsp;is defined as the distribution of rights and duties among the stakeholders of the organisation. It is a process through which the stakeholders fulfil the Institution&rsquo;s corporate mission and protect the institution&rsquo;s assets over time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Corporate governance, is defined as the set of processes, customs, policies, laws and institutional behaviours affecting the way a corporation is directed, administered or controlled. It provides the checks and balances through which the owners and other stakeholders set the standards of objectives and accountability. Corporate governance includes the relationships among the many stakeholders involved and the goals for which the institution is governed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The principal players are the shareholders, the board of directors and management as well as other stakeholders who include employees, customers, lenders, regulators, suppliers, the environment and the community at large</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The key objectives of designing the corporate governance structure is to warrant the highest degree of transparency and accountability at all levels and to ensure that all officers act in conformity with the objectives of the business and its shareholders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Corporate Governance evolves over time in response to changes in the legal structure, complexity and sophistication of the organisation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Corporate Governance is a process defined by the BoD of the Institution. The Board of Director is aware and agrees on the mechanisms used in order to provide effective governance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The governance structure is designed to incorporate a clear distinction between the various bodies of the Institution, specifically the BoD and the MT. The BoD defines the Institution&rsquo;s commercial policies and the supervision of the institution (&acute;decision controlling&acute;). The Management Team defines the responsibility for the operative business (&acute;decision management&acute;).</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263147\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210492\"></a>3.2&nbsp; Structure of the Institution</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>In line with the laws of Kenya and reflecting the specific character of the Institution, the governance structure consists of the following bodies:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>General Meeting of Shareholders (GMSH) or General Assembly (GA).&nbsp;</strong>This is the highest decision making organ of the Institution. It approves the by-laws and annual financial statements of the company, appoints the external auditors and decides on the allocation of profits and dividends (if any). The GMSH is composed of all the shareholders and the Chairman of the Board of Directors will preside as Chairman at every General Meeting of the Shareholders</li>\r\n	<li>The The Directors are nominated by the Shareholders and appointed by the GMSH. The BoD is subordinated to the GMSH. It has a dual mandate of guiding the institution in achieving its corporate mission and protecting the institutions assets over time. Consequently it is responsible for defining and approving internal policies of the Institution, approving the Strategic Plan and Annual Budget and, importantly, agrees strategies for effective governance.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Audit Committee (AC).&nbsp;</strong>This is a Sub-Committee of the Board and is appointed by the BoD to which it reports. Its functions are defined in this manual and include the review and confirmation of the internal audit charter and the annual audit plan. It recommends to the BoD the appointment of the external auditor, reviews its terms of engagement and receive the activity reports and recommendations of the internal auditor who reports directly to the Audit Committee.</li>\r\n	<li>The<strong>&nbsp;Risk Management, Asset and Liability Committee (RALCO)&nbsp;</strong>is a Sub-Committee of the Board and is appointed by the BoD to which it reports. Its objective is to provide oversight of a sound risk management system that is commensurate with the Institution&rsquo;s capacity and its acceptance of risk taking. Its functions are defined in this manual and include the review of management&rsquo;s performance with regard to risk management and compliance and to offer support and advise the BoD on the implementation and monitoring of the risk management policy. It also reviews reports prepared by the managements Asset and Liabilities Committee (ALCO).</li>\r\n	<li>The<strong>&nbsp;HR Committee</strong>&nbsp;is a Sub-Committee of the Board and is appointed by the BoD to which it reports. This Committee shall monitor and guarantee the transparency of appointing, renewing and replacing the members of the BoD and the CEO; evaluate the effectiveness of the BoD as a whole, as well as each member separately; evaluate the performance of the members of the MT; ensure the transparency of the policies on the compensation of the board members&#39; and the salaries, rewards and compensations of the MT. These policies need to be in line with the Institution&rsquo;s objectives and strategy.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Management Team (MT).&nbsp;</strong>The Management Team is the principal executive body of the Institution. The members of the MT are appointed by the BoD to which it reports. The MT makes policy proposals to the BoD and is held responsible for the implementation of the BoD decisions. It carries the overall responsibility for the Institution&rsquo;s operative business. It is composed of the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and a minimum of two other members, up to a maximum of five (including the CEO), all of whom are appointed by the BoD. Currently (June 2015) the CEO; CFO (Chief Financial Officer),COO (Chief Operations Officer); IT Manager and CHRO (Chief HR Officer)&nbsp; are members of the MT. The MT makes its decisions in the MT-Meeting, to which the Internal Auditor and Risk Manager are invited as a non-voting attendees to provide technical advice and counsel.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Assets and Liabilities Committee (ALCO).&nbsp;</strong>This Committee is responsible for the management of the Institution&rsquo;s exposure to risks and for providing active oversight of the risk management system on a day-to-day basis. The ALCO executes its work within the framework of policies and limits. The ALCO reviews the Institution&rsquo;s exposure to risk and decides on measures to steer the Institution&rsquo;s risk within the provide framework by the BoD. The responsibility for ALCO includes all risk categories including, but not limited to credit risk, operational risk, strategic, financial and liquidity risks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO is further responsible for the Institution&rsquo;s obligation to report to the Central Bank of Kenya.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO Members are determined by the BoD, based on their function. They include the members of the MT as voting members, with the CEO as the Chairman of the ALCO. &nbsp;In addition, the Risk Manager is the Secretary of the ALCO as a non-voting member. The Internal Auditor is a permanent, non-voting guest of the ALCO. The members of the ALCO can invite further guests to the meeting. The ALCO is subordinated to and reports to the Risk Management and Asset and Liability Committee of the Board of Directors on all material matters arising from its review and monitoring functions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263148\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210494\"></a><a name=\"_Toc162260187\"></a>3.3&nbsp; General Meeting of Shareholders (GMSH).</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The by-laws of the GMSH are provided in the Memorandum and Articles of Association (MEMARTS) of the Institution. The respective latest version of the MEMARTS is the basis for the Institution&rsquo;s governance structure. An attachment describes the latest version of the MEMARTS.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263164\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210499\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263149\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263150\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263151\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263152\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263153\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263154\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263155\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263156\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263157\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263158\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263159\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263160\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263161\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263162\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263163\"></a>4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Board of Directors (BoD).</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board of Directors has a dual mandate:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>To guide the institution in fulfilling its corporate mission</li>\r\n	<li>To protect the Institution&rsquo;s assets over time</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD needs to fully comprehend its mandate before it can discuss tactics and strategies for effective governance.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263165\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210500\"></a>4.1&nbsp; Responsibilities of the BoD</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD&rsquo;s has several responsibilities which can be grouped in five categories:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Legal obligations</li>\r\n	<li>Strategic direction</li>\r\n	<li>Fiduciary</li>\r\n	<li>Oversight</li>\r\n	<li>Self-assessment</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263166\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210501\"></a>4.2&nbsp; Legal obligations</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD ensures that the Institution fulfils its legal obligations and protects it from unnecessary liability and legal action. It monitors the Institution&rsquo;s compliance with its MEMARTS, internal policies and procedures as well as pertinent government rules and regulations including statutory and regulatory requirements laid down by the Central Bank of Kenya</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263167\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210502\"></a>4.3&nbsp; Strategic Direction</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The board ensures that the Institution&rsquo;s mission is well defined, reviewed periodically and respected. A crucial responsibility, therefore, is to ensure that the institution has a formal mission statement that clarifies the institution&rsquo;s main purpose of being. It provides institution direction that is conducive to the fulfilment of the mission. In recognising that the mission may change and evolve over time, the BoD will review the mission periodically and make changes in response to a changing environment and amended priorities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD ensures effective planning. The MT assumes responsibility for preparing strategic, business and other action plans, the BoD oversees the process, provides guidance and input into three areas: i) Charting the institutions strategic course, ii) Setting broad operational policies, iii) Resolving strategic issues as they arise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The board works to enhance the image of the institution and plays an important part in shaping the institutions image, prestige and credibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263168\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210503\"></a>4.4&nbsp; Fiduciary</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board serves as the institutions steward. It is the ultimate repository of the power and property invested in the institution by third parties. The BoD is entrusted to protect their property and ensure that it is managed in a manner that is consistent with agreed values and goals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD should also ensure that the institution has adequate resources to implement the agreed plans. There are two components to this responsibility:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Understanding the institution&rsquo;s short and long term financial position in relation to its strategic plan, and</li>\r\n	<li>Taking necessary actions to secure the necessary resources in order to implement that plan</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition the BoD balances the short term pressures on financial performance with an awareness and understanding of what is needed to guarantee the institutions long term viability</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263169\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210504\"></a>4.5&nbsp; Oversight</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The BoD governs, but does not manage the institution. The BoD provides direction to management in the area of strategic planning and oversees that the MT carries out the strategic plan. The MT assumes operational authority and ensures implementation of the institution&rsquo;s program of activities as agreed upon with the BoD.</li>\r\n	<li>The BoD appoints and oversees the performance of the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of the Institution and of the other members of the MT. The BoD appraises the performance of the MT.</li>\r\n	<li>The BoD monitors operational and business performance and in order to ensure that the Institution uses its resources effectively the board monitors the performance of the portfolio, operations and financial indicators. It does this through frequent and transparent reports, regular board meetings, internal and external audit reports and any other instruments.</li>\r\n	<li>The BoD evaluates the institutions performance against its peer institutions, both locally and globally.</li>\r\n	<li>The BoD assesses and responds to internal and external risks and establishes early warning systems and ensures that the Institution operates prudently in the face of these challenges.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263170\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210505\"></a>4.6&nbsp; Self Assessment</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The BoD shall regularly assess its own performance. The following assessments are to be submitted to the Central Bank not later than three months after the end of each financial year (annex 1 provides the format for this assessment):</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>An annual self assessment questionnaire of each Board member</li>\r\n	<li>An annual self assessment Board evaluation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc301210506\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263171\"></a>4.7&nbsp; Proceedings at BoD Meetings</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The BoD shall meet at least once every quarter.</li>\r\n	<li>The quorum necessary for the transaction of the business of the BoD shall be fixed by the Directors and unless so fixed shall be five (5) Directors present either personally or by Alternate (Article 108 of MEMARTS),</li>\r\n	<li><a name=\"_Toc214077518\"></a>&nbsp;A written resolution signed by all Directors shall be as valid and effectual as if it has been duly passed at a meeting of the BoD</li>\r\n	<li>Any Director shall be entitled to participate in a meeting of the BoD in which he or she is not physically present, by telephone or video conference or similar electronic means and the chairman of such meeting shall record such Director&rsquo;s observations in the minutes of such meeting.</li>\r\n	<li>Written notice of each meeting of the BoD or a committee shall be given to the Directors and their alternates, if any, at least fifteen (15) days in advance of such meeting (except in the case where all the Directors agree to a shorter notice).Such notice to include an Agenda together with necessary information and supporting documents</li>\r\n	<li>Resolutions of the BoD regarding the Reserved Matters set forth below may only be passed by the BoD with the affirmative vote of the majority of the members of the BoD in a meeting where at least four Directors are present.</li>\r\n	<li>the hiring, firing or changing the compensation, including approving any option grants of (i) any senior manager or C-Level position of the Company/ Musoni Kenya or any of its Subsidiaries or of (ii) any employee with an annual salary in excess of the local equivalent of KSH 5,000,000;</li>\r\n	<li>Transfer or secondment of any employee to any Affiliate of the Company whether locally or abroad;</li>\r\n	<li>the incurrence of indebtedness (liability on the balance sheet) or guarantee of any indebtedness, by the Company/ Musoni Kenya or any Subsidiary of the Company/ Musoni Kenya;</li>\r\n	<li>the creation of any mortgage, charge, pledge, lien (other than liens arising by operation of law or in the normal and ordinary course of trading) or other encumbrance in relation to the assets of the Company/ Musoni Kenya or any subsidiary or the giving of any guarantee or indemnity (other than standard trade guarantees or indemnities given in the ordinary course of business and customary for persons carrying out the business);</li>\r\n	<li>the granting of any general power of attorney or similar authority;</li>\r\n	<li>(other than in the ordinary course of business) the entering into of any joint venture, agency, distribution, production or other similar arrangement or agreement that is not terminable without penalty or 3 months notice or some shorter period;</li>\r\n	<li>to enter into any contract or transaction except in the ordinary and proper course of the Business on arms length terms, including entering into contracts with Affiliates of the Company;</li>\r\n	<li>to enter into any contracts with Musoni Kenya Limited;</li>\r\n	<li>proposals to the general meeting of shareholders of the Company/ Musoni Kenya with regard to the adoption of the annual Budget and variation of greater than 20% in Budgeted annual expenditures;</li>\r\n	<li>the alteration of the Company&rsquo;s/Musoni Kenya&rsquo;s Fiscal Year;</li>\r\n	<li>nominations for the appointment or removal of the Auditors to the general meeting of shareholders of the Company/ Musoni Kenya;</li>\r\n	<li>proposals to the general meeting of shareholders of the Company/ Musoni Kenya for the adoption of, or subsequent alteration to, the accounting policies of the Company;</li>\r\n	<li>the entry into any contract which (i) has a minimum duration in excess of 12 months or notice period to terminate such contract in excess of 3 months or (ii) imposes an obligation upon the Company to make payment(s) in excess of KSH 1,000,000 or (iii) may be reasonably considered to be abnormal, unusual or outside of the Company&rsquo;s ordinary business for any reason;</li>\r\n	<li>the instigation, settlement or abandonment of any litigation other than against clients of the Company/ Musoni Kenya or its subsidiaries, other than the taking of legal measures which cannot be delayed, where the contingent liability and/or related costs exceed KSH 1,000,000;</li>\r\n	<li>to make any investment inconsistent with any investment policy approved by the Board of Directors;</li>\r\n	<li>to sell, assign, license, pledge or encumber material technology or intellectual property, other than licenses granted in the ordinary course of business;</li>\r\n	<li>Approval of any loans extended in excess of such amounts and limits as may be set by the Board from time to time;</li>\r\n	<li>Establishing pension schemes and granting pension rights in excess of those arising from existing arrangements;</li>\r\n	<li>Approving employee share option schemes; and</li>\r\n	<li>Any amendment to the Financial Projections.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Each committee of the Board shall consist of at least three board members, at least two of which shall be Investor appointed Directors. The Board of Directors shall be entitled, at its own discretion, to create sub-committees.</li>\r\n	<li>Any Director may with the consent of the BoD appoint any person, whether a member of the Company or not, to be an alternate director of the Company, and may at any time remove any alternate director of the Company so appointed by him from office provided that the consent of the BoD will not be required if the person so appointed as alternate is a Director...</li>\r\n	<li>An alternate director shall be entitled to receive notices of all meetings of the BoD and to attend and vote as a Director at any such meeting at which the Director appointing him is not personally present.</li>\r\n	<li>Every appointment and removal of an alternate director shall be effected by notice in writing to the Company under the hand of the Director making or revoking such appointment.</li>\r\n	<li>As long as the Institution has not reached break-even on an annual basis, it will not pay any Directors&rsquo; fees, nor reimburse any expenses incurred by the Directors in relation to their participation in Board meetings, with the exception of a fee per board meeting in conformity with market practice payable by the Company to independent local board members upon their attendance of such board meeting.</li>\r\n	<li>Once the Institution has reached break-even on an annual basis, the following remuneration policy will apply in respect of Directors&rsquo; fees&nbsp; and reimbursements by the Institution of expenses incurred by Directors in relation to their participation in Board meetings: (i) Directors shall receive, Directors&rsquo; fees as authorized by the Shareholders in General Meeting; (ii) Directors reasonable hotel accommodation shall be reimbursed; (iii) Directors&rsquo; airplane tickets shall be reimbursed for economy class airplane tickets</li>\r\n	<li>A Board or Institution Secretary may be appointed by the Board for such term, at such remuneration and upon such conditions as it may think fit and the appointment of any Secretary may be terminated by the Board. The provisions of sections 178 to 180 inclusive of the Companies Act shall be observed (requiring minimum qualifications with possibility of an exception being granted).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263172\"></a>4.8&nbsp; Reporting Obligations to the BoD</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The Management Team will routinely issue to the members of the BoD the following information at the following periodicity:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Audited year-end financial statements of the Company, not later than 60 days after termination of the respective business year;</li>\r\n	<li>Quarterly (unaudited) financial and operational statements, including revisions of the full year latest estimates and quarterly key information in respect of the Company&rsquo;s activities and operational/market developments within 30 days after the end of each quarter of the Financial Year</li>\r\n	<li>An annual budget and (amended) 5-year business- and operating plan, including strategy for growth, market and company analysis, proposed investments, profit and loss statement, balance sheet and cash flow forecasts and explanatory notes at least six weeks prior to the commencement of the new financial year</li>\r\n	<li>Half-yearly financial projections within 30 days after the end of each half of the Financial Year.</li>\r\n	<li>Post Completion Action Plan within 30 days after the Completion Date. The Post Completion Action Plan shall include actions related to all relevant outcomes of the due diligence processes. The Company shall execute the Post Completion Action Plan as to be agreed with Investors.</li>\r\n	<li>The Company will inform the Investors promptly on any deviation from the Financial Projections.</li>\r\n	<li>The Company will furnish Directors such other information relating to the financial condition, business, prospects or corporate affairs of the Company as they may from time to time request.</li>\r\n	<li>Annual Social and Environmental Performance Report evaluating the social and environmental performance of the Company during the previous business year, not later than six months after the termination of the respective business year;</li>\r\n	<li>Copies of (i) all management letters of accountants commenting on, without limitation, the adequacy of the financial control procedures, policies and controls for anti-money laundering and combating the financing of terrorism, accounting systems and management information system of the Company; (ii) notification of material litigation, including, without limitation, any litigation, administrative, regulatory or criminal investigations or proceedings or freezing of assets by a government authority involving the Company, and / or its employees with regard to money laundering or financing of terrorisms, and (iii) copies of all material filings made with governmental agencies;</li>\r\n	<li>Any additional reports on the operations of the Company as reasonably requested by the members of the BoD and any other information reasonably requested by the members of the BoD or to which they are entitled to.</li>\r\n	<li>The Company undertakes to establish by 31st&nbsp;July 2015 (the &ldquo;Final AML/CTF Compliance Date&rdquo;) an adequate Anti-Money-Laundering (AML) and Combat-Terrorist-Financing (CTF) mechanism in line with the 40+9 recommendations<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=21&amp;action=edit#_ftn1\" name=\"_ftnref1\">[1]</a>&nbsp;of FATF-GAFI, including:</li>\r\n	<li>general AML policies, practices and procedures, including quarterly reporting;</li>\r\n	<li>risk assessment;</li>\r\n	<li>Know-Your-Customer, due diligence and enhanced due diligence;</li>\r\n	<li>reportable transactions and prevention and detection of transactions with illegally obtained funds;</li>\r\n	<li>transactions monitoring;</li>\r\n	<li>AML training;</li>\r\n	<li>The Company and the Shareholders agree to cooperate in good faith to implement such an AML/CTF System as a priority matter within the 90 days of the effectiveness of the shareholders agreement. KfW shall confirm in writing its satisfaction with such system after which the exit option shall no longer apply</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263173\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210507\"></a>5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sub-Committees of the Board of Directors</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp; Microfinance (Deposit Taking Microfinance Institutions) Regulations of 2008 requires that every board shall constitute at least an Audit Committee and Credit Committee and the board committees shall meet at least once in a quarter, to deliberate on the affairs and financial condition of the institution and provide oversight and guidance to the management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MEMARTS state that each board committee shall consist of at least three (3) Board members, at least two (2) of which shall be Directors appointed by either KfW, Access Africa Fund, LLC, Oikocredit and/or Grameen Foundation USA (as long as they remain Members).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Regulations stipulate that neither the CEO nor Chairman of the BoD can be members of the Audit or Credit Committee, but they can attend such meetings by invitation for consultation</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263174\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210508\"></a>5.1&nbsp; The Audit Committee</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263175\"></a>5.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Formation and regularity of meetings</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Audit Committee (AC) shall have a minimum of three members, and the Board Chairman should not be one of them. The AC Chairman should be an independent member with at least one member who has academic qualification and/or practical experience in accounting and finance.</li>\r\n	<li>Members of the AC are appointed and removed by the BoD.</li>\r\n	<li>The quorum for meetings shall be at least two-thirds of the committee members, where at least one attendee must be a non-executive director of the institution</li>\r\n	<li>The AC shall be subordinated to, and shall report to, the BoD.</li>\r\n	<li>The committee shall convene four meetings per year and the minutes of those meetings shall be presented to the next available BoD Meeting for formal adoption</li>\r\n	<li>The internal procedures of the AC shall be defined by the AC members and agreed with the BoD in conformity with the laws of Kenya.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263176\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210509\"></a>5.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Responsibilities of the AC</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Review financial reports and control and supervision systems, the scope, results and extent of internal and external auditing, review the accounting issues that affect essentially the financial statements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263177\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210511\"></a><a name=\"_Toc225584128\"></a>5.1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AC&rsquo;s authorities and duties:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The AC shall be entitled to get any information to practice its work. It may invite to its meetings any experienced or specialized person to consult his/her opinion, and any member of the board or executive management; the internal auditing director shall be invited to the committee&#39;s meeting.</li>\r\n	<li>Review the regular financial statements before submitting them to the boards, and make recommendations on them to the board; follow up the accounting issues that essentially affect the financial statements in order to secure that the financial reports are fair and transparent.</li>\r\n	<li>The AC shall assess the effectiveness and efficiency of internal control and supervision systems; the committee shall be responsible, among other things, to:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Assess the effectiveness and efficiency of internal auditing function and make sure that the instructions in effect issued by the relevant bodies are complied with.</li>\r\n	<li>Assess the effectiveness and efficiency of the scope of internal audit.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Review the results of reports by internal audit and make sure that the necessary measures have been taken.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Review and approve the auditing plans proposed by the internal audit.</li>\r\n	<li>Recommend appointing, transferring and dismissing the Head of internal audit, determine his/her compensations and evaluate his/her performance.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The AC shall have the power to contact directly and meet the external auditor without the management attendance once at least annually. In this regard, the committee&#39;s responsibility shall include among other things:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Recommend appointing and dismissing the external auditor, determine his/her compensations and evaluate his/her performance.</li>\r\n	<li>Assess the external auditor&#39;s objectivity and independence.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Review and approve the appointment letter.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Approve the possibility that the external auditor provides services other than regular auditing, and make sure that this will not affect the external auditor&#39;s independency.</li>\r\n	<li>Review the results of external auditing reports and supervisory authorities&#39; reports, and make sure that the necessary measures have been taken in their regard.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The AC shall review the operations with the relevant stakeholders and inform the BoD on them.</li>\r\n	<li>The AC shall review the extent of compliance with the laws and regulations and abidance by the Institution&rsquo;s policies and bylaws.</li>\r\n	<li>The AC shall convene regular meetings with the external auditor once at least per year, and twice at least with the internal auditor. The internal and external auditors may request meeting the committee whenever the work necessitates that.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263178\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210516\"></a>5.2&nbsp; The Risk Management Committee (RMC)</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<em>Risk Management and Asset and Liabilities Committee (RALCO)&nbsp;</em>incorporates the legally required Credit Committee, is a separate Committee of the Board and is appointed by the BoD to which it reports. Its objective is to provide oversight of a sound risk management system that is commensurate with the Institution&rsquo;s capacity and its acceptance of risk taking. Its function is to review the MT performance with regard to risk management of credit, market, liquidity, operation, compliance, reputation and other risks, and to offer support and advise the BoD on the implementation and monitoring of the risk management policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263179\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210517\"></a>5.2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Formation and regularity of its meetings</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>This RALCO should consist of at least three members; two (2) of which shall be Directors appointed by either KfW, Access Africa Fund, LLC, Oikocredt and/or Grameen Foundation USA (as long as they remain Members)</li>\r\n	<li>Members of the RALCO are appointed and removed by the BoD.</li>\r\n	<li>The RALCO members shall elect a chairperson among themselves who shall be a non-executive director.</li>\r\n	<li>The quorum for meetings shall be at least two-thirds of the committee members, where at least one attendee must be a non-executive director of the institution.</li>\r\n	<li>The RALCO shall be subordinated to, and shall report to, the BoD</li>\r\n	<li>This RALCO shall convene four meetings at least per year and the minutes of those meetings shall be presented to the next available BoD Meeting for formal adoption..</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263180\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210518\"></a>5.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; RALCO&rsquo;s authorities and duties:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>This RACLO shall review all risk management strategies and policies before presenting them for adoption by the BoD, and make sure that these strategies and policies are implemented.</li>\r\n	<li>Review the regular reports on the nature and size of the risks that the Institution is subject to, and the risk management activities.</li>\r\n	<li>This RALCO shall report regularly to the BoD, and provide statistics on the risks that the Institution is facing and changes and developments that occur to the risks of the Institution.</li>\r\n	<li>Review ceilings of risks and align risk appetite and limits to the Mission and Vision of Musoni.</li>\r\n	<li>The RALCO is responsible for presenting emergency plans and managing crisis that the institution might ace by coordinating with the MT.</li>\r\n	<li>Specifically in relation to credit risk the RALCO should</li>\r\n	<li>review and oversee the overall lending policy, including monitoring and risk management tools;</li>\r\n	<li>review loan applications based on established discretionary approval limits;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>review lending practices and quality of loan portfolio;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>ensure that there are effective procedures and adequate resources to identify and mitigate credit risk;</li>\r\n	<li>monitor and evaluate all issues that may materially impact on the present and future quality of the loan portfolio and credit risk management;</li>\r\n	<li>delegate and review lending limits to the sanctioning arms of the institution;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>ensure adequate provisions for loans and advances, bad and doubtful debts and write off policy;</li>\r\n	<li>conduct loan reviews independent of any person or committee responsible for sanctioning credit;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>ensure that the credit policy and risk lending limits are reviewed at least once on an annual basis and as and when the environment so dictates; and</li>\r\n	<li>set limits on lending exposure in line with the institution&rsquo;s risk management programs and market conditions</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263181\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210519\"></a>5.2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reports to be reviewed by the RALCO</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All Financial and Non-Financial Reports submitted by Management to its monthly ALCO meetings including, but not limited to\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Credit Risk</li>\r\n		<li>Liquidity Risk</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Operational Risks</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Compliance with Regulatory Requirements</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Minutes of Monthly ALCO meetings held by Management indicating measures taken to monitor and control ALL risks throughout the institution.</li>\r\n	<li>All new or amended product approval requests from Management</li>\r\n	<li>Results of any tests done on the Disaster Recovery and Business Continuity Plan and/or any incident involving the DRBC Plan</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263182\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210513\"></a>5.3&nbsp; The HR Committee (HRC)</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The HR Committee (HRC) is created to monitor and guarantee the transparency of recruiting, appointing, promoting, contract renewal, performance appraisals and disciplinary procedures (if any) in respect of&nbsp; Senior Managers of the Institution defined as</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The CEO</li>\r\n	<li>Any Manager who is a direct report of the CEO</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any Member of Staff with an annual salary greater than KES 5 million</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The HRC shall be subordinated to, and shall report to the BoD.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263183\"></a><a name=\"_Toc225584139\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210514\"></a>5.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HRC&rsquo;s formation and regularity of its meeting</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>This Committee should consist of at least three (3) non-executive members, ; two (2) of which shall be Directors appointed by either KfW, Access Africa Fund, LLC, Oikocredit and/or Grameen Foundation USA (as long as they remain Members)</li>\r\n	<li>The HRC members shall elect a chairperson among themselves who shall be a non-executive director.</li>\r\n	<li>This Committee shall convene quarterly meetings but may also need to hold ad-hoc meetings (by video conference) to consider promotions and disciplinary issues of a more urgent nature.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263184\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210515\"></a><a name=\"_Toc225584140\"></a>5.3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HRC Committee&#39;s authorities and duties:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Set the requirements and criteria of appointing Senior Management, their performance evaluation and replacement plan and to review Senior Management appointments (including CEO, direct reports to the CEO, and other Managers with an annual salary in excess of KES 5 million (if any) at Head Office) and review reports of exit interviews with them when they leave the institution</li>\r\n	<li>Review recommendations from management for the dismissal of any member of Staff and to recommend to the BoD to dismiss any Senior Manager if (s)he proves to be ineffective and inefficient in performing his/her duties and responsibilities.</li>\r\n	<li>Ensure that clear policies are in place regarding the rewards, compensations, salaries and any other benefits to the members of the Management Team corresponding to their expertise and qualifications.</li>\r\n	<li>To review all HR Policies of the Institution, including the Staff Handbook and to ensure that the employee grievance handling procedures are functional and impartial.</li>\r\n	<li>To review with the CEO, at least once per year, the succession planning policy and process in place</li>\r\n	<li>Meet the Human Resources Manager once at least annually to make sure that the staff appointment and evaluation mechanism and the policy of rewards and salaries are in place, sufficient, fair and clear to attract and maintain qualified people.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263185\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210520\"></a>6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Management Team (MT)</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The Management Team is the principal executive body of the Company. The Management Team is under the direction of the Chief Executive Officer (CEO). The CEO chairs all meetings of the Management Team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Including the CEO, the Management Team shall have a minimum of three (3) and a maximum of six (6) members. The BoD shall decide upon the exact number and composition of the Management Team. One or more of the other members of the Management Team may be appointed to the position of a Deputy Chairman of the MT by the BoD</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CEO shall determine and shall be responsible for any decisions relating to the business of the Company within the limits set by the Articles of Association, and the Laws of Kenya. Within the limits of this general policy, each member of the MT shall be autonomous and shall be responsible for the conduct of the business of his or her department.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MT shall decide on the differences of opinion between its members. Any decision of the MT shall be adopted by simple majority of the members of the MT present at the meeting. If the Management Team is unable to reach a decision, the CEO shall have a second or casting vote. In addition, the CEO may exercise a right of veto where the CEO fundamentally disagrees with the result of a majority vote and would normally exercise that right of veto in favour of maintaining the existing status quo</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263186\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210521\"></a>6.1&nbsp; Composition and work distribution of the MT</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The MT consists of the following members:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Chief Executive Officer (CEO),&nbsp;</strong>heads the MT and carries the overall responsibility for the institution&rsquo;s operative business, including business areas subordinated to other members of the MT. Whilst Branch Managers report directly to the Chief Operating Officer (COO), it is essential to recognise that the CEO will provide direction across the whole Institution and that Branch Managers mirror the CEO&rsquo;s role in their own branches.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Chief Operating Officer (COO)</strong>&nbsp;carries MT-level responsibility for all operations including both the loan portfolio and the deposit portfolio (one the deposit taking licence is issued) all credit and non-credit products and services across the whole of the network. Consequently the COO manages and supervises all Branch Managers and all Wealth Creation Officers throughout the Institution. The responsibilities, cover both the Front and Middle Office so that the COO will be equally responsible for quantity and quality of the portfolios and will consequently chair the Head Office Credit Committee and delegate authority to Branch Credit Committees.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Chief Financial Officer (CFO)&nbsp;</strong>carries MT level responsibility for the company&rsquo;s finance, accountancy premises and infrastructure, logistics, administration and other corporate functions, which include budgeting and planning, fiscal policies and procedures, financial systems and internal controls. Within the organization, the CFO carries responsibility for the whole of the Back Office and support functions including all Bank accounts and cash operations of the Institution. The CFO is the Principal Point of Contact (PPOC) with the Central Bank on all Regulatory and Reporting issues and for obtaining the necessary approvals for the Institution to do business.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Chief Human Resources Officer (CHRO)&nbsp;</strong>is responsible for all HR matters across the institution supporting and facilitating the recruitment, development and retention of qualified and motivated staff; institutionalization and implementation of the Musoni Performance Management system; and all matters relating to the HR Policies and Procedures;.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Risk Manager (RM)&nbsp;</strong>is responsible for managing risks to the organization, its employees, customers, reputation, assets and interests of stakeholders in a variety of sectors including enterprise risk, corporate governance, regulatory, operational, business continuity, information and security, technology, market and credit risk. The RM will identify and assess threats, put in place plans for mitigation and decide how to avoid, reduce or transfer risks.</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>IT Manager (ITM)&nbsp;</strong>is responsible for deployment, monitoring, maintenance, development, upgrade, and support of all IT systems of the institution including but not limited to the Musoni System, Emails, Website, operatings systems, software applications, databases and IT peripherals.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263188\"></a><a name=\"_Toc301210522\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425263187\"></a>6.2&nbsp; MT Meetings and Items for discussion</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Management meetings will be held at least monthly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No formal record of the verbatim discussions will be taken but an Issue Log prepared of Issues discussed and a note of decisions taken together with Agreed Action Points (including who is handling the matter and when the task is to be completed).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When appropriate and for particular items on the Agenda, members of MT are free to invite other Staff from their Departments as observers and advisors but with no voting rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Head of Internal Auditor &nbsp;and the Risk Manager are invited as a non-voting attendees to provide technical advice and counsel.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a name=\"_Toc301210523\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239403918\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239415940\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239436180\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239403919\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239415941\"></a><a name=\"_Toc239436181\"></a>&nbsp;<strong>Department independent of the Management Team</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263189\"></a>Within the Institution there is one Department that is wholly independent of the MT and which derives its authority directly from a committee of the Board of Directors:</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Internal Audit Department</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Internal Audit Department is an independent review function set up within the Institution as a service to the BoD including all Board Sub Committees and all levels of management. The Internal Audit function is responsible for effective review of all aspects of risk management and control throughout Musoni&rsquo;s activities. The Internal Audit department fulfils this role by conducting independent appraisals highlighting identified risks which lead to a report with findings and recommendations addressed, as appropriate, to (a) the levels of management who need to know and those who are capable of ensuring that action is taken as necessary and (b) the Audit Committee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Internal Audit Department is independent of the activities it audits to ensure the unbiased judgment essential to its proper conduct and impartial advice to management. It does not perform line tasks; neither does it have any direct responsibility for, nor authority over the activities it reviews.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Internal Audit provides independent confirmation on the effectiveness and efficiency of the risk management system for compliance with policies and procedures. Internal audit should therefore monitor key risks identified through the risk management system. Internal Audit reports directly to the Internal Audit Committee. The Internal Auditor is invited to attend meetings of the MT and of ALCO as a nonvoting attendee. The Internal Audit Manager is the head of the department. A number of audit officers support the work of the department appropriate to the size and complexity of the Institution</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263190\"></a>8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Asset and Liabilities Committee (ALCO)</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>ALCO</strong>&nbsp;is responsible for the management of the Institution&rsquo;s exposure to risks and for providing active oversight of the risk management system on a day-to-day basis. The ALCO executes its work within the framework of policies and limits, specifically the Liquidity and Fund Management Manual, Lending and Credit manual, and other internal policies</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO reviews the Institution&rsquo;s exposure to risk and decides on measures to steer the Institution&rsquo;s risk within the provided framework by the BoD. The responsibility for ALCO includes all risk categories including, but not limited to:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Credit Risk:</li>\r\n	<li>Credit Risk related to individual exposures which have been entered into through the Institution&rsquo;s credit process</li>\r\n	<li>Portfolio risk related to concentrations of risk in specific products, sectors, regions, or any other relevant criteria</li>\r\n	<li>Credit Risk related to exposures to external counterparties such as other financial Institutions where the Institution deposits its fund</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Market Risk:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Financial risks including interest rate risk and currency risks or any other risks which relate to the development of market process</li>\r\n		<li>Liquidity risk</li>\r\n		<li>Funding risks</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Operational Risk:</li>\r\n	<li>Risk of losses resulting from inadequate or failed internal processes, people, systems or from external events</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO is further responsible for the Institution&rsquo;s obligation to report to the Central Bank of Kenya and will be responsible for the delivery of requested information to the Risk Management Committee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>.ALCO&rsquo;s formation and regularity of its meeting</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO members are determined by the BoD, based on their function. They include the members of the MT as voting members, with the CEO as the Chairman of the ALCO. In addition, the Risk Manager is the Secretary of the ALCO as a non-voting member. The Internal Auditor is a non-voting guest of the ALCO. The members of the ALCO can invite further guests to the meeting. The ALCO is subordinated to and reports to the Risk Management Committee of the BoD on all material matters arising from its review and monitoring functions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO will establish its own Terms of Reference which shall be presented to the Risk Management Committee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>ALCO Meetings and Items for discussion</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>ALCO meetings will be held at least monthly and follow an agenda that is set in the Terms of Reference in details.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263191\"></a>9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Conflict of Interest</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263192\"></a>9.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Board of Directors</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>A Board member shall not participate in the discussions and decision-taking process on a subject or transaction in relation to which he has a conflict of interest. A Board member has a conflict of interests whenever:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>He has directly or indirectly a financial or non-financial interest in a company with which the institution intends to enter into a transaction</li>\r\n	<li>He has a partner, child, parent or relative with a financial or non-financial interest in a company with which the institution intends to enter into a transaction</li>\r\n	<li>He is a member of the Board, Managing Board or Supervisory Board or has a similar status with a company with which the company intends to enter into a transaction.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Each Board member shall immediately report any potential conflict to the Chair of the Board, providing all information relevant to the conflict.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263193\"></a>9.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management Team</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Any member of the Management Team of the Institution shall at all appropriate times inform the BoD of any Conflict of Interest or potential Conflict of Interest which he/she perceives to exist or which it reasonably anticipates might arise between the interests of the Institution and him-/herself, or between the Institution and Musoni BV or any other Shareholder. The BoD shall determine whether a conflict of interest exists, and, if so, shall resolve such conflict of interest in its sole, absolute discretion.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263194\"></a>9.1.3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other Employees</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Any other employee of the Institution shall inform the Management Team of any conflict of interest or potential Conflict of Interest which it perceives to exist or which it reasonably anticipates might arise between the interests of the Institution and him-/herself. The Management Team shall determine whether a conflict of interest exists, and, if so, shall resolve such conflict of interest in conformity with the applicable rules and procedures defined in the Institution&rsquo;s staff regulations, which shall be developed by the CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425263195\"></a>Annex 1: Board performance evaluation</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The aim of the Board performance evaluation is to identify whether the board is performing well as a board, and how it might improve, and to assess the performance of individual directors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The evaluation is in two parts - an evaluation of the performance of the board and then an evaluation of individual director.&nbsp; Evaluating the performance of the board is not the same as evaluating individual director performance. The purpose of the board evaluation is to look at the board as a whole, although a side benefit may be that individual board members gain appreciation for the roles and responsibilities of directorship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Board Review</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Schedule:&nbsp; Annually, in line with the fiscal year.&nbsp;&nbsp; Complete the process in time for review at the April next board meeting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Process</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Each director completes Board self-evaluation</li>\r\n	<li>Chairman scores and summarizes and gives feedback to the Board</li>\r\n	<li>Board discusses and agrees on areas for improvement and goals for the coming year</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Evaluation of effectiveness of Musoni Kenya&#39;s Board of Directors</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Director&#39;s name:____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date of completing form:____________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use standard evaluation form with ratings 1-5</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1: Unsatisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2: Partly satisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3: Fully satisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4: Superior</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5: Outstanding</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is room for comment after each rating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1. How would you rate Musoni Kenya&#39;s Board governance processes?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2. How would you rate the Board&rsquo;s understanding of Musoni Kenya&#39;s vision, aims and programmes of work?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3. Are the roles of the Chair, other Directors and the Management team clear?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4. To what extent does the Board focus on strategy, policy and governance rather than on management issues?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>5. Does the Board represent the organisation effectively to its stakeholders?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>6. Does the Board monitor performance effectively and evaluate progress toward strategic goals?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>7. Do the Board members work together effectively?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>8. Does the Board have a good working relationship with the Management Team?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>9. How effectively does the Board evaluate, challenge, motivate and develop the Management Team?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>10. Other comments</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Director&#39;s Review</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Process</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Directors complete self-evaluation</li>\r\n	<li>All evaluation given to the Chairman</li>\r\n	<li>Chairman discusses with each Director</li>\r\n	<li>Chairman self-evaluation given to the Deputy Chairman</li>\r\n	<li>Deputy Chairman discusses with the Chairman</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Director&#39;s Self Review Form</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Director&#39;s name: ________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date of completing form: ________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date last (re)elected to the Board: _________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date joined Board:_____________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Attendance record at Board meetings since last (re)election: __ out of __ meetings</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Self-appraisal of personal effectiveness</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please consider the following points and make your own comments under each question</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1: Unsatisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2: Partly satisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3: Fully satisfactory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4: Superior</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5: Outstanding</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1. How do you rate your contribution to Musoni Kenya&#39;s governance?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2. Do you have sufficient opportunity to read the Board papers and prepare for meetings?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3. Are you a willing and enthusiastic promoter of Musoni Kenya Ltd?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4. Do you work effectively with the Chair of the Board, other Board members and the Management Team?</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>5. Comments</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>FATF recommendations of 2012 can be found under: http://<a href=\"http://www.fatf-gafi.org/recommendations\">www.fatf-gafi.org/recommendations</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','','2017-03-30 07:00:15','2017-03-30 07:00:15'),(9,1,1,10,2,'Risk Management Manual','risk-management-manual-1490868139','<p>Version 2: July 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Revised by: Frankfurt School for Finance, Rosemary Muyeshi &amp; James Onyutta</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:593px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"6\"><strong>Amendments</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Table</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Date</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Status: In progress/ Complete</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Chapter/Section/Page Number</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Description of Amendment/ Reference Number</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Manual updated by:</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>Head of Department and Reviewer</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Page Section 1.1</td>\r\n			<td>Incorporation of a section on General provisions.</td>\r\n			<td>Rose Mary Muyeshi (RM) &amp; Frankfurt Business School (FBS)</td>\r\n			<td>James Onyutta (CEO), Lisa Marie Kienzle (LMK) and Pauline Vaughan (PV)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Page Section 1.2</td>\r\n			<td>Re-defining the purpose of the manual in reference to the Governance Structure and role of boards and Committees.</td>\r\n			<td>RM &amp; FBS</td>\r\n			<td>CEO. LMK &amp; PV</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Page Section 1.3</td>\r\n			<td>Re-defining Risk approach in line with the &ldquo;three lines of defense&rdquo; and deletion of reference to CBK as basis of guidance</td>\r\n			<td>RM &amp; FBS</td>\r\n			<td>CEO. LMK &amp; PV</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Page Section 1.4 &amp; 1.5</td>\r\n			<td>Insertion of Risk management philosophy and definition of Musoni Risk Appetite.&nbsp; Deletion of Statement referring to manual as based on simple business model.</td>\r\n			<td>RM &amp; FBS</td>\r\n			<td>CEO. LMK &amp; PV</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Page Section 2</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Section 2.2</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Removal of roles &amp; Responsibility of Risk committee as this is defined in Governance Manual.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Addition of Management team responsibilities under and incorporation of Assets and Liabilities Committee</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>RM &amp; FBS</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>CEO. LMK &amp; PV</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Jun/15</td>\r\n			<td>Complete</td>\r\n			<td>Section 2.3</td>\r\n			<td>Addition of a section on Risk Management Unit, its responsibilities, structure and special tasks of this unit.</td>\r\n			<td>RM &amp; FBS</td>\r\n			<td>CEO. LMK &amp; PV</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc393321671\"></a><a name=\"_Toc425253672\"></a><strong>TABLE OF CONTENTS</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253672\"><strong>TABLE OF CONTENTS</strong>. 2</a></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253673\"><strong>Introduction</strong>. 3</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253674\"><strong>1.1.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>General Provisions</strong>. 3</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253675\"><strong>1.2.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Purpose</strong>. 3</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253676\"><strong>1.3.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Approach</strong>. 4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253677\"><strong>1.4.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Risk Management Philosophy</strong>. 4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253678\"><strong>1.5.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Risk Appetite</strong>. 4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253679\"><strong>Structure</strong>. 5</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253680\"><strong>2.1.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Board of Directors &ndash; Risk Management, Asset and Liabilities Committee</strong>. 5</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253681\"><strong>2.2.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Management Team &ndash; Assets and Liabilities Committee</strong>. 5</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253682\"><strong>2.2.1.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Management Team</strong>.. 5</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253683\"><strong>2.2.2.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Assets and Liabilities Committee</strong>. 6</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253684\"><strong>2.2.3.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>The Risk Management Unit (RMU)</strong>&nbsp;8</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253685\"><strong>2.2.4.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Individual Staff Members</strong>. 10</a></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253686\"><strong>Special Tasks of the RMU</strong>. 10</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253687\"><strong>3.1.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Risk Matrix</strong>. 10</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_Toc425253688\"><strong>3.2.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Risk Management Activity Plan</strong>. 11</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253673\"></a><a name=\"_Toc144007113\"></a><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Introduction</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253674\"></a><strong>1.1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>General Provisions</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Risk Management Manual</strong>&nbsp;of Musoni was developed in accordance with the laws of the Republic of Kenya, the regulations of the Central Bank of Kenya, including the regulation No. 19 of 2006, The Microfinance Act, and the Microfinance (Deposit Taking Microfinance Institutions) Regulations of 2008, related to the governance/risk management or internal control in Microfinance Institutions, internal regulations as well as the mission statement of Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board of Directors (BoD) understands that having a risk management framework is fundamental for the healthy control and prevention of the accumulation of unacceptable levels of risk at Musoni. Thus, in an effort to improve risk management practices of Musoni, BoD has adopted this Risk Management Manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual aims to facilitate the anchoring of the risk management function of Musoni in a control environment of three lines of defense. It defines the risk management philosophy and risk appetite directly on the basis of Musoni&#39;s mission statement and reiterates the commitment of Musoni to contribute to the development of its target clientele through the provision of microfinance services in Kenya.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Risk Management Manual provides guidance on the risk management process of Musoni, including the identification, measurement, monitoring, control, mitigation and reporting of risk exposures. It also defines the powers and responsibilities of the structures and stakeholders within the organization involved in the risk management process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Risk Management Manual establishes the general framework of risk management at Musoni. It provides the common roof on which the elementary risk management policies of Musoni will be based. The elementary risk management policies will cover in detail the specific risk limits and authorized instruments for the mitigation of risks in each category.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253675\"></a><a name=\"_Toc144007114\"></a><strong>1.2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Purpose</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of this manual is to document the principles and processes of the Risk Management Framework as they are applied at Musoni. This manual takes reference to the&nbsp;<strong>Governance Structure Manual</strong>&nbsp;that describes the role of the Board of Directors, the board-level committees (Audit Committee, Risk and ALCO Committee, HR Committee), the Management Team, and the Asset and Liabilities Committee (ALCO). The Risk Management Manual explains the work related to risk management in detail.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253676\"></a><strong>1.3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Approach</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:100%\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Concept of the three lines of Defense in Risk Management at Musoni</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk Management in the Operating Business</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Promote a strong risk culture and sustainable risk-return thinking among Wealth Creation Officers</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Portfolio optimization on the macro and micro level through diversification</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Promote a strong culture of adhering to limits and managing risk exposure</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ongoing monitoring of positions and inherent risks</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk Management Department</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Combination of watchdog and trusted advisor for the Operating Business</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Enforce limits and actively challenge business</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Develop methodologies and tools to monitor risk</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Overarching &ldquo;risk oversight unit&rdquo; across all risk types</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Internal Audit</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Challenge the front office and risk management function</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Independent oversight function with enforcement ability</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni puts a strong emphasis on the proper approach to the management of risks. Musoni applies the best practice concept of &ldquo;Three Lines of Defense&rdquo; for its risk management framework. A strong risk culture combined with a sharp focus on three effective lines of defense, front office, risk management function, and internal audit are the key to Musoni&rsquo;s successful risk management. The three lines of defense are staffed with capable individuals with a strong sense of proper risk management and the desire to continuously improve the approach to manage risks.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253677\"></a><strong>1.4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Risk Management Philosophy</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni believes that effective management involves accepting a certain level of residual risk. Musoni does not seek to prevent or eliminate any risk exposure at all costs. This risk manual and its elementary components will help Musoni make informed decisions on the treatment of risks. Management may well choose to accept, diversify, mitigate or transfer identified risks.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253678\"></a><strong>1.5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Risk Appetite</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni is an active risk taker in the area of credit risk, but attempts to minimize the exposure to other risks. As an active risk taker, the overall risk appetite of Musoni is &ldquo;<strong>low</strong><strong>&nbsp;to moderate&rdquo;</strong>. Musoni believes that maintaining strict limits in relation to risk exposures is the most appropriate approach to ensure the sustainable provision of financial services to low-income populations in Kenya.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, Musoni will neither invest in a financial instrument, nor raise funds nor engage in a financial activity unless it is consistent with its mission to grow, build and maximize the potential of the businesses of the poor and unbanked of Kenya through the provision of affordable, flexible and customer-orientated financial services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The risk appetite as defined in this manual will guide Musoni&rsquo;s strategy and the decision to launch new products and enter new markets. In the elementary policies, the risk appetite will be translated into appropriate exposure limits for each risk dimension.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253679\"></a><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Structure</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Governance Structure Manual defines the governance structure of Musoni and prepares the basis for the Risk Management Framework. The framework is an inherent part of the governance structure. The Risk Management Manual provides further details on the roles and responsibilities of the committees involved in the risk management process at Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253680\"></a><strong>2.1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Board of Directors &ndash; Risk Management, Asset and Liabilities Committee</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Board of Directors (BoD) is ultimately responsible for all activities of Musoni, including all the risks that Musoni takes through its activities. The BoD has formed the Risk and ALCO Committee (RALCO) as a sub-committee. The RMC incorporates the legally required Credit Committee. The members of the RMC are appointed by the BoD to which it reports. RMC&rsquo;s objective is to provide oversight of a sound risk management system that is commensurate with Musoni&rsquo;s risk appetite. This includes a review of the institution&rsquo;s performance with regard to risk management of credit, market, liquidity, operation, compliance, reputation and other risks, and to offer support and advise the BoD on the implementation and monitoring of the risk management policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The details of the formation and regularity of meetings is handled in the Governance Structure Manual.</li>\r\n	<li>The RMC&rsquo;s authorities and duties are handled in the Governance Structure Manual</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The RMC receives detailed reports about all risk categories including all reports which are produced for and reviewed by the monthly ALCO.<a name=\"_Toc390949838\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390949950\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950141\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950207\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950273\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950339\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390975962\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390949840\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390949952\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950143\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950209\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950275\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390950341\"></a><a name=\"_Toc390975964\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253681\"></a><strong>2.2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Management Team &ndash; Assets and Liabilities Committee</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253682\"></a><strong>2.2.1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Management Team</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Management Team (MT) of Musoni is defined as the principal executive body of the Institution and as such, responsible for the day-to-day operations of the institution, including risk management. The general composition and work distribution is defined in the Governance Structure Manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With regards to aspects of risk management, the MT is responsible for:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Promoting fair practices and professionalism, with respect to internal dealings and external transactions, including situations where there are real or potential conflicts of interests</li>\r\n	<li>Creating an accountability framework for the staff</li>\r\n	<li>Providing the BoD with information on all potentially material risks facing Musoni. The information shall be comprehensive, accurate, complete and timely. More detailed reporting requirements can be derived from the authorities and duties of the RMC as defined in the Governance Structure Manual</li>\r\n	<li>Implementing the policies and procedures for conducting risk management as approved by the Board of Directors. This includes:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Approving risk management related guidelines that do not require the approval by the BoD</li>\r\n	<li>Approving a framework of detailed sub-limits</li>\r\n	<li>Annual review of procedures, policies and limits. Guidelines shall be updated frequently to reflect the evolution of risks (e.g., as new strategies are introduced, at least annually) and shall be developed after seeking input from across the organization</li>\r\n	<li>Continuously improving risk culture within Musoni</li>\r\n	<li>The Management Team can form committees for the continuous and efficient management of Musoni&rsquo;s risks. Musoni&rsquo;s Board of Directors has authorized the establishment of the ALCO on the management level.</li>\r\n	<li>The Management Team ensures that Musoni has effective risk management and control processes, reliable risk measurement and reporting systems, and competent staff for sound Risk Management</li>\r\n	<li>The Management Team will review periodically the adequacy and appropriateness of Musoni&rsquo;s policies and procedures, and risk management processes. The review should cover the methodologies, models and assumptions used to measure risk and limit exposures.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h1><strong>2.2.2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc425253683\"></a>Assets and Liabilities Committee</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Asset and Liabilities Committee (ALCO) is a Committee at the level of the Management Team. The members of the ALCO and the general responsibilities of the ALCO are defined in the Governance Structure Manual<a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_ftn1\" name=\"_ftnref1\">[1]</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO meets at minimum on a monthly basis. Ad-hoc meetings can be called if necessary. Responsibilities of the ALCO cover the all spectrum dimensions of risks at Musoni. This includes in particular the traditional scope of asset-liability management (liquidity, interest rate risk, currency risk) as well as close monitoring of the credit portfolio and operational risk exposures. More specifically, the ALCO performs the following activities:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1) Prepare an interim report to the RMC on risk exposures and strategies used to manage or mitigate them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2) Advise the RMC on future adaptations of risk management policies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3) Delegate certain authorities concerning investment and short-term financing to Treasury Manager - while respecting the internal control and powers of signatures on bank accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4) Define operational limits for financial risks and treasury management and verify compliance with these limits by authorized personnel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5) Monitor portfolio credit risk exposure profile</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6) Analyze the profile of vulnerability to operational risks and summary reports of materialized incidents and decide upon appropriate mitigation measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7) Evaluate potential risks in the development process of new products and entering new markets</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The regular agenda of the ALCO meeting includes the following topics related to Enterprise Risk Management (ERM):</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1) Recent macroeconomic developments relevant for Musoni</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2) Management Accounting: Last monthly accounting closing with a profitability analysis and gaps vis-&agrave;-vis the budget.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3) Credit Portfolio Analysis: Portfolio structure, arrears trends, vintage curve analysis, and concentration assessment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4) Operational Risk Dashboard: Key process vulnerabilities identified through operational risk self-assessments, results of incident reporting and external emerging events and graphic presentation on key risk indicators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5) Treasury reporting: Cash flow forecast, historical and forecasted liquidity ratios bench marked against liquidity limits, stress test results.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6) Interest Rate Risk: Re-pricing gap report with emphasis on co-movements to the market index for each major balance sheet currency, assessment of change on reference rates on bank net interest income over the next 12 months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7) Currency Risk: Calculation of per currency open and aggregate open positions in comparison to regulatory capital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8) Capital Adequacy: Tracking historical and forecast trends in the adequacy of regulatory capital as prescribed by CBK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9) Contractual Commitments dashboard: Identification and monitoring of contractual commitments (financial ratios and indicators) set within the various debt agreements, visualization of the evolution of indicators in relation to the more stringent limits imposed by the commitments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The decisions made by the ALCO are binding for the whole institution. If necessary, the ALCO shall develop its own Terms of Reference beyond the explanations covered here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All reports and proposals for presentation at the ALCO need to be submitted to the Secretary of the ALCO in advance of the meeting. All proposals need to include a recommendation by the Risk Manager and other areas if recommended by the Risk Manager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ALCO&rsquo;s decisions are made by a majority vote of the voting members. The minutes of the ALCO include a summary of any key issues presented/discussed as well as the details about any decisions taken, including the recommendations by Risk Manager (or Internal Auditor if applicable).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The minutes are distributed to the MT and the RMC. The distribution to the RMC also includes all submitted documents as well as the ALCO Agenda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO makes decisions on credit transactions, including decisions on the classification of loan indebtedness and loan loss provisioning. Details on credit approval authorities and credit portfolio concentration limits are handled in the Lending and Credit Manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO makes decisions on the procedures and scope of the delegation of authority. Those decisions will be documented in the respective manuals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO reviews the Liquidity and Funding position of Musoni regularly, takes mitigation measures as necessary and determines the strategy, mechanisms and characteristics of efficient fund allocation and fund planning for the institution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ALCO sets limits for any active and passive operations, including the selection and monitoring of Musoni&rsquo;s institutional counterparties, for the institution&rsquo;s exposure, limits for financial market operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253684\"></a><strong>2.2.3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>The Risk Management Unit (RMU)</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The RMU is responsible for the day-to-day execution of Risk Management at Musoni, and shall work closely with relevant staff in the Finance, Operations and Internal Audit departments. The RMU is headed by Musoni&rsquo;s Risk Manager who is responsible for the execution of the activities of the RMU.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>RMU constitute the independent risk management function that operates on the second line of defense in Musoni&rsquo;s Risk Management Framework. RMU Staff take the role as internal consultants for risk management, responsible for supporting the operational units in the identification, measurement and management of risks that may arise in the course of doing business at Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Responsibilities of the RMU</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The responsibilities of the RMU are listed in the following. It is recognized that the intensity of each activities is dependent on the overall scope of the business activities. The responsibilities include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Quantitative and qualitative assessment on a regular and ongoing basis of risks to which Musoni is exposed.</li>\r\n	<li>Development and maintenance of a system of internal limits that are more granular than the high-level organizational risk limits set and approved by the BoD/RMC. This is particularly relevant at the credit risk level and should allow for a fine tuning of efforts to monitor key risks and ultimately influence effective portfolio management. The Risk Manager may monitor this separately or else suggest formalizing this granular limit structure (and any changes therein) to the ALCO and seek approval as needed on an ongoing basis.</li>\r\n	<li>Monitoring of Musoni&rsquo;s risk profile, particularly that risk remains at levels deemed acceptable by ALCO, through reporting of trends and fluctuations (particularly if acceptable limits are bypassed or new, unacceptable risks are taken). For that task, the Risk Manager shall rely on the support from IT, Finance, Operations, HR, Internal Audit, and other relevant departments. The respective departments are required to provide support to the Risk Manager.</li>\r\n	<li>Periodically develops and presents reports on different risk aspects at Musoni, laid out in the detail sections on each risk.</li>\r\n	<li>Supports the implementation of IT solutions for risk management.</li>\r\n	<li>Management of Musoni&rsquo;s Credit Risk in line with the descriptions in the Lending and Credit Manual</li>\r\n	<li>Management of Musoni&rsquo;s Operational Risk in line with the descriptions in the various additional policies that cover Operational risk.</li>\r\n	<li>Management of Musoni&rsquo;s Liquidity and Market Risk in line with the various additional policies that cover Liquidity referenced in that chapter with the support of the respective departments.</li>\r\n	<li>Management of Musoni&rsquo;s Other Risks in line with the descriptions in the Chapter &ldquo;Special Tasks and Situations&rdquo; and with the support of the respective departments.</li>\r\n	<li>Examining new product proposals and making appropriate recommendations to Management Team when considering approvals of such new products. This examination is done in coordination with the Internal Auditor.</li>\r\n	<li>Monitoring of other risks as appropriate, including assessing fundamental risk factors including Early Warning Indicators.</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain a business relationship with the local regulators and be the first contact point for questions related to Risk Management from the Regulator.</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of the RMC. This includes the preparation of the reporting package, collecting the agenda items and preparation of proposals.</li>\r\n	<li>Tracking of decisions by the RMC through minutes and support to the RMC in the communication of the RMC decisions within the organization as appropriate.</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of the ALCO. This includes the preparation of the reporting package, collecting the agenda items and preparation of proposals.</li>\r\n	<li>Tracking of decisions by the ALCO through minutes, communication of the ALCO decisions within the organization as appropriate.</li>\r\n	<li>Coordination with the Internal Audit Department to ensure that Internal Audit is in the position to control compliance with established internal risk policy and structures.</li>\r\n	<li>Regular review of policies and guidelines and elaboration of suggestions for improvements</li>\r\n	<li>Regular review processes and elaboration of suggestions for improvements.</li>\r\n	<li>Developing mechanisms and strategies designed to improve the overall risk culture within Musoni, including appropriate training and support.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>RMU Structure and Resources</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To properly fulfill its responsibilities, the Risk Management Unit will have adequate human and technical resources for optimizing existing methods and introducing new techniques for identifying and quantifying risks to which Musoni is exposed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Risk Manager can suggest to the ALCO or if necessary to the RMC the staffing plan of the RMU and request the required human resources. Under certain circumstances and for special projects, RMU could seek temporary project based resources from other departments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Independence of RMU</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through this manual, Musoni establishes the principle of independence of the Risk Management Unit. This independence means that RMU staff will in no case be involved in operational tasks; they will never be subordinated to the business units that they are supposed to control and their compensation schemes will not include commercial risk-taking targets.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253685\"></a><strong>2.2.4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Individual Staff Members</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual establishes that all staff members of Musoni are an integral part of the Risk Management Framework and will be held accountable for individual risks. They are responsible to continuously improve the approach to Risk Management. While Musoni&rsquo;s Risk Unit is in place to manage the risks of the organization, it is the responsibility of each staff member to act responsibly and not enter risk in inappropriate ways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"_Toc144007115\"></a>Musoni promotes the understanding among all the staff that Risk Management and risk awareness are a key part of Musoni&rsquo;s risk culture. Every staff member is requested to report systematically and promptly to their managers and the Risk Manager via the provided tools (Risk self-Assessment, incident reporting) or if necessary through direct communication, any perceived new risks or failures of existing control measures. Musoni will undertake what measures it deems appropriate to promote and reward such efforts by its staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253686\"></a><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Special Tasks of the RMU</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253687\"></a><strong>3.1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Risk Matrix</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni uses a risk matrix that is based on industry best practice, adjusted for the specific needs of the institution. The Risk Matrix covers the risk categories governance, external risks, operational risk, IT risk, credit risk, and market risk. In each of these categories, several criteria are pre-defined and space is provided to define additional criteria. In the risk matrix, classifications are in three levels (low, medium, and high). Using initial severity and impact, and assessing the existing control mechanisms, a risk gap can be derived. This risk gap reflects the remaining open risk in that specific criteria. Based on assessment of Musoni&rsquo;s Risk Manager, this gap can be classified between 1 (low) and 5 (high).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next steps involves classification of all criteria by the rating of the gap. From that step an action plan for improvements to the risk management process for the next 12 months is derived. The specific activities of the action plan depend on the nature of the gap. This can range from updating policies to implementing additional checks or tool at just the criteria for internal audit to review processes and procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is recommended to update the risk matrix on an annual basis to check the progress made with regards to mitigating the most important risk gaps and to analyze whether additional risk criteria have to be considered in the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc425253688\"></a><strong>3.2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Risk Management Activity Plan</strong><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Risk Manager will complete an annual Activity Plan which includes all the tasks and special assignments related to Risk Management aside from the regular routine tasks as mentioned in the policies and manuals. The Activity Plan is largely based on the findings of the Risk Matrix with additional input from the Management Team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Risk Manager is responsible for the execution of the Activity Plan but can suggest a delegation of responsibilities where appropriate. In addition, the Risk Manager can also request additional resources in the execution of the activity plan</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Activity Plan is reviewed and approved by the Risk Management Committee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=23&amp;action=edit#_ftnref1\" name=\"_ftn1\">[1]</a>&nbsp;See Governance Structure Manual Section 8.1: The Members of the ALCO include the members of the MT as voting members, with the CEO as the Chairman of the ALCO. In addition, the Risk Manager is the Secretary of the ALCO as a non-voting member. The Internal Auditor is a non-voting guest of the ALCO. The members of the ALCO can invite further guests to the meeting.</p>\r\n','','2017-03-30 07:02:19','2017-03-30 07:02:19'),(10,1,1,11,2,'Human Resource Development Manual','human-resource-development-manual-1490868231','<p><strong>04. Human Resource Development Manual</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Version: Dec, 2016</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Revised by: Judy Ndungu &amp; James Onyutta</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reviewed by: The Board HR Committee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni BV, Musoni DTM Limited and Musoni Kenya Limited jointly own the intellectual property rights to this manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni DTM Limited and Musoni Kenya Limited may change or deviate from processes set out by the Manuals and the Musoni System as they see fit EXCEPTING where such change or deviation affects the provision of MIS Services by Musoni BV. In such a case the proposed change or deviation must be approved by a board resolution by Musoni DTM Limited / Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Such resolution can only be provided upon completion of an impact analysis carried out jointly by the Musoni Kenya Limited / Musoni DTM Limited and Musoni BV, which impact analysis concludes that it is possible to implement the proposed change without affecting MIS Services as defined in the Licence Agreement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If Musoni Kenya Limited / Musoni DTM Limited amend this manual, then they shall promptly notify Musoni BV of such amendments. Every six months, Musoni Kenya Limited / Musoni DTM Limited will provide updated electronic copies of all manuals to Musoni BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the avoidance of doubt neither Musoni Kenya Limited or Musoni DTM Limited have any intellectual property rights to IT services (including but not limited to any IT programming, stored procedures, SQL scripting, C# programming, source code, software) supplied by Musoni BV and referenced in this manual.<br />\r\nAmendments Table</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Status: In progress/ Complete</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chapter/Section/Page<br />\r\nNumber<br />\r\nDescription of Amendment/ Reference Number</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Manual updated by: [name]<br />\r\nHead of Dept./ Team Leader&rsquo;s Initials</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Added new performance appraisal form</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 6<br />\r\nPerformance<br />\r\nAppraisal Form<br />\r\nJudy<br />\r\nNdung&rsquo;u<br />\r\nDavid<br />\r\nJames<br />\r\n30/12/2013 Performance<br />\r\nAppraisal Process<br />\r\nChapter 5.1 Judy Ndungu<br />\r\nPerformance Improvement Plan Guidelines Chapter 5.2 Judy Ndung&rsquo;u<br />\r\nRevised Performance Based Bonus Scheme Chapter 11 Judy Ndungu<br />\r\nCEO Recruitment and Selection Process Chapter 3.0 Judy Ndung&rsquo;u<br />\r\n15/04/2014 Succession Planning Guidelines Chapter 6.0 Judy Ndung&rsquo;u<br />\r\n30/11/2015 Payroll Administration Clause Chapter 11.0 Judy Ndung&rsquo;u<br />\r\n10/02/2016 Review of Whistleblower policy Chapter 2.0 Judy Ndung&rsquo;u<br />\r\nTable of Contents<br />\r\n1. INTRODUCTION 7<br />\r\n1.1. Musoni Kenya limited 7<br />\r\n1.2. Vision 7<br />\r\n1.3. Mission 7<br />\r\n1.4. Core values 7<br />\r\n2. GENERAL PRINCIPLES 8<br />\r\n2.1. Equal opportunity: 8<br />\r\n2.2. Open-Door Policy 8<br />\r\n2.3 Whistle Blowing Policy 8<br />\r\n2.4. Harassment Policy 13<br />\r\n3.0 RECRUITMENT 14<br />\r\n3.1 Recruitment and Selection Process 14<br />\r\n3.2 Recruitment and selection Process for the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) 18<br />\r\n3.3 Probation 21<br />\r\n4. Human Resource Development 22<br />\r\n5. PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT 24<br />\r\n5.1 Performance Appraisal 24<br />\r\n5.1.1 How to Set Performance Targets (setting goals) 24<br />\r\n5.1.2 The Appraisal Process 26<br />\r\n5.1.3 The Appraisal Form 26<br />\r\n5.1.4 Scheduling and Holding a Performance Meeting 26<br />\r\n5.1.5 Completing the Appraisal Form 27<br />\r\n5.2 PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENT PLAN 29<br />\r\n5.2.1Introduction 29<br />\r\n5.2.2 Objectives of PIP 29<br />\r\n5.2.3 Eligibility 30<br />\r\n5.2.4 PIP Process for WCOs 30<br />\r\n6. SUCCESSION PLANNING 33<br />\r\n6.1 Introduction 33<br />\r\n6.2 Objectives 33<br />\r\n6.3 Steps to Execute Succession Planning 33<br />\r\n6.4 Succession Factors 33<br />\r\n6.5 Succession Summary Grids 34<br />\r\n6.6 Succession Chart (Sample) 34<br />\r\n34<br />\r\n7. CODE OF ETHICS 35<br />\r\n7.1 Conflict of interest 35<br />\r\n7.2 Communication with the press 36<br />\r\n7.3 Unauthorized disclosure of information (Confidentiality) 36<br />\r\n7.4 Personal Business 36<br />\r\n7.5 External commitments 37<br />\r\n7.6 Gifts and Favour 37<br />\r\n7.7 Intellectual property 37<br />\r\n8. FAIR AND RESPECTFUL TREATMENT OF MUSONI CLIENTS 38<br />\r\n9. ATTENDANCE AND LEAVE PROCEDURES 39<br />\r\n9.1 Working hours 39<br />\r\n9.2 Leave 39<br />\r\n9.2.1. Leave Procedures 39<br />\r\n9.2.2. Maternity/Paternity leave 40<br />\r\n9.2.3. Sick leave 40<br />\r\n9.2.5. Compassionate Leave 41<br />\r\n10 .CUSTODY AND RETENTION OF STAFF MEMBERS RECORDS 42<br />\r\n10 .STANDARDS AND EXPECTATIONS AT WORKPLACE 42<br />\r\n10.1 Reporting Unsafe Conditions or Practices 42<br />\r\n10.2 Reporting an Injury 42<br />\r\n10.3 Care of Company property and Supplies 42<br />\r\n10.4 Smoking at the Workplace 43<br />\r\n10.5 Violence and Weapons 43<br />\r\n10.6 Drug-Free Workplace 43<br />\r\n10.7 Appearance and Dressing 43<br />\r\n11. REMUNERATION AND BENEFITS 44<br />\r\n11.1Salaries 44<br />\r\n11.2 Payroll Administration 44<br />\r\n11.3 Salary Advances 45<br />\r\n11.4 Performance Based Bonus Scheme 45<br />\r\n11.4.1Bonus Objectives 45<br />\r\n11.4.2 Target Staff 45<br />\r\n11.4.3 Bonus Calculation for WCOs (GL) 46<br />\r\n11.4.4 Bonus Calculation for Individual Loan Officers (ILOs) 47<br />\r\n11.4.5Bonus Calculation for Branch Managers (BM) 47<br />\r\n11.4.6 Bonus Calculation for Mashinani SWCOs 47<br />\r\n11.4.7 Conclusion 48<br />\r\n11.5 Medical Cover 48<br />\r\n11.6 Pension 48<br />\r\n12. DISCIPLINARY CODE AND PROCEDURE 49<br />\r\n12.1 Policy Statement 49<br />\r\n12.2 Principles 49<br />\r\n12.3 Disciplinary Code 49<br />\r\n12.3.1 Misconduct: 49<br />\r\n12.3.2 Disciplinary Process 50<br />\r\n12.3.3 Guiding Principles 50<br />\r\n12.3.4 Warning Procedures 51<br />\r\n12.3.5 Gross Misconduct 52<br />\r\n12.3.6 Disciplinary Process and Procedure for Gross Misconduct 53<br />\r\n13. GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES 54<br />\r\n15. Other Obligations at End of Service 57<br />\r\nAnnex 1: Sample External job advert 58<br />\r\nAnnex 2: Interview assessment form 59<br />\r\nAnnex 3: Leave Application form 61<br />\r\nANNEX 4: Sample Appraisal Form 63<br />\r\nAnnex 5: Candidate Profile Template (Succession Planning) 67<br />\r\nAnnex 6: Employee exit form (Form 4.6) 68<br />\r\nAnnex 7: Letter of confirmation (Form 4.7) 71</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. INTRODUCTION</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This manual provides the General terms and conditions of employment for staff members of Musoni Kenya Limited and shall apply to all staff. This Manual outlines policy to be followed in the management of staff matters. It is freely accessible for Musoni employees and relevant stakeholders. All conditions have been made in good faith and are subject to prevailing laws.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.1. Musoni Kenya limited</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited was born out of a desire to improve both the quality and accessibility of financial services available to poor and unbanked Kenyans. It was incorporated by Musoni BV, based in Amsterdam, the Netherlands. Musoni BV is a service company, a management company, a repository of knowledge and expertise on starting and running MFIs, and a holding company of stakes in MFIs. Musoni Kenya Limited is the first microfinance institution to be established by Musoni BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In May 2012 Musoni BV welcomed three strategic partners with KfW, Grameen Foundation, and Access Africa Fund becoming new shareholders in the company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.2. Vision<br />\r\nTo be the most efficient microfinance institution in Kenya by being cashless, paperless and data-driven to offer the best value, most flexible and most customer-oriented financial services in the market.<br />\r\n1.3. Mission</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To grow, build and maximize the potential of the businesses of the low income and unbanked of Kenya through the provision of affordable, flexible and customer-oriented financial services.<br />\r\n1.4. Core values<br />\r\nWe pursue long-term relations with Musoni Kenya clients, employees and stakeholders. Musoni<br />\r\nKenya core values are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Innovation: Develop new ideas to enable us to be the most efficient microfinance institution in Kenya, delivering innovative and competitive financial services by using the latest technology and data analytics.<br />\r\nIntegrity: Do what is right, treat clients, partners and each other with utmost respect, honesty and uphold the highest ethical standards.<br />\r\nCustomer Focus: Delivering process oriented and Quality driven services aligned with our customer needs.<br />\r\nExcellence: Strive to deliver first class service through best talent and continuous personal and professional development aiming to create value to our staff, clients and shareholders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. GENERAL PRINCIPLES</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.1. Equal opportunity:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited is an equal opportunity employer. Therefore, Musoni shall apply objective and fair criteria to ensure that staff members are selected, assessed, promoted and treated on the basis of their merits, abilities and experience relevant to their post. No suitable job applicant or staff member shall receive less favourable treatment than others in similar circumstances on grounds of personal characteristics, such as race, colour, national, social or ethnic origin and language, gender, marital status, disability, class, age, political or religious belief or HIV status.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The final criterion for appointment and promotion is merit. The principle of equal opportunity shall form the fundamental framework for human resource development. Musoni Kenya Limited shall pay male and female employees equal remuneration for work of equal value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.2. Open-Door Policy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In keeping with the company&rsquo;s philosophy of open communication, all employees have the right and are encouraged to speak freely with management about their job-related concerns. We urge you to go directly to your supervisor to discuss your job-related ideas, recommendations, concerns and other issues which are important to you. If after talking with your supervisor, you feel the need for additional discussion, you are encouraged to speak with the Chief Executive Officer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most important relationship you will develop at the Company will be between you and your supervisor. However, should you need support from someone other than your supervisor, the entire management team, including the CEO, is committed to resolving your individual concerns in a timely and appropriate manner (see Annex I: Organogram).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.3 Whistle Blowing Policy<br />\r\nMusoni is committed to high standards of ethical, moral and legal business conduct. In line with this commitment, and the Board and the management is committed to open communication. This policy aims to provide an avenue for Musoni employees to raise concerns and reassurance that they will be protected from reprisals or victimization for whistleblowing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whistleblowing policies are generally intended to make it easier for members of staff to be able to report irregularities in good faith, without having to fear that their action may have adverse consequences.<br />\r\nThe Whistleblowing Policy is a key element for safeguarding the Musoni&rsquo;s integrity. It is aimed at enhancing transparency and underpinning its system for combating practices that might damage its activities and reputation.<br />\r\nProtecting the integrity and reputation of MUSONI requires the active support of all members of MUSONI&rsquo;s staff, who are required to report incidents of suspected fraud, corruption, collusion and coercion, and other serious infringements of the rules and policies in force at MUSONI. Members of staff must also cooperate in investigations into such incidents.<br />\r\nBy creating an environment of trust and maximum protection for the members of its staff, MUSONI wants to encourage them to cooperate in full. It is putting in place arrangements that will ensure that members of staff who report irregularities in good faith are afforded the utmost confidentiality and greatest degree of and most effective protection possible against any retaliation or reprisals, whether actual or threatened, as a result of their whistleblowing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a. Basic whistleblowing principles<br />\r\nThe basic principles of MUSONI&rsquo;s Whistleblowing Policy are as follows:<br />\r\nthe persons concerned must have a choice between a number of channels for whistleblowing and communication; in certain circumstances, they must be able to bypass the main channels for whistleblowing if these prove inappropriate;<br />\r\nmembers of staff must not under any circumstances be subject to reprisals for whistleblowing;<br />\r\nmembers of staff who report incidents in good faith must be protected and their identity must insofar as possible remain confidential;<br />\r\nthe reported incidents shall be verified in the appropriate manner and, if they are confirmed, MUSONI shall take all necessary steps to identify appropriate remedies;<br />\r\nthe basic rights of any person implicated by the reported incidents must be respected, whilst ensuring that the procedures provided for are effective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Scope of the policy<br />\r\nMUSONI&rsquo;s Whistleblowing Policy applies to all permanent staff members and any other person providing MUSONI with services, including consultants and other service providers under contract (grouped together for the purposes of this document under the term &ldquo;staff member(s)&rdquo;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c. Reporting Obligations<br />\r\nMembers of staff are required to report any suspected or presumed incidents of illegal behaviour in the activities of MUSONI or of serious misconduct or serious infringement of MUSONI&rsquo;s rules, policies or guidelines, or any action that is or could be harmful to the mission or reputation of MUSONI (hereinafter &ldquo;irregularities&rdquo;).<br />\r\nSuch incidents may involve members of staff, borrowers, promoters, contractors, suppliers, beneficiaries or any other persons or entities. Members of staff are required to cooperate in any official investigation, audit or similar request. No members of staff may use their position to prevent other members of staff from exercising their rights or complying with their obligations as indicated above.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>d. Reporting Procedures<br />\r\nReporting of cases of alleged fraud, corruption, money laundering or financing of terrorism<br />\r\n&ndash; or &ndash;<br />\r\nof a serious failure or infringement of ethics or integrity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(i) For cases of alleged fraud, corruption, collusion or coercion, money laundering and financing of terrorism, or any other unlawful activity that is detrimental to the financial interests of MUSONI, the member of staff is required to inform the internal auditor through the following contacts:<br />\r\nEmail: annemwasi@musoni.co.ke<br />\r\nCell phone: +254722870101<br />\r\n(ii) If the event the use of the above reporting procedures is not appropriate in view of the circumstances or nature of the incidents (for instance, if there is a conflict of interest or a risk of reprisals, the intended recipient of the report is personally implicated in the incidents to be reported, or the authority initially alerted fails to take appropriate action), the member of staff may inform Musoni CEO through the following contacts:<br />\r\nEmail stanleymunyao@musoni.co.ke<br />\r\nCell phone: +254721702156<br />\r\n(iii) In the event of the use of the above reporting procedures is not appropriate in view of the circumstances or nature of the incidents (for instance, if there is a conflict of interest or a risk of reprisals, the intended recipient of the report is personally implicated in the incidents to be reported, or the authority initially alerted fails to take appropriate action), the member of staff may as a last resort, refer the matter to Musoni BOD through the following contacts:<br />\r\nEmail wambuikyama@gmail.com<br />\r\nCell phone; 254722643121<br />\r\nOR<br />\r\nEmail: duncan@musoni.co.ke</p>\r\n\r\n<p>e. Reporting arrangements and anonymity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is up to staff members to choose the most appropriate channel for reporting incidents which they must disclose. However, if a matter is reported to an authority that is not competent to deal with it, it is up to that authority to transmit, in strictest confidence, the relevant information and documents to the competent authority and to inform the member of staff accordingly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>f. Maintaining confidentiality<br />\r\nThe confidentiality and anonymity of persons making complaints or expressing concerns will be maintained to the fullest extent possible, consistent with the need to conduct an investigation unless required by law to break that confidentiality. The Board encourages you to supply contact information with your submission to facilitate clarification and any assistance with possible investigation.<br />\r\nTo assist the Board in reviewing and, if necessary, investigating your complaints or concerns, you should provide as much factual, rather than speculative, information as possible. To the extent possible, you should include the following information in your submission:<br />\r\nthe alleged event, matter or issue that is the subject of the complaint or concern;<br />\r\nthe name of each person you believe involved;<br />\r\nif the complaint or concern involves a specific event or events, the approximate date(s) and location(s) of each event; and<br />\r\nany additional information, documentation or other evidence you believe support the complaint or concern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>g. Protection of the whistleblower<br />\r\nAny staff member who reports an irregularity, provided that this is done in good faith and in compliance with the provisions of this policy, shall be protected against any acts of retaliation.<br />\r\nFor the purposes of this policy, &quot;retaliation&quot; is defined as any action or threat of action which is unjustly detrimental to the whistleblower because of his/her report, including, but not limited to, harassment, discrimination and acts of vindictiveness, direct or indirect, that are recommended, threatened or taken against the whistleblower.<br />\r\n&ldquo;Good faith&rdquo; can be taken to mean the unequivocal belief in the veracity of the reported incidents, i.e. the fact that the member of staff reasonably believes the transmitted information to be true.<br />\r\nStaff members, who make a report in bad faith, particularly if it is based knowingly on false or misleading information, shall not be protected and shall be subject to disciplinary measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>h. Protective Measures<br />\r\nThe protection of a person reporting an irregularity shall be guaranteed first of all by the fact that their identity will be treated in confidence. This means that their name will not be revealed, unless the whistle-blower personally authorises the disclosure of his/her identity or this is a statutory requirement, particularly if it is essential to ensure that the right of the persons implicated to be given a fair hearing is upheld. In such a case, person handling the report (one of the three persons mentioned above) shall be required to notify the whistleblower before revealing their identity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. No Retaliation<br />\r\nNo member of staff who in good faith reports irregularity shall suffer harassment, retaliation or adverse employment consequence. Where members of staff consider that they have been the victim of retaliation for reporting an irregularity or have good reason to believe or fear that they are exposed to a risk of retaliation as a result of their reporting an irregularity, they shall be entitled to complain to the any other person mentioned above and request that protective measures be adopted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The authority approached shall assess the circumstances of the case referred to it and may recommend to the BOD that temporary and/or permanent measures that are necessary in the interests of MUSONI be adopted with a view to protecting the staff member in question. The staff member shall be informed in writing of the results of this procedure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>j. Training of staff on whistleblowing<br />\r\nAll Musoni staff will be trained on the whistleblowing at all levels of the organization in relation to whistleblowing law and the organization&rsquo;s policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>k. Handling reported violations<br />\r\nAll reports will be promptly investigated and treated consistently and fairly within 60 days from the day of reporting. Appropriate corrective action will be taken if warranted by the investigation. The complainant will be informed that follow-up has or is occurring within two weeks after the Executive Director or board officer has received the complaint or report. The Executive Committee shall be informed of all such complaints or reports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>l. Penalties for those taking retaliatory actions<br />\r\nAny form of retaliation undertaken by a staff member against any person for reporting an irregularity in good faith is prohibited and considered to be a serious breach of the loyalty and professional ethics requirements of MUSONI&rsquo;s Code of Conduct. In such a case disciplinary measures shall be taken.<br />\r\nMembers of staff will be informed of the measures taken by MUSONI following the discovery of acts of retaliation for reporting an incident. The information provided will not contain any data that will enable the people concerned to be identified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>m. Rights of persons implicated<br />\r\nAny staff member implicated by reports of irregularities must be notified in good time of the allegations made against them, provided that this notification does not impede the progress of the procedure for establishing the circumstances of the case. In any event, findings referring to a staff member specifically by name may not be made upon the completion of the above-mentioned procedure, unless that staff member has had the opportunity to put forward their comments in keeping with the principle of respect for the right to be given a fair hearing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After having heard the implicated staff member, or after having requested the latter to put their case in writing if, for objective reasons, it is not possible to hear them directly, the person handling the report (one of the three persons mentioned above) shall decide on the measures required in MUSONI&rsquo;s interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the reporting of irregularities and/or the ensuing procedure will involve dealing with personal data, such data shall be managed in keeping with the principles and rules provided for in the regulations applicable to MUSONI. Those involved in the reporting procedure and in any related procedure, including whistle-blowers themselves, may contact the GM at any time in order to check that the rights conferred by the relevant provisions have been respected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>n. Annual Reporting<br />\r\nAt the end of each year the Head of Internal Audit shall report on how the organizations reputation has been saved or how it has been saved from making losses by a whistle blower.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>o. Modification<br />\r\nThe Audit Committee or the Board of Directors of Musoni Kenya can modify this Policy unilaterally at any time without notice. Modification may be necessary, among other reasons, to maintain compliance with local regulations and/or accommodate organizational changes within the Company.<br />\r\n2.4. Harassment Policy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Company will not tolerate harassment or intimidation of our employees on any basis prohibited by law, including race, colour, sex, age, religion, national origin, or marital status. Moreover, any suggestions made to any employee that sexual favors will affect any term or condition of employment with the Company will not be tolerated. It is the policy of the Company that any harassment, including acts creating a hostile work environment or any other discriminatory acts directed against our employees, will result in discipline, up to and including termination of service. The Company also will not tolerate any such harassment of our employees by our clients or vendors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For purposes of this policy, Sexual Harassment is any repeated unwanted behavior of a sexual nature perpetrated upon an individual by another&rdquo;. It may be verbal, visual, written or physical and can occur between people of different genders or those of the same sex. The following are examples of conduct that, depending upon the circumstances, may constitute sexual harassment:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unwelcome sexual jokes, language, epithets, advances or propositions;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Written or oral abuse of a sexual nature, sexually degrading or vulgar words to describe an individual;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The display of sexually suggestive objects, pictures, posters or cartoons;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unwelcome comments about an individual&rsquo;s body;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Asking questions about sexual conduct;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unwelcome touching, leering, whistling, brushing against the body, or suggestive, insulting or obscene comments or gestures;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Demanding sexual favors in exchange for favorable reviews, assignments, promotions, or continued employment, or promises of the same.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employees must bring any violation of this policy to the immediate attention of their immediate supervisor, CHRO or the CEO. The Company will thoroughly investigate all such claims with due regard for the privacy of the individuals involved. Any employee who knowingly retaliates against an employee who has reported workplace harassment or discrimination shall be subject to immediate<br />\r\ndisciplinary action, up to and including termination of service.<br />\r\n3.0 RECRUITMENT</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy is intended to provide assistance to those members of staff involved in the recruitment process within the organisation and specifies the procedures through from advertising to offer of employment. It is also intended to provide advice on best practice to ensure that the company&rsquo;s recruitment process is consistent and effective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recruitment in Musoni Kenya Limited shall be targeted at addressing specific needs of the organization. Musoni Kenya shall strive to attract employees of the highest caliber and integrity to ensure the achievement of the organizational goals &amp; objectives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.1 Recruitment and Selection Process<br />\r\nStep 1: Request to recruit</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The head of department shall make a formal request and justify the need to recruit. Details of vacancies and the job specifications/requirements shall be submitted to the CHRO by the Head of Department where new staff is required. Open positions are not automatically approved but must be reviewed before the position is posted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: CEO Approval and HR feedback</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CHRO shall consult the Chief Finance Officer to advise on whether the vacant position is budgeted for and the approved salary range. The Chief Executive Officer (CEO) will be the final person to approve any recruitment of a new staff.<br />\r\nHR will then communicate with the relevant Head of Department upon approval. In case of non-approval, clear reasons will be given.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3: Advertising for open position</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Human resources will advertise and attempt to fill staff vacancies by promotion and/or transfer within the organization and, subject to the provision that merit is the final criterion. Preference shall be given to suitably qualified staff members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Internal Advertisement</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff members shall be notified of upcoming vacancies through internal advertisement. Qualifications and experience required for the post will be stated in an advertisement, which will be circulated to all staff via email (all@staff.musoni.co.ke). Staff members who wish to be considered for an advertised position should submit an application letter and an updated CV before the closing date indicated in the advertisement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>External Advertisement</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In case we are not able to source internally, an external advert will either be done through the daily newspaper, directly with recognized middle level colleges or Universities, appointed Head Hunters or referrals. All advertisements for vacancies shall be approved by the CHRO or his/her designate before publication External advertisement.<br />\r\nHead Hunting<br />\r\nHeadhunting is a very specialized area of recruitment of sourcing high profiles without dependency on job adverts and employees seeking employment. It involves hunting candidates through direct contacts or personal meetings in order to convince the candidates to participate in the recruitment process. Musoni Kenya may occasionally engage a Headhunting Firm to find best talent for senior level positions and jobs that require a high degree of expertise. Musoni will provide the headhunter with a detailed job description and work closely together in the interviewing and selection process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4: Application screening process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All job applications for any advertised position will come thru the careers@musoni.co.ke email account which acts as the central database for all job applications. During the time of advertising, the applicants will be advised to quote the job title on the subject line as they apply which makes it easy to sort out all the applications that relate to the specific job that we have advertised for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The HR will do the initial screening of the CVs as per the actual Job Description and print out the applications that meet the job specifications. The hard copy file will be shared with the Head of Department and soft copy folder with the Branch Manager. The shortlisting will be done by a panel of 3 people. A summary of all the applicants that have been shortlisted by the panel will be provided to ensure that the panel has an upper hand on the shortlist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Departmental Heads are allowed to access all the applications that have been received from the official recruitment email account careers@musoni.eu and act as a 2nd checkers to the HR. The password for this email account will keep on changing for security reasons and the heads of departments must therefore request for the new password.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 5: Interview process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Senior management interview</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A panel of not less than three C-level persons, including the CEO and CHRO, and a Board Member shall conduct an interview for the senior management and Internal Auditor. Branch Managers will also be interviewed by at least 3 members of the Senior Management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For every Management position, the panel should interview at least 8 shortlisted candidates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other staff interview</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A panel of not less than three people persons, including the Head of Department or his/her designate under which the vacant position falls, shall conduct the interview.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each panelist shall fill in a score sheet for each candidate who is interviewed indicating the score in each of the different categories being examined. A standard score sheet will be used and it may be varied from time to time to suit the requirements for each job</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Practical Tests</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Practical tests shall be given to candidates depending on the position to evaluate the candidate&rsquo;s practical ability to perform the job. The CHRO and the Head of Department or his/her designate shall be involved in setting the practical test that must be relevant to that particular position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CEO will approve the test and the pass mark. The test will be marked and evaluated by HR or any other independent person appointed by the CHRO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In case of recruitment of Fresh Graduates from recognized institutions&rsquo;, the aptitude test will be used to eliminate the many applicants. Graduates that pass the aptitude test will qualify for the oral interview. The aptitude test will be administered by the HR department.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Psychometric Tests<br />\r\nMusoni has adopted the Hogan Psychometric tests in the recruitment process to help give a better overall evaluation of candidate and hopefully secure the best fit for the role. The format of tests varies and can either measure single factors or multiple variables. Tests typically consist of knowledge tests, personality questionnaires and accuracy tests. A psychometric test will never be used in isolation but as one component of a wider, integrated evaluation strategy.<br />\r\nStep 6: Selection process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The selection criteria at Musoni will be based on MERIT i.e. the skills, knowledge and attributes that a candidate has in order to undertake successfully the responsibilities and duties of a position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following criteria will be used by the interviewing panel: -</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Mandatory levels of qualification, experience and or training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Core competencies required to undertake the duties and responsibilities of the job. iii. Possession of good communication skills<br />\r\niv. Ability of the applicant to show that he/she has good computer knowledge or basic arithmetic</p>\r\n\r\n<p>skill for WCO&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The final decision on the most suitable candidate for the job will be made by the interview panel based on the selection criteria. The decision on the hiring of C-level staff and the Internal Auditor will be made by the Board of Directors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 7: Reference Check/ Background Check<br />\r\nEvery successful candidate (with the exception of Fresh Graduates) will undergo an additional independent background check to ensure that we do not attract candidates that are fraudulent or with bad history and therefore putting Musoni into risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni has an approved independent firm (Hawk eye Technologies) who shall do the following on behalf of Musoni:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Verify highest level of education for authenticity and confirm with the issuing institution.<br />\r\nInvestigate past employment history<br />\r\niii. Verify if the candidate has ever been involved in any criminal activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 8: Appointment of candidate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chief Executive Officer shall exercise the Board of Directors&#39; authority in respect of all non- management staff members&#39; appointments, transfers and promotions. Upon appointment, each staff member shall receive a letter of appointment, which shall include the following provisions: -<br />\r\na) The names and addresses of the parties to the contract of employment;<br />\r\nb) Effective date of continuous service;<br />\r\nc) The title of the job that the employee is employed to do, the nature of the appointment, including reporting lines. A detailed job description, or terms of reference, shall be attached to the letter of appointment;<br />\r\nd) A statement adopting the provisions of the Human Resource Policies Manual;<br />\r\ne) The duty station to which the staff member shall be deployed at that time;<br />\r\nf) The nature of the appointment, which may be temporary, permanent or contractual;<br />\r\ng) The employees&rsquo; normal hours of work and the days of the week on which the work is to be performed;<br />\r\nh) The length of the probation period to be served;<br />\r\ni) The starting salary, details of salary payments, standard deductions, including any staff contributions (for example to pension scheme) and allowable benefits;<br />\r\nk) The fact that every staff member shall be expected to undertake an assignment in any duty station in Musoni Kenya network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8.1 Once the letter is signed by the staff member and returned to the Human Resource Department, the letter of appointment, Employee Handbook and job description shall constitute the contract between the staff member and Musoni Kenya Limited.<br />\r\n8.2 Non-national staff members shall be required to obtain a permit (residence/work permit) authorizing him/her to reside and work in the respective country. The Chief HR Officer or his/her designate shall obtain an assurance of the permit applicable which allows the staff member (in some cases a visa and work permit are both required) initially to enter the country to take up employment and residence. Musoni Kenya Limited shall assist the staff member to obtain all permits for the staff member and his/her family. All costs involved in the initial issue and in the renewal of the applicable permits and visas shall be borne by Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8.3 A staff member who has been appointed to work with Musoni Kenya Limited will accept his/her appointment in any case not later than 7 days from the day he/she is given his/her appointment letter. If after 7 days he/she has not accepted the appointment, then it shall become null and void.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2 Recruitment and selection Process for the Chief Executive Officer (CEO)<br />\r\nThe Chief Executive Officer (CEO) has the overall responsibility for the performance of the Company, the development and implementation of a company strategy, and will take all actions necessary to meet the goals and targets agreed with the Board. In case this key position falls vacant, the following recruitment and selection process will be followed.<br />\r\n3.2.1 Advertisement<br />\r\nThe CEO position will be advertised both internally and externally. The advert shall be approved by the Chairman of the Board or his/her designate before publication.<br />\r\n*The Board of Directors may also decide to engage a Head Hunter for the CEO recruitment and work closely together in the interviewing and selection process.<br />\r\nInternal Advertisement</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff members shall be notified of the upcoming vacancy through an internal advertisement. Qualifications and experience required for the post will be stated in an advertisement, which will be circulated to all staff via email (all@staff.musoni.co.ke)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>External Advertisement<br />\r\nIn case we are not able to source internally, an external advert will either be done through the daily newspaper, appointed recruitment agencies or referrals. The public external advertisement should include the following information:<br />\r\nBrief description of Musoni Kenya Limited.<br />\r\nJob title.<br />\r\nJob specification.<br />\r\nPerson specification.<br />\r\nQualifications and experience required for the post.<br />\r\nLocation of duty station.<br />\r\nClosing date for submission of applications.<br />\r\nAddressee of applications.<br />\r\nA special email account will be created where all applications will be received. The interviewing panel (explained below) will access all the applications through a shared password.<br />\r\nHead Hunting<br />\r\nHeadhunting is a very specialized area of recruitment of sourcing high profiles without dependency on job adverts and employees seeking employment. It involves hunting candidates through direct contacts or personal meetings in order to convince the candidates to participate in the recruitment process. Musoni Kenya may occasionally engage a Headhunting Firm to find best talent for senior level positions and jobs that require a high degree of expertise. Musoni will provide the headhunter with a detailed job description and work closely together in the interviewing and selection process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2.2 Screening and Short-listing of applicants will be carried out by a selection panel of not less than 3 people, including the Chairman of the Board, Chairman of the Board HR Committee plus any other Board Member(s) that may be appointed by the Board of Directors to act as their representative.<br />\r\nThe selection panel will screen all the applications and come up with the initial shortlist as per the actual Job Description. Due to the different geographical locations and time differences for the Directors, each member of the panel will be expected to come up with a summary of all the applicants that he/she has shortlisted. The panel will then compare their individual shortlists and come up with one final shortlist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2.3 First Round of Interviews<br />\r\nThe selection panel shall interview not less than 8 of the shortlisted candidates. They will endeavor to conduct the first round of interviews together and physically meet the candidates. In case it&rsquo;s not possible due to the different geographical locations, then the first interviews could be conducted on Skype. Each panelist shall fill in a score sheet for each candidate who is interviewed indicating the score in each of the different categories being examined. A standard score sheet will be used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2.4 Practical and psychometric tests</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Practical tests shall be given to the best 2 candidates to evaluate the candidate&rsquo;s practical ability to perform the job. The panel shall be involved in setting the practical test that must be relevant to this particular position. The test will be marked and evaluated by the Chairman of the Board or any other independent person appointed by the Board of Directors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly, we shall partner with a credible independent consultancy firm that offers assessment services to conduct a set of psychometric tests on the 2 best candidates. The purpose will be to evaluate the candidate&rsquo;s ability to solve different business related problems and decision making. The tests will also highlight the negative tendencies of the candidates and characteristics that might influence occupational success. In addition, they will be tested on how they are likely to act in various circumstances and note the candidate&rsquo;s strengths and weaknesses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2.5 Final interviews and Selection<br />\r\nThe selection panel will conduct the 2nd round of interviews and settle on the most suitable candidate for the job. The selection criteria at Musoni will be based on MERIT i.e. the skills, knowledge and attributes that a candidate has in order to undertake successfully the responsibilities and duties of a position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following criteria will be used by the selection panel:-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandatory levels of qualification, experience and or training.<br />\r\nCore competencies/skills required to undertake the duties and responsibilities of the job.<br />\r\nPersonal Attributes of the candidate.<br />\r\nAffordability based on approved budget.<br />\r\n3.2.6 Reference Check/ Background Check</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The successful candidate will undergo a background/reference check to verify the following: -<br />\r\nHighest level of education for authenticity and confirm with the issuing institution.<br />\r\nInvestigate past employment history<br />\r\nVerify if the candidate has ever been involved in fraud or any other criminal activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.2.7 Appointment of candidate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chairman of the Board shall exercise the Board of Directors&#39; authority in respect of the CEOs appointments. Upon appointment, the CEO shall receive a letter of appointment, which shall include the following provisions: -<br />\r\na) The names and addresses of the parties to the contract of employment;<br />\r\nb) Effective date of continuous service;<br />\r\nc) The title of the job that the employee is employed to do, the nature of the appointment, including reporting lines. A detailed job description, or terms of reference, shall be attached to the letter of appointment;<br />\r\nd) A statement adopting the provisions of the Human Resource Policies Manual;<br />\r\ne) The duty station to which the staff member shall be deployed at that time;<br />\r\nf) The nature of the appointment, which may be temporary, permanent or contractual;<br />\r\ng) The employees&rsquo; normal hours of work and the days of the week on which the work is to be performed;<br />\r\nh) The length of the probation period to be served;<br />\r\ni) The starting salary, details of salary payments, standard deductions, including any staff contributions (for example to pension scheme) and allowable benefits;<br />\r\nA non-national CEO shall be required to obtain a permit (residence/work permit) authorizing him/her to reside and work in Kenya. The Human Resource Manager or his/her designate shall obtain an assurance of the permit applicable which allows the staff member (in some cases a visa and work permit are both required) initially to enter the country to take up employment and residence. Musoni Kenya Limited shall assist the CEO to obtain all permits for himself and his/her family. All costs involved in the initial issue and in the renewal of the applicable permits and visas shall be borne by Musoni Kenya Limited.<br />\r\nNote: CEOs recruitment and selection is a Board responsibility. The CHRO acts a coordinator while the Board Chairman takes the lead.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3 Probation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.1 Staff members shall ordinarily be required to serve a period of probation upon initial appointment. The duration shall be specified in the letter of appointment, but will be for a minimum of six (6) months</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.2 An employee&#39;s supervisor shall evaluate the employee at the end of the probation period and recommend confirmation or otherwise. At least two weeks in advance of the termination of the probation period the staff member(s) concerned shall receive written advice, signed by the CEO or designate, confirming or terminating his/her appointment. (See Annex 6: Appraisal Form)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.3 Where an employee has not performed satisfactorily, the CHRO or his/her designate, in liaison with the staff member&#39;s supervisor, may extend the initial probation period, for a further period but in any case not exceeding 3 months, to accord the employee an opportunity to show improvement in any specific areas in his/her work or conduct. If the employee&rsquo;s performance is still not satisfactory the Management will either extend the probation for another 3 months or terminate the appointment in<br />\r\nwriting. No employee shall be on probation for more than 12 months aggregate period. For probation<br />\r\nextension of senior management positions, the CEO must notify and consult with the Board of</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Directors before the extension is granted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.4 After a staff member&#39;s probation has been extended, he/she will be appraised and if his/her performance is satisfactory, he/she will be confirmed. But if his/her performance is found to be below average or poor, his/her services will be terminated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.5 The employee shall be required to acknowledge receipt of the letter in writing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.6 During the probation period, either party may terminate the employment relationship by giving one month written notice of termination or by payment by Musoni Kenya Limited to the employee seven days&#39; wages in lieu of notice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.7 During the probationary period, a staff member will be eligible for standard employee benefits with the exception of staff loans and advances, Medical Scheme and Pension Scheme which will be granted upon confirmation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.3.8 During probation, a staff member will be entitled to sick leave. The period of employment under probation will be fully counted in respect to annual leave, but the staff member will not be entitled to<br />\r\nutilize annual leave in excess of ten working days during the probationary period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Human Resource Development</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited recognizes that the Human Resource is the key resource in the organization through which other resources can be fully and effectively utilized. MKL realizes that in order to attain a competitive advantage there is need to invest in developing the skills and competence of the Human Resource. Investment in staff members shall be necessary for both current and future development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.1 Musoni Kenya LTD shall endeavor to develop, improve the understanding, knowledge and skills of all staff members. This will enable staff members to perform with maximum efficiency and effectiveness; thereby enabling the company to achieve its set goals and objectives. Musoni Kenya Limited shall offer induction training to all staff members joining the organization. The purpose of induction shall be to welcome new staff members who are joining Musoni Kenya Limited and to give them the necessary information to enable them accustom themselves to the job. The employee shall be introduced to the work place and a job description given to him/her. He/she will also fill in all necessary documents and give information pertinent to his/her employment. A copy &#39;of the Employee Handbook will be provided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The staff member shall be given a brief description of Musoni Kenya Limited basic conditions of employment, hours of work, statutory holidays, organizational mission, goals and objectives, organizational governance, management structure and the overall institutional operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where the new employee&#39;s job requires liaison with other departments, the staff member will be accorded opportunity to familiarize himself/herself with the respective departments including a visit to selected branches. The HR Department is responsible for the successful induction of new staff member.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.2 On the job training will be carried out for the staff members at various stages of employment to ensure that there is proper understanding of the tasks of all staff members as outlined in their job descriptions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.3 Musoni Kenya Limited shall promote the long term learning and development of staff members on a continual basis internally as well as externally. Adequate planning and budgetary provisions shall be done where appropriate, in order to achieve this policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.4 Development of the Human Resource shall be done in such a way that it is directly relevant to the core business of Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.5 Fairness and equity shall be essential in the Implementation of this policy. Every staff member shall have a right to access to support and to available resources and opportunities to enable them develop and fulfill their responsibilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.6 Training Needs Assessment (TNA) shall be conducted on a regular basis by the Training</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Function, Senior Management, supervisors, and line managers, using any of the following methods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Direct observations<br />\r\n&bull; Questionnaires</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Performance appraisals</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Informal discussions</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Interviews</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.7 Training Needs Assessment results will be compiled and presented to management for review and approval.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.8 Musoni Kenya Limited shall maintain a training function to support the implementation of this policy. This function will be responsible for the following: -</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Identifying training needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Planning the implementation of training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Identification of resources.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Designing courses relevant to address the needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Conducting training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Evaluating training and development outcomes to staff members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Provision of feedback to management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Further development of Musoni Kenya Limited resource center.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Examining participants as appropriate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.9 This policy will be reviewed periodically and its implementation will be subject to availability of funds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.10 Further Professional Development:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff members are encouraged to pursue further studies in terms of professional development. Musoni Kenya Limited shall not fund such career development programs. All staff members taking evening classes shall be expected to do so after the official working hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.10.1 Work takes precedence over any other activity; therefore, no staff member shall leave Musoni</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kenya Limited urgent work unfinished to go and attend classes<br />\r\n5. PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1 Performance Appraisal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Performance appraisal is a critical instrument of management toward various decision related to development, retention and effective utilization of available Human Resource, including defining fair rewarding system in return to the excellent performers. Consequently, an effective appraisal system will help us to assess our staff against defined objectives. It gives us the chance to give constructive feedback and to praise staff for their good work, which in turn will make them feel valued. It also offers the opportunity to:<br />\r\nAddress problems related to performance<br />\r\nDiscuss apparent weaknesses<br />\r\nFind possible alternative solutions available in place.<br />\r\nProvides a chance to define further objectives for our employees.<br />\r\nEvery employee must be appraised/evaluated at least twice per year i.e. in January and July of every year. However, employees under probation will be appraised at the end of the probation period which is 6 months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to have an effective, efficient and fair appraisal system, it&#39;s useful to set out clear objectives, ideally with quantifiable performance targets, so our staff understands what we expect of them. Defining performance targets to the staff will help in the following;<br />\r\nIt will ensure that every employee&#39;s contribution fits into the overall aims and target of the business<br />\r\nProvide clear and precise direction to both supervisor and employee<br />\r\nIt will help individual employees better understand their aims and role within the business<br />\r\nForm common frame of reference around which the supervisor and the employee can effectively communicate.<br />\r\nIt will Create standards to measure the quantity and quality of employees&#39; work<br />\r\nHelps to monitor the success of the department and its contribution to the business as a whole.<br />\r\nIt also helps to Identify ways to make the Department run more efficiently</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.1 How to Set Performance Targets (setting goals)<br />\r\nAt every end of a year the line manager / supervisor should set out at least 5 key performance indicators for individual employees, from which they will be appraised their performance in the subsequent year. However, in order to set out sensible and viable key performance indicators, following issues are very important;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Agreeable Goals and Targets<br />\r\nLine manager or supervisor should make sure that employees are well and strongly involved in identifying the performance indicators and agree them. This will help to make the employees feel being part of the decision hence increase their commitment to the goals or targets in hand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Targets/ Goals V&rsquo;s Job description<br />\r\nThe Performance indicators or Targets should follow the key areas of performance as shown in the job description and the key aspects of the job. If the goals and targets put in place seem unbearable to the employee, then break goals down into smaller goals, or sub goals / objectives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Goals and Targets Should be &ldquo;SMART&rdquo;<br />\r\nAll set out targets and goals should be SMART, in the following sense;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>S Specific. Avoid being vague. For example, &quot;work harder&quot; does not indicate in what aspects of the job the employee should put more effort in. However, mention of customer relations, numeracy accuracy, processing of applications, team relations etc. are specific.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>M Measurable. The expected behaviour and results should be quantifiable. For example improve on customer relations is not measurable. However, &quot;visit three major customers a week&quot; is measurable. Another example is; &quot;reduce departmental costs by 15%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Agreed. Targets and objectives that are not agreed between the manager and employee have little chance of being achieved. Avoid giving easy targets. Avoid giving the same targets to all your staff unless you perceive them to have equal abilities. Agree with the employee based on the business unit objectives and the employee&#39;s current competencies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R Realistic. Both manager and employee should ensure that the set targets are achievable. Consider the employee&#39;s abilities and potential, work environment, motivation levels and anticipated obstacles and availability of important resources to meet the goals agreed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>T Time bound. Targets that do not indicate by when they should be achieved are weak targets. They have little chance of being achieved. Put a time limit to the target. For example: &quot;Reduce number of customer complaints from 6 to 2&quot; is specific and measurable, but lacks in time restriction. That is, in what time span must this happen? &ldquo;Reduce number of customer complaints from 6 in a week to 2 has a time limit&quot;.<br />\r\nOther examples include: 1. Compile the customer report and present it by 15 July. 2. Prepare the staff-training programme and costs for input into the budget by the end of the financial year. 3 Reduce the departmental costs by 15% within the next 6 months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.2 The Appraisal Process<br />\r\nThe purpose of the Employee Performance Appraisal is to provide a regular, structured process for employees to receive feedback on the previous review period and to plan for the next review period.<br />\r\nStep 1 &ndash; Employee Performance Appraisal Forms are issued to Supervisors<br />\r\nStep 2 &ndash; Supervisor and employee agree key tasks to be reviewed, and agree date for the Appraisal Meeting which is a minimum of 2 weeks later<br />\r\nStep 3 &ndash; Employee completes relevant sections of the form and passes it to the supervisor a minimum of 2 days before the meeting<br />\r\nStep 4 &ndash; Supervisor completes relevant sections of the form<br />\r\nStep 5 &ndash; The appraisal meeting takes place at which supervisor and employee discuss their comments and complete Section 4 of the form together<br />\r\nStep 6 &ndash; Employee, supervisor and reviewing manager add any comments in Section 5 and sign the form<br />\r\nStep 7 &ndash; No later than 1 week after the appraisal meeting, the completed, signed form is passed to the HR department</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.3 The Appraisal Form<br />\r\nThe purpose of the Employee Performance Appraisal Form is to ensure that the discussion between the employee and their supervisor is documented clearly and that both employee and supervisor have an opportunity to comment on the content.<br />\r\nThe form represents a record of the appraisal meeting and becomes a working document for the supervisor and the employee, allowing each to check progress against the agreed action points.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.4 Scheduling and Holding a Performance Meeting<br />\r\nThe purpose of the Appraisal Meeting is for the employee and supervisor to:-<br />\r\nReview the employee&rsquo;s performance over the review period<br />\r\nClarify comments<br />\r\nDiscuss different points of view<br />\r\nAgree actions for the next review period<br />\r\nTell the employee that you are initiating a scheduled performance review. Remind him/her of what is involved in the process. Schedule the meeting about two weeks in advance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Distribute the performance appraisal forms to staff at least two weeks before the actual performance meeting, for the staff to fill their inputs on their respective areas as prescribed in the forms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before getting in a performance meeting, Appraiser should have sufficient contact with the employee to be making valid judgments. Don&rsquo;t comment on employee&rsquo;s race, sex, religion, nationality or a handicap or veteran status. Record major accomplishment, exhibited strength and weaknesses according to the dimensions on the appraisal form, and suggest actions and training or development to improve performance. Use example of behavior wherever you can in the appraisal to help avoid counting on hearsay. Always address behavior, not characteristic of personality. Be sure to address only the behavior of that employee, rather than behavior of other employee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Performance Appraisal Meeting:<br />\r\nState the meeting&rsquo;s goals of exchanging feedback and coming to actions plans, where necessary.<br />\r\nLet the employee speak first and give their input and then respond with your own input.<br />\r\nThen discuss areas where you disagree. Attempt to avoid defensiveness; admitting what you feel at the present time helps a great deal.<br />\r\nDiscuss behavior and not personalities.<br />\r\nEncourage participation and be supportive.<br />\r\nTry to end the meeting on a positive note.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.1.5 Completing the Appraisal Form<br />\r\nSection Action Required Person Responsible<br />\r\n1 &ndash; Key Performance Indicators (KPI)<br />\r\nAppraisal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Identification of up to 5 key tasks<br />\r\nEmployee Supervisor<br />\r\nDescription to include why these tasks are important, how they have performed in the task including individual effort and initiative involved, the resulting output.<br />\r\nAchievement must be stressed rather than efforts and initiatives involved<br />\r\nEmployees are encouraged to use examples<br />\r\nEmployee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comment on employee&rsquo;s performance (optional)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisor<br />\r\nComment if any on Supervisor&rsquo;s rating in this part (optional)<br />\r\nEmployee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &ndash; Behavioural Appraisal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comment on employee&rsquo;s behaviour<br />\r\nSupervisor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: the People Management section is only to be used for employees with people management responsibilities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employees may add comments regarding the supervisor&rsquo;s comments in relation this section</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee<br />\r\nSupervisor may put additional comments on Employee&rsquo;s behaviour ( Optional) Supervisor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &ndash; Skills Profile<br />\r\nSkills in which the employee is strong should include:<br />\r\nTechnical skills that are relevant to the role, in which the employee is strong<br />\r\nPotential strengths that the employee could bring to the role<br />\r\nSkills that are not required for the current role but which may be relevant in future roles</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Skills needed to enhance effectiveness should include:<br />\r\nPotential areas for training, development or experiences that may enhance the employee&rsquo;s performance<br />\r\nNote that the HR department will use these recommendations to establish consolidated training needs with priority areas which may be included in the annual training calendar</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee<br />\r\nSupervisor&rsquo;s comments (optional) Supervisor<br />\r\n4- Overall Rating and Comments The overall performance assessment rating in this section relates to the performance rating which best summarises the Staff member&#39;s performance over the period of review.<br />\r\nSupervisor will complete the overall rating based on individual ratings in section 1 and 2, using the percentage scale.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: Overall Score average should be measured as shown hereunder;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>101% and above = Good (G)<br />\r\n76% - 100% = Satisfactory (S)<br />\r\n51% - 75% = Partly Satisfactory (PS)<br />\r\n50% and below = Unsatisfactory (U)<br />\r\nThe ratings will be rated by supervisor on the space provided on the right side, and will be rated as follows;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rating</p>\r\n\r\n<p>101% - and above<br />\r\nTo receive Good performance requires a level of performance above the expected and shown in the job description.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>76% - 100% Rating (Fully Satisfactory)<br />\r\nThe rating of Fully Satisfactory means that in all respects the Staff member has met the standards of Performance required.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>51% - 75% (Partly satisfactory)<br />\r\nThe rating Partly Satisfactory means staff has not reached satisfactory level, however is relatively near the margin to reach the satisfactory level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>50% and below (Unsatisfactory)<br />\r\nThe rating Unsatisfactory should be regarded as constructive criticism and be accompanied by helpful suggestions on ways to improve. If a Staff member is rated as Unsatisfactory and the rating does not improve during the subsequent action plan period, then such a Staff member can be considered unsatisfactory. In such cases the supervisor should seek the advice of the Human Resources Department. We would expect a personal development plan for such an employee to be included in Section 3 of the performance assessment form. The Supervisor could also recommend that the staff be place on PIP.<br />\r\nSupervisor<br />\r\nSupervisor&rsquo;s comments on Employee&rsquo;s (Optional) average score Supervisor<br />\r\nEmployee comments on Supervisor&rsquo;s Ratings( Optional) Employee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &ndash; Key Performance Goals<br />\r\nIdentification of at least 3 performance goals for the next review period. Goals should reflect:<br />\r\nThe increased skill level achieved as a result of training or development activities included in section 3<br />\r\nAny potential strengths identified in Section 3<br />\r\nAction required for any section of the form where a less than satisfactory level of performance has been identified, who is responsible for taking action, and deadlines for such action<br />\r\nAny personal action points generated during the appraisal meeting</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee Supervisor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &ndash; Overall Comments and Signatures<br />\r\nAny comments that are not included elsewhere on the form, may be included by the employee, supervisor and reviewing manage<br />\r\nEmployee, Supervisor, Reviewing Manager</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All parties are required to sign the form<br />\r\nSignatures are evidence that the appraisal meeting took place and do not necessarily signify agreement<br />\r\nIf there are any disagreements, the employee and supervisor should note these on the form then sign off their comments<br />\r\nIf disagreements cannot be resolved by the employee and supervisor, the HR department will follow up on them, with any appeals being brought to the reviewing manager<br />\r\nEmployee, Supervisor, Reviewing Manager</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any employee that falls below 75% of the total appraisal outcome will be placed under the Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) by the HR in consultation with the immediate supervisor.<br />\r\n5.2 PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENT PLAN</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.1Introduction<br />\r\nA performance improvement plan is a formal process used by supervisors to help employees improve performance or modify behaviour. The performance improvement plan or PIP identifies performance and/or behavioural issues that need to be corrected and creates a written plan of action to guide the improvement and/or corrective action.<br />\r\n5.2.2 Objectives of PIP<br />\r\nFundamentally, a PIP is a structured communication tool designed to facilitate constructive discussion between the employee and the supervisor. The key objectives will be:-<br />\r\nTo correct workplace behaviors affecting performance, productivity or staff relationships.<br />\r\nTo provide employees an opportunity to correct a situation rather than implementing a more serious step in the disciplinary process.<br />\r\nAn effective PIP will:<br />\r\nSpecifically identify the performance to be improved or the behavior to be corrected.<br />\r\nProvide clear expectations and metrics about the work to be performed or behavior that must change.<br />\r\nIdentify the support and resources available to help the employee make the required improvements.<br />\r\nEstablish a plan for reviewing the employee&#39;s progress and providing feedback to the employee for the duration of the PIP.<br />\r\nSpecify possible consequences if performance standards as identified in the PIP are not met.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.3 Eligibility<br />\r\nAny staff can be placed on PIP up to and including Supervisors/Managers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.2.4 PIP Process for WCOs<br />\r\nFailure to achieve the following individual KPIs targets might result to PIP:<br />\r\nTotal Funded Borrowers<br />\r\nOutstanding Loan Book<br />\r\nGroup/Client Registration<br />\r\nLoan Disbursements<br />\r\nPAR (Should be below 3%)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NB: For other support functions, we shall consider individual KPIs as per the Job Description.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phase 1 (Communication Phase)<br />\r\nWhen an employee is not performing or meeting expectations, the Branch Managers have at their disposal several options to correct the behavior. They will rely on corrective actions such as verbal warnings, continuous support and caution.<br />\r\nAt this stage, the BM must clearly communicate to the employee about the intention to place him/her on PIP if performance does not improve within 30 days and communicate the same to the COO and HR.<br />\r\nIn case the Branch Manager fails to initiate PIP discussions with a poor performing employee, the COO or HR have the right to instruct the BM to take this initiative.<br />\r\nPhase 2 (Yellow Phase)<br />\r\nIf the employee does not improve within a period of 1 month from when the communication was done; PIP will be administered. During this period the Branch manager will develop a growth plan for the WCO using the existing PIP templates and forward the filled in templates to the HR. The Branch Manager will also issue an official 1st warning letter which will be placed on the employees file.<br />\r\nPAR<br />\r\nIf PAR is still above 5%, the WCO may disburse loans to his or her repeat borrowers but not to new ones. New clients will be handed over to other WCOs under the supervision of the Branch Manager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phase 3 (Orange Phase)<br />\r\nIf after the 2nd month the WCO is still below the agreed target, he/she will be moved to the Orange Phase. At this stage, the Branch Manager will issue the 2nd warning letter which will be placed on the employees file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PAR<br />\r\nIf PAR is still above 5%, the WCO will focus 100% of his/her effort on recovery and shall not disburse any loans. Both repeat and new loans shall be disbursed by other WCOs. The WCO will be closely monitored and must have daily meetings with the Branch manager to discuss the daily action plan and progress made on the previous day&rsquo;s plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phase 4 (Red Phase)<br />\r\nDuring the Red Phase, the WCO will have spent a total of 3 months in PIP. If performance is still wanting, the WCO will meet the Performance Review Committee comprised of the Branch Manager, COO, HR and any other member of the Senior Management. During this meeting, the committee will reach a decision on how best to manage the WCOs portfolio going forward. Below is guidance on how the Review Committee should be administered: -<br />\r\nObjective is to reach a decision to revive the portfolio growth and ensure that Musoni is well protected.<br />\r\nThe Committee should look at how the WCO has developed from the day he/she was put on PIP<br />\r\nIf there is evidence that the WCOs performance was negatively affected for reasons beyond their control, the WCO will be given some more time to work out the portfolio. The minutes of the meeting will form the basis of the extension which should not exceed 2 months.<br />\r\nIf inadequate performance was achieved due to WCOs negligence, he/she will face further disciplinary action up to and including termination of service. The minutes of the committee will form the basis for this decision. Minutes of the meeting should include information on the following: -<br />\r\nIs the lack of portfolio growth and high PAR the result of WCOs negligence or policy violation?<br />\r\nWhy didn&rsquo;t the WCO meet the agreed performance standards?<br />\r\nWhat is the quality of the WCOs performance in terms of PAR management, customer service, interpersonal skills and teamwork?<br />\r\nIn case the employee is dissatisfied with the decision of the Performance Review Committee, he/she has 7 calendar days to appeal to the CEO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An employee cannot be on PIP more than once in 1 calendar year. In case an employee&rsquo;s performance deteriorates after reinstatement from PIP then Musoni will have no other option but to terminate the contract of employment without further notice.<br />\r\n6. SUCCESSION PLANNING<br />\r\n6.1 Introduction<br />\r\nSuccession Planning is an on-going process that identifies necessary competencies, and then works to assess, develop, and retain a talent pool of employees, in order to ensure continuity of leadership for all critical positions.<br />\r\n6.2 Objectives<br />\r\nTo proactively identify, assess and develop potential candidates for succession in the organization.<br />\r\nTo shield the business from unexpected circumstances and outline contingency plans.<br />\r\nTo ensure that the organization is not left in a vulnerable position.<br />\r\nTo determine the critical positions and build bench strength for current and future need.<br />\r\n6.3 Steps to Execute Succession Planning<br />\r\nIdentify key/critical positions in each Department or Branch.<br />\r\nDetermine the required job competencies for selected key positions.<br />\r\nDetermine the likelihood of these positions getting vacant in future.<br />\r\nAnalyse and match the competencies between the selected positions and employees who closely match the required competencies.<br />\r\nDecide on two successors for each position based on performance and potential.<br />\r\nEmployee with the closest match to competency requirements of the position will be the first successor to the position.<br />\r\nThe second successor will be the one with the second closest competency match to the position requirements.<br />\r\nProvide visibility, stretch assignments, growth projects and internal development opportunities for successors.<br />\r\nEnsure an effective pipeline is in place and reassess it against changing organizational needs and priorities.<br />\r\nPut a plan in place to address critical gaps.<br />\r\nGain support and commitment at all levels.<br />\r\n6.4 Succession Factors<br />\r\nPerformance<br />\r\nDemonstrated performance over the last 2 years based on attaining goals for the given year.<br />\r\nPotential - Capability to take on greater levels of responsibility given reasonable development opportunities.<br />\r\nRetention Risk - Impact to the business if the individual exits the organization and mitigation strategies.<br />\r\nReadiness - Assessment of candidates&rsquo; readiness: is he/she ready now, ready in 1-2 years, ready in 3-5 years.<br />\r\nGrowth and Development - Opportunities that can be provided to potential successors based on assessed gaps and readiness criteria, and completed succession charts for the critical roles.<br />\r\n6.5 Succession Summary Grids<br />\r\nName Performance Potential Retention Risk Readiness Actions/ Successor<br />\r\n(H, M, L) (H, M, L) (H, M, L) (Now, 1-2 years, 3-5 years) Development Plans (if candidate exits)<br />\r\n1<br />\r\n2<br />\r\n3<br />\r\n4<br />\r\n5<br />\r\n6<br />\r\nH - High<br />\r\nM - Medium<br />\r\nL &ndash; Low</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.6 Succession Chart (Sample)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 7: Candidates Profile Template &ndash; to be filled in by the candidates&rsquo; immediate supervisor and submitted to HR. The candidates&rsquo; development plan should be very clear.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7. CODE OF ETHICS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The code of ethics touches on moral principles in terms of integrity, competence, standards, honesty and devotion to work. Furthermore, it safeguards against conflict of interest in terms of personal investments and abuse of Musoni Kenya Limited resources, business gifts and affiliations, hospitality and confidentiality of information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Code of ethics reinforces the core values of Musoni Kenya Limited leading to achievement of the strategic objectives and thereby the realization of the mission and vision of Musoni Kenya Limited. Besides it instills and enforces discipline in individual employees and the institution as a corporate entity; thus portraying a positive image of the institution.<br />\r\n7.1 Conflict of interest<br />\r\nStaff members shall avoid any conflicts between their interests and those of Musoni Kenya Limited. The conflict of interest policy is to ensure that the company&rsquo;s financial position, integrity and reputation are not compromised. The fundamental principal guiding the implementation of this policy is that no Musoni employee should have or appear to have personal interests or relationships that conflict with the best interest of Musoni. This conflict of interest policy is not exhaustive but examples of conflict of interest are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. An employee has directly or indirectly a financial or non-financial interest in a company with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction or a company which is in competition with Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. He/she has a partner, child, parent or relative with a financial or non-financial interest in a company with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. He/she is a member of the Board, Managing Board or Supervisory Board or has a similar status with a company with which Musoni intends to enter into a transaction or which is Musoni&rsquo;s competitor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iv. Profiting personally e.g. through commissions, loans, expense reimbursements or other payments from any organizations seeking to do business with Musoni Limited or competes with Musoni Limited</p>\r\n\r\n<p>v. Holding an interest in or accepting free or discounted goods from any organization that does, or is seeking to do business with Musoni Limited, by any employee who is in a position to directly or indirectly influence either Musoni&rsquo;s decision to do business or the terms upon which business would be done with that organization<br />\r\nvi. Be employed by (including a consultant) or serving on the board of any organization which does or is seeking to do business with Musoni Limited or which competes with Musoni Limited<br />\r\nConflict due to political activities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly, a staff member who is involved in political activities shall inform Management accordingly and if a staff member intends to run for a political office, he/she should first terminate his/her employment with Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conflict due to familial relations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employment of relatives is not allowed. Each employee shall immediately report to his superior any family relation up to the second degree (meaning first cousins, nephews and nieces) he has with other (potential) employees of Musoni. This is also the case if he intends to marry another (potential) employee of Musoni. In cases of close links, Musoni might decide to change or stop the function of either employee if that is in the interest of Musoni.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Duty of Disclosure</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the employee&rsquo;s responsibility to report to the immediate supervisor or the CHRO any actual or potential conflict that may exist between the employee and the company and to seek the company&rsquo;s written consent to continue to engage in the activity that poses actual or potential conflict interest with the company. The company will at its sole discretion allow or refuse the employee to continue with the activity.In the absence of a report, violations of the principles and standards contained in this policy shall be subject to discipline up to and including summary dismissal. The company shall have the final authority to determine the appropriate penalty for such violations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.2 Communication with the press</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A staff member, except with the prior express authorization of the Chief Executive Officer or designate, is forbidden to issue statements, or communicate with the press on Musoni Kenya Limited matters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.3 Unauthorized disclosure of information (Confidentiality)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff members shall exercise the utmost discretion in regard to matters of official business and shall not, without prior written permission from the immediate supervisor or designate, disclose any information known to them that has not been made public. Staff members shall at no time, including after the end of service with Musoni Kenya Limited, use such confidential information for personal or third party advantage, unless authorized by the Management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only designated and authorized staff members shall make statements or express opinions on behalf of the Management of Musoni Kenya Limited to the press and media, including electronic media.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.4 Personal Business</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conducting personal business using Musoni Kenya Limited office resources, including phones, computers, photocopiers, stationery and other equipment before, during or after office hours is not<br />\r\nallowed.<br />\r\n7.5 External commitments<br />\r\nBefore making any commitment, staff should disclose any possible part time employment, external consultancy and business activities that may interfere with their day to day work. A written approval from the Management must be obtained before an employee embarks on this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Failure to disclose or have approved external consultancies and commitments will be considered gross misconduct of staff. Members undertaking such activities will be subject to disciplinary action. Any external commitments in progress at the time this Employee Handbook go into effect, such as at the time of hiring, must be made known to Management and individually approved in writing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.6 Gifts and Favour</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A staff member shall inform his/her Supervisor if, in the course of or as a result of his/her work for Musoni Kenya Limited; he/she is offered an honor, favour or gift exceeding Kshs. 1,000. The Supervisor may decide that such honor, favor or gift be declined. No gift is acceptable as a reward for services to be rendered; but only as a token of appreciation for something already done. Gifts shall be received without any consideration and / or compromises in return.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.7 Intellectual property</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unless otherwise negotiated, Musoni Kenya Limited is the inherent copyright owner of the data and documentation that any staff member or consultant may have developed, gathered, reviewed and/or analyzed on behalf of Musoni Kenya Limited and during Musoni Kenya Limited contracted time. A staff member shall undertake both during and at the end of service with Musoni Kenya Limited, not to<br />\r\npublish such data without giving due credit to their origin and to Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8. FAIR AND RESPECTFUL TREATMENT OF MUSONI CLIENTS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni employees should treat clients with honesty, fairness and respect. Clients should be treated responsibly and must never be discriminated on personal characteristics of gender, ethnicity or affiliations (religion &amp; politics). Non-discriminatory treatment is important for providing access to financial services for all clients who can use them and for building client confidence in the fairness of Musoni. Examples of inappropriate practices include:<br />\r\nOffensive Language and threats<br />\r\nUnethical seizure of collateral<br />\r\nViolation of privacy<br />\r\nDiscrimination<br />\r\nCareless debt extension<br />\r\nCorruption, theft and kickbacks<br />\r\nMusoni will ensure that clients who are mistreated can complain to the institution through the provided channels and have their complaint addressed. Any employee who does not treat our clients responsibly shall be violating Musoni&rsquo;s rules and regulations and will be subject to further disciplinary action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9. ATTENDANCE AND LEAVE PROCEDURES</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each employee is important to the overall success of our operation. When you are not here, someone else must do your job. Consequently, you are expected to report to work on time at the scheduled start of the workday. Reporting to work on time means that you are ready to start work, not just arriving at work, at your scheduled starting time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company depends on its employees to be at work at the times and locations scheduled. Excessive absenteeism and/or tardiness will lead to disciplinary action, up to and including termination of service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.1 Working hours</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The regularly scheduled workday for our business office is: Monday to Friday, 8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m with a one-hour lunch break between 1:00pm and 2:00pm. These start and end times are only guidelines; you will be expected from time to time to work outside working hours to complete your daily tasks. You will be expected to observe punctuality at all times. If for some reason you shall be absent from duty, adequate notice should be given to your immediate supervisor. In this case the following leave procedures will apply: -</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.2 Leave<br />\r\nEmployees will be entitled to 25 annual leave days (working days) after twelve consecutive months of service. At the beginning of every year, a leave roster will be drawn up to avoid people being on leave at the same time. The company reserves the right to determine the appropriate time when such leave shall be taken.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.2.1. Annual Leave Procedures</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All supervisors shall ensure that they have agreed upon a leave schedule for all staff under their supervision at least six months in advance.<br />\r\nEvery beginning of the month each supervisor shall review the above plan with their subordinates and any employee scheduled to go on leave during the said month shall make an application through the ESS (HRIS System). The application shall be made and approved before 5th of every month.<br />\r\nIn case of an emergency, an employee can apply for annual leave at any time of the month. The only emergencies that will be considered in Musoni are hospitalization, accidents or bereavement.<br />\r\nOnce leave has been granted, the employee will get a system notification via email clearly indicating the start date and the end date.<br />\r\nThe HR department in collaboration with IT department shall monitor all approved leave in the HRIS and shall disable any staff who commences leave from the Core Banking System. The employees&rsquo; rights shall be reinstated upon his/her return from leave and supported by a formal request of reinstating rights form the immediate supervisor.<br />\r\nNo one will be allowed to carry forward more than 10 leave days of a particular year to the next calendar year. The system will automatically forfeit the excess days come 31st December of every year.<br />\r\nWhere an official holiday falls within an approved annual leave period, that holiday shall not be considered as part of the annual leave.<br />\r\nNew employees will be eligible to apply for leave if they have worked for more than three months. Only in special cases of emergencies will one be allowed to apply leave before the expiry of three months.<br />\r\nFor school going employees, examination leave will be deducted from one&rsquo;s annual leave.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.2.2. Maternity/Paternity leave<br />\r\nFemale employees are entitled to 3 months (90 calendar days) maternity leave at full pay. In addition, the female employee is also entitled to her annual leave which can be taken before or after the maternity leave. A staff member shall apply for maternity leave at least one month before the expected delivery date (EDD) to allow time for proper handing over and due notice to be given to a staff member or reliever who may need to step in her absence. It is expected that the employee will resume duty after the expiry of her leave and continue with her normal duties. However, should a female employee require maternity leave during the probationary period, her probation will be deferred by the same number of days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Male employees are entitled to 2 weeks (14 calendar days) paternity leave. Application for Paternity leave should be done two weeks before the commencement date. Application for paternity leave must be supported by a copy of birth notification form which must be provided immediately after resuming from leave. Paternity leave can only be taken once in a year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.2.3. Sick leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The employee will report before 09:30 to his or her supervisor in case of sickness or absence from work. After two consecutive months of service, an employee shall be entitled to a sick leave of not less than 7 (seven) days with full pay and thereafter to sick leave of 7 (seven) days with half pay in each period of twelve consecutive months of service. The 12 consecutive months commence from the date of employment and the anniversary thereof. A medical certificate signed by a duly qualified medical practitioner must be produced by the employee to confirm the inability to work and the duration of the incapacity for absence exceeding 3 consecutive working days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If an employee requires additional sick off other than what has been provided, he/she can request an additional period not exceeding two months of sick leave without pay which must be approved by the Management. If after the second month, the sickness of the employee still continues, Musoni Kenya Limited will be entitled to terminate the contract of employment on medical grounds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.2.5. Compassionate Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event of the death of spouse, own child, sibling or parent, an employee shall be entitled to paid compassionate leave of not more than 5 working days per year, without any deductions from the annual leave. Any additional days needed for the above reason will be deducted from the employee&rsquo;s<br />\r\nannual leave.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*In the event that an employee is absent from work to take care of an ailing child or spouse, the days taken will be recovered from one&rsquo;s annual leave.<br />\r\n10. CUSTODY AND RETENTION OF STAFF MEMBERS RECORDS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All staff members&#39; documents and/or records shall be in the custody of and retained by the CHRO and they shall be kept in strictest confidence. It is your responsibility to provide current information regarding your address, telephone number, insurance beneficiaries, change in dependents, marital status, academic achievements etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, employee personnel files are the property of the company, and do not belong to the employee. However, upon request, the company will provide employees with copies of performance evaluations and other performance-related documents that the employee has previously received. Employees will have their job performance reviewed after every six months by their immediate supervisor. Copies of performance records will be placed in individual files.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10. STANDARDS AND EXPECTATIONS AT WORKPLACE<br />\r\nThe company believes in maintaining safe and healthy working conditions for our employees. However, to achieve our goal of providing a safe workplace, each employee must be safety conscious. We have established the following policies and procedures that allow us to provide safe and healthy working conditions. We expect each employee to follow these policies and procedures, to act safely, and to report unsafe conditions to his or her supervisor in a timely manner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.1 Reporting Unsafe Conditions or Practices</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employees are expected to continually be on the lookout for unsafe working conditions or practices. If you observe an unsafe condition, you should warn others, if possible, and report that condition to your supervisor immediately. If you have a question regarding the safety of your workplace and practices, ask your supervisor for clarification.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you observe a coworker using an unsafe practice, you are expected to mention this to the coworker and to your supervisor. Likewise, if a coworker brings to your attention an unsafe practice you may be using, please thank the coworker and make any necessary adjustments to what you are doing. Safety at work is a team effort.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.2 Reporting an Injury</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employees are required to report any injury, accident, or safety hazard immediately to their supervisor(s). Minor cuts or abrasions must be treated on the spot. A first aid box will be maintained in every work station to take care of minor injuries. More serious injuries or accidents will be treated accordingly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.3 Care of Company property and Supplies</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All employees are expected to take care of all company property and supplies provided to them. You are responsible for maintaining this property in proper working condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Neglect, theft, and/or destruction of the company&rsquo;s property are grounds for disciplinary action, up to</p>\r\n\r\n<p>and including termination of service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.4 Smoking at the Workplace</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company&rsquo;s policy is to provide smoke-free environments for our employees, customers, and the general public. Smoking of any kind is prohibited inside our office and on our worksites. Employees may smoke on scheduled breaks or during meal times, as long as they do so outside the office.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.5 Violence and Weapons<br />\r\nThe company believes in maintaining a safe and healthy workplace, in part by promoting open, friendly, and supportive working relationships among all employees. Violence or threats of violence have no place in our business. Violence is not an effective solution to any problem. Employees are strictly prohibited from bringing any weapons to the office. Neither threats of violence nor fighting will be tolerated. Furthermore, if you have a problem that is creating stress or otherwise making you agitated, you are encouraged to discuss it with your supervisor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You are expected to immediately report to your supervisor any violation of this policy. Any employee found threatening another employee, supplier or client, fighting, and/or carrying weapons to the office will be subject to disciplinary action, up to and including termination of service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.6 Drug-Free Workplace</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company does not tolerate the presence of illegal drugs in our workplace. The use, possession, distribution, or sale of controlled substances such as drugs or alcohol, or being under the influence of such controlled substances is strictly prohibited while on duty, while on the company&rsquo;s premises. The use of illegal drugs is a threat to us all because it promotes problems with safety, customer service, productivity, and our ability to survive and prosper as a business. Violation of this policy will result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination of service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.7 Appearance and Dressing<br />\r\nTo present a business-like, professional image to our customers and the public, all employees are required to wear appropriate clothing on the job. Employees should be neatly groomed and clothes should be clean and well ironed. Leisure clothes such as cut-offs or halter tops are not acceptable attire for the business office. The company will provide employees with shirts bearing the Company&rsquo;s logo (corporate wear), which employees are expected to wear as appropriate in the business office. Jeans and casual trousers are also not allowed from Monday to Thursday, they can only be worn on Fridays.<br />\r\n11. REMUNERATION AND BENEFITS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.1Salaries<br />\r\nMusoni Kenya Limited shall pay a monthly salary to all staff. Salary shall be payable monthly in arrears by the end of each month, after deducting all legal amounts as required by law. The Board of Directors shall approve salary levels and the related structures. Consideration shall be given to prevailing market rates, inflationary changes and cost of living. All staff members&#39; salaries will be based on this salary structure. The Salary Structure is a framework for a transparent salaries and career path for all positions at Musoni Kenya (see Annex 9 - Current Salary Structure).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In determining a staff member&#39;s entry point into a particular level, his/her qualifications, past experience and general competence shall be considered. New staff on probation will be placed on the structure but will attract 90% of the salary. They will be entitled to 100% salary upon confirmation. If a<br />\r\nnew staff is hired on any other day other than the 1st day of the month, then his/her salary shall be computed according to the number of days worked in the month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Salaries appropriate to each level shall be monitored regularly and reviewed periodically. This review will be dependent on Musoni Kenya Limited financial position. The objective of the salary review shall be to ensure conformation with the industry remuneration scales and to take into account any increase in the cost of living.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.2 Payroll Administration<br />\r\nMusoni Kenya has outsourced the payroll calculation to a payroll agency by the name Mansoft Limited. Payroll preparation is a shared role between the HR Department and Finance Department.<br />\r\nHR ensures that people are paid correctly and on time by submitting monthly payroll changes in relation to additional staff, staff exits, confirmations, promotions, appointments and loan deductions. For a new employee to be included in the payroll, the following details must be submitted to the Chief Finance Officer or designate by the 18th day of every month.<br />\r\nFull name of the employee<br />\r\nDate of Employment<br />\r\nID Number<br />\r\nPIN Number<br />\r\nNSSF Number<br />\r\nNHIF Number<br />\r\nBank Account Number<br />\r\nBasic Salary and allowances<br />\r\nAppointments/ promotions must be supported by official appointment letters signed by the CEO.<br />\r\nOnce all the changes have been compiled, the HR will then send a soft copy folder of all the changes by email and also submit signed hard copy documents to the Chief Finance Officer for further payroll preparation and authorization as documented in the Accounting Manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.3 Salary Advances<br />\r\nAn employee may apply for a salary advance when faced with emergency situations. Emergencies include death of a close family member or hospitalization of a close relative. This money will be given for compassionate related reasons only. The employee will need to request for the same in writing and forward the letter to the CHRO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The amount of salary advanced to any one staff will depend on the salary; the borrower must remain with at least &frac12; (half) of the net salary after computing all other deductions appearing on the pay slip in a month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.3.1 Staff Loans<br />\r\nMusoni provides attractive loan benefits to confirmed employees for both professional and personal development. The current loan facilities include: -<br />\r\nUnsecured loan facilities<br />\r\nEducational loan facility<br />\r\nCar loan facility for supervisors<br />\r\nPlot purchase and mortgage<br />\r\nLoan application forms and product specs will be provided by the HR department. Terms and conditions apply.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.4 Performance Based Bonus Scheme</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.4.1Bonus Objectives<br />\r\nThe revised bonus scheme is designed to motivate staff to achieve high performance levels, change behaviours and attitudes. The main objectives of the bonus scheme are as follows:<br />\r\nThe bonus should be aligned with the strategic objectives and growth of the Institution<br />\r\nMotivate staff to meet and exceed their monthly target.<br />\r\nSimple to calculate<br />\r\nFair &amp; transparent<br />\r\nPay bonus monthly<br />\r\nReward Achievement and Performance.<br />\r\n11.4.2 Target Staff<br />\r\nWe shall include only the WCOs and the BMs in the initial phase and as soon as we have reached Operational Break Even Point we will develop an Annual Performance based Bonus for Head Office Staff and Support Staff in the branches i.e. Customer Service Advisors.<br />\r\nThe following will also apply:-<br />\r\nStaff must be confirmed to earn a bonus<br />\r\nA female employee on maternity leave cannot earn a bonus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.4.3 Bonus Calculation for WCOs (GL)<br />\r\nThe revised bonus scheme puts into consideration 4 key variables namely number of disbursements, OLB, Total Funded Borrowers (TFB) &amp; PAR. The PAR section is a deduction and is designed to be punitive.<br />\r\nNumber of Disbursements<br />\r\nThe monthly target will be a minimum of 40 disbursements. If the WCO exceeds the minimum monthly target, he/she will be rewarded for each loan in excess of 40 per month. Disbursements will include Wepesi Loans.<br />\r\nLD= Loan Disbursements&gt;40&times;Kshs.200<br />\r\nOutstanding Loan Balance (OLB)<br />\r\nA WCO will earn 0.21% of the value of his/her outstanding loan portfolio above Kshs. 5M.<br />\r\nOlB=Outstanding Loan Balance&gt;Kshs 5 million&times;0.21%<br />\r\nTotal Funded Borrowers (TFB)<br />\r\nThe revised bonus scheme has been designed to spur growth and motivate staff to meet and exceed their monthly targets. For Musoni to reach operational breakeven point, each WCO should have achieved at least 330 Total Funded Borrowers. To encourage our WCOs to keep growing their client base, this variable will be treated as follows:-<br />\r\nTotal Funded Borrowers %age of Bonus Earnings<br />\r\n&lt;200 0%<br />\r\n&gt;200&lt;231 20%<br />\r\n&gt;232&lt;263 40%<br />\r\n&gt;264&lt;295 60%<br />\r\n&gt;296&lt;330 80%<br />\r\n&lt;331 100%</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Portfolio at Risk (PAR)<br />\r\nThe Arrears section of the bonus scheme is a deduction and is designed to be punitive. For every 1% of PAR&gt;1 (otherwise known as PAR Total) the bonus payout is reduced by 20%. It follows that at PAR Of 5% the whole bonus is wiped out (100%) as follows.<br />\r\nPAR Total % of Bonus Awarded<br />\r\nPAR&gt;5% 0 bonus &amp; PIP<br />\r\nPAR =5% 0 bonus &amp; Lending Stop<br />\r\nPAR =4% 20% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =3% 40% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =2% 60% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =1% 80% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =0% 100% bonus<br />\r\n11.4.4 Bonus Calculation for Individual Loan Officers (ILOs)<br />\r\nIL is a fairly new product that has been developed in 2013. Our intention is to grow the IL loan book by 50% of the total loan book by the end of 2014. The bonus will put into consideration 4 main variables as follows:-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Total Funded Borrowers (TFB)<br />\r\nThe minimum thresh hold will be 35 clients. For an ILO to be eligible for the bonus, he/she must have achieved at least 35 Total Funded Borrowers.<br />\r\nOutstanding Loan Balance (OLB)<br />\r\nAn ILO will earn 0.21% of the value of his/her outstanding loan portfolio above Kshs. 5.0M.<br />\r\nOLB=Outstanding Loan Balance&gt;Kshs 5.0 million X 0.21%<br />\r\nNumber of Disbursements<br />\r\nThe monthly target will be a minimum of 7 disbursements. If the ILO exceeds the minimum monthly target, he/she will be rewarded for each loan in excess of 7 per month.<br />\r\nLD= Loan Disbursements&gt;7 x Kshs.200<br />\r\nPortfolio at Risk (PAR)<br />\r\nThe Arrears section of the bonus scheme is a deduction and is designed to be punitive. For every 1% of PAR&gt;1 (otherwise known as PAR Total) the bonus payout is reduced by 20%. It follows that at PAR Of 5% the whole bonus is wiped out (100%) as follows.<br />\r\nPAR Total % of Bonus Awarded<br />\r\nPAR&gt;5% 0 bonus &amp; PIP<br />\r\nPAR =5% 0 bonus &amp; Lending Stop<br />\r\nPAR =4% 20% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =3% 40% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =2% 60% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =1% 80% bonus<br />\r\nPAR =0% 100% bonus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.4.5Bonus Calculation for Branch Managers (BM)<br />\r\nBranch Managers bear the greatest responsibility for achieving the branch target. The bonus calculation for each Branch Manager is related to the WCOs bonus at the branch they are working for.<br />\r\nBM Bonus = 10% of the total net bonus of WCOs in his/her branch.<br />\r\nFor Branches with Mashinanis, the Branch Manager will earn 10% of the total net bonus of WCOs in the Main Branch and 5% of the total net bonus of Mashinani WCOs.<br />\r\n11.4.6 Bonus Calculation for Mashinani SWCOs<br />\r\nMashinani SWCOs are the Individual Loan Officers in their respective Mashinanis. They also bear overall responsibility of the Mashinani in terms of leadership, supervision and portfolio growth. The bonus calculation for each SWCO is related to the WCOs bonus at the Mashinani they are working for.<br />\r\nMashinani SWCO Bonus = ILO Bonus + 5% of the total net bonus of WCOs in his/her Mashinani.<br />\r\n11.4.7 Conclusion<br />\r\nAn incentive scheme is a direct way of measuring performance based on specific targets set by the Institution. The revised bonus scheme has powerful effects on the performance and productivity of WCOs, ILOs, SWCOs and Branch Managers.<br />\r\nThis scheme relies on individual efficiency. It is expected to improve loan disbursements, grow OLB and reduce delinquency thereby boosting the overall performance of the institution.<br />\r\nNote:<br />\r\nThe Management will review the Bonus after every 6 months and ensure that the total amount paid out does not exceed 20% of the total WCO gross pay.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.5 Medical Cover</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You and your family (spouse and up to a maximum of four (4) children) will be included in a medical scheme that includes outpatient and inpatient cover after probationary period and confirmation of appointment. Members will be educated on the cover upon joining. In case a member of staff exceeds the limit provided, any extra monies shall be paid by the staff in case of outpatient or inpatient including maternity. The CHRO should be notified on any inpatient cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.6 Pension<br />\r\nOn successful completion of your probation, you will become eligible to participate in the staff contributory pension scheme. The company will contribute 10% of your basic salary towards Staff Contributory Pension Scheme, with an additional 5% to be contributed by you as a payroll deduction. This sum is payable to you upon termination of service or upon retirement as per Retirement Benefits Authority (RBA) terms and regulations.<br />\r\nThe company however reserves the right to change the nature, quality or level of these benefits at any time without reference to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12. DISCIPLINARY CODE AND PROCEDURE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.1 Policy Statement</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited is an institution requires our staff to ascribe to high standards of ethics and integrity. This code of discipline is therefore intended to ensure that staff are responsive to these standards. The purpose of this code therefore is not to set a list of dos and don&#39;ts but rather to establish an ethical base upon which Musoni Kenya Limited can achieve client satisfaction and shareholder value. It is therefore essential that staff are aware of the situations which could lead to disciplinary action and the resulting consequences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.2 Principles</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Disciplinary process is premised on prevention and rehabilitation rather than on being punitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; All disciplinary action taken should be through the due disciplinary process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; To ensure that staff who have breached the disciplinary code are treated justly and with consistency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3 Disciplinary Code</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The disciplinary code contains two categories of infractions:. Misconduct and Gross misconduct. This however will not preclude management from taking action against misconduct not mentioned in the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3.1 Misconduct:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Definition: Misconduct shall include violations of Musoni Kenya Limited operational rules and procedures that do not necessarily amount to gross misconduct but may affect the continuity, and efficiency of Musoni operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Misconduct may result in either verbal or written warnings to the employee as per the progressive disciplinary process. Any violation of the rules after a final written warning has been issued shall be classified as Gross Misconduct for which an employee will be liable to Dismissal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fallowing are examples of Misconduct that may result in either verbal or written warnings to the employee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Late coming</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Absenteeism</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Failure to achieve set performance targets</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Misuse of Musonis property or name</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Being involved in actions that bring Musoni Kenya into disrepute</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Physical Violence<br />\r\nThe foregoing procedure (progressive disciplinary process) shall be invoked following any misconduct by an employee.<br />\r\n12.3.2 Disciplinary Process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Definition: Progressive discipline is a system where the severity of the disciplinary penalty increases each time an employee commits an ordinary infraction amounting to Misconduct. Typically the progression will normally begin at the lowest step in the progressive discipline process but may be advanced dependent upon the seriousness of the performance or infraction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Serious infractions amounting to gross misconduct shall not be subjected to the progressive disciplinary process but shall be referred to a disciplinary panel/committee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3.3 Guiding Principles</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Degrees of discipline are progressive and are used to ensure the employee has the opportunity to correct their performance. Factors to be considered are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; The variety and number of problems involved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; The seriousness of the violation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; The time interval and employee response to prior disciplinary action(s).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Previous work history of the employee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In general, verbal warnings should, at the next violation, be followed by a Written Warning, followed at the next violation by suspension or final warning, then dismissal. This is especially true in those cases where the time interval between the violations is short and the employee isn&#39;t remorseful about their indiscipline or demonstrates a lack of desire to improve his/her performance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following disciplinary penalties shall be used in progression as appropriate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a) Verbal Warning b) Written Warning<br />\r\nc) Final Written Warning</p>\r\n\r\n<p>d) Dismissal, Summary Dismissal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Progression of Disciplinary Process:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following processes from verbal warning to final warning shall be administered at the department level assisted by the Chief Human Resources Officer and shall not necessitate a formal disciplinary hearing:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a) Verbal warning: The Verbal Warning is a conversation between a supervisor and an employee held in private about a disciplinary or performance problem. It is the first step of the progressive disciplinary process. Like all other disciplinary actions Verbal warnings must be documented and sent<br />\r\nto the Chief Human Resource Officer (CHRO) to be placed on the employees file.<br />\r\nb) Written warning: A written warning is a documented formal conversation between a supervisor and an employee about a disciplinary or performance problem. It is the second step of the progressive disciplinary process. The Written Warning is usually used only after a Verbal Warning has been given and no change in performance has resulted. Upon documenting the conversation, the supervisor shall request the employee to sign against it and forward it to the CHRO to be placed on the employee&#39;s file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c) Final Written Warning: A final written warning is a documented formal conversation between a Head of Department and an employee about a continuing disciplinary or performance problem. It is the third step in the progressive discipline process. The purpose of the Final Written Warning is to correct a performance problem by discussing it with the employee and providing a written record of that conversation. This is a last chance step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When to use a Final Written Warning: The Final Written Warning is used after a Verbal Warning and Written Warning have been given by the employee&#39;s immediate supervisor and no change in performance has resulted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3.4 Warning Procedures</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is desirable for all Heads of departments plus Branch Managers to follow the following steps before a verbal warning, written warning or final warning is issued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Talk to the employee privately (in an office, Board room or other quiet area).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; State the specific problem in terms of desired performance and actual performance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Refer to previous informal counseling about the problem if it&#39;s a verbal warning or previous verbal or written warnings in subsequent cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Give the employee a chance to respond and explain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Tell the employee the specific change in his/her performance which you expect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Have the employee confirm that he/she knows exactly what you expect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Indicate your confidence in his/her ability to perform properly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Document the conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Required Information</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The warning letter must contain the following information:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a) The date of the conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b) The specific rule violation or performance problem that has occurred.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c) A reference to previous Informal counseling or warning notices about the problem.<br />\r\nd) A statement of the specific change in the employee&#39;s performance or behaviour you expect. e) Any comments or statements the employee made during the conversation.<br />\r\nf) A statement indicating your confidence in the employee&#39;s ability to perform properly in the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>g) Have the employee sign the memo. If the employee refuses, a statement regarding your attempt to have the employee sign and his/her refusal to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Role of Documentation in the Disciplinary Process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Documentation is an essential element of the disciplinary process. Documentation ensures that a manager accurately remembers the goals that he/she has set for an employee, whether performance standards were met, why standards were not met, and how an employee performed months before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Without documentation, a manager is unable to provide an employee with specific examples of performance. The more complete and accurate the documentation, the easier it is for a manager to make and substantiate an evaluation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Documentation is also critical when a manager/supervisor needs to substantiate his actions to others. In the event that an evaluation, pay raise, or disciplinary action is challenged, documentation will be the key to supporting that action. Memory alone will not be substantial enough to support a decision when grievances, disciplinary hearings, and unfair dismissal suits arise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3.5 Gross Misconduct</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gross Misconduct includes any violation of Musoni Kenya Limited rules and regulations of such a degree that continued employment of the individual shall not be desirable. The following are examples of some scenarios that amount to Gross Misconduct warranting an employee&#39;s instant dismissal:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Absenteeism from work without permission</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Incapability whilst on duty brought on by alcohol or illegal drugs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Negligence of duty &ndash; if one willfully neglects to perform any work which was his duty to perform or if one carelessly performs any work that was his duty to perform under his contract of employment that might cause unacceptable loss, damage or injury.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Use of abusive language or behaving in a manner that is insulting to his/her employer or to a person in authority. This includes assault, battery or intimidation of other staff members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Insubordination - refusal to obey a command from a senior officer which is within the scope of your duty to perform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; If an employee breaks the law and is arrested and imprisoned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Theft, fraud or deliberate falsification of records</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Serious breach of confidentiality</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Conflict of interest</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.3.6 Disciplinary Process and Procedure for Gross Misconduct</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon the commission of a violation amounting to gross misconduct an employee will immediately be relieved of his/her duties and shall be placed on investigative suspension by the Disciplinary Committee which shall consist of the [CEO, CHRO, Head of Department and any other member of the Management Team] An investigative suspension is a period during which an employee is relieved of his or her job with half pay, because of allegations of Gross misconduct.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In some circumstances it may be necessary to suspend the employee for a period whilst enquiries are made. The purpose of the suspension is to make a full investigation to determine the facts of the case. Investigative suspension shall not exceed 30days or the duration of the investigation whichever is shorter but in all cases where such investigation exceeds 30 days, the employee&#39;s salary shall be restored to full pay until the investigation is complete. In cases where the employee is absolved, his<br />\r\n/her outstanding pay for the duration of the suspension shall be paid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In cases where the misconduct does not necessitate further investigation the employee will be dismissed from our employment without notice. The power to dismiss shall be vested in the disciplinary committee. The committee shall, before terminating the employment of an employee or summarily dismissing an employee hear and consider any representations which the employee makes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An employee whose contract is terminated summarily shall lose his entitlement to the normal terminal benefits including, notice pay. However, such employee shall be entitled to pay for actual days<br />\r\nworked during the month in which the dismissal occurs, and accrued leave.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13. GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES<br />\r\nGrievance is any dissatisfaction or feeling of injustice on the part of the employee in connection with his/her work situation, management&#39;s decision, or disciplinary action against him/her</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any individual staff member wishing to seek redress for grievances relating to his/her employment will in the first instance report the grievance or dispute to his/her Manager/Supervisor and/or the CHRO or designate in writing who shall undertake to investigate the problem without delay and seek resolution. If the staff member feels that his/her grievance or dispute cannot be dealt with or easily resolved through either of these channels, he/she will resort to the CEO, whose role will be to handle and mediate appeals, cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A staff member who perceives that he/she is subject to harassment and/or intimidation shall immediately report his/her complaint in writing to his/her supervisor or the CHRO or designate The staff member accused of harassment and/or intimidation shall be advised immediately in writing and invited to present his/her case. Resolution shall be sought as quickly as possible</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The grievance procedure will be subject to review by management on a regular basis. The grievance procedure has the objective of resolving disputes internally. The employee should only invoke this procedure if he remains dissatisfied. Grievance reports should be dealt with in strict confidentiality by the involved employee, the witness and by Musoni. This procedure applies to all employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1: Statement of grievance</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The employee should set out the grievance in writing and send it to his direct supervisor. Without such a written statement, Musoni has no obligation to take the grievance to a meeting. The statement should be addressed, be headed by the word &ldquo;Grievance&rdquo; and should clearly include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; The problem</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; How it affects the employee</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Who and what causes it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; What the employee thinks Musoni and the employee should do about it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: Meeting</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As soon as reasonably possible after receiving the statement, Musoni will invite the involved employee to attend a meeting to discuss the grievance. The meeting will be arranged as quickly as possible after Musoni had a reasonable opportunity to consider the response. Afterwards Musoni will inform the involved employee in writing what Musoni has decided to do about the grievance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3: Appeal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The employee must write to Musoni if he wishes to appeal against the Musoni decision within a week after he received the written decision of Musoni. Musoni will then invite the employee to attend a further meeting. If deemed necessary by Musoni, Musoni shall be represented at the appeal meeting by a more senior person than attended the first meeting. After the appeal meeting, Musoni will inform<br />\r\nall involved of the final decision.<br />\r\n14. TERMINATION</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy sets out the conditions and procedures relating to termination of employment with Musoni. It aims to ensure that Musoni is in line with good employment practice and complies with the statutory requirements. Termination shall fall under the following categories:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.1 Retirement</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The retirement age in Musoni Kenya Limited is 60 years. This shall in no way preclude management from offering a particular employee a further term on a fixed contract.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.2 Expiry of Contract</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Contracts of service that have run their term shall for purposes of this section be considered terminated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.3 Incapacity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Incapacity should be certified by a medical doctor appointed by Musoni Kenya Limited confirming that an employee is incapable of carrying out his/her duties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.4 Death</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Death shall automatically discharge a contract of employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.5 Resignation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where an employee terminates his/her contract of service by giving the requisite notice stipulated in their contracts. The following steps shall be followed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1: Submission of Resignation Letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any staff that wishes to terminate his employment must submit a letter of resignation to the Chief Human Resources Officer with a copy to the Immediate Supervisor. The immediate supervisor should endorse the letter to signify his/her acknowledgement of the resignation and send the copy to the CHRO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: Return of Musoni Property</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon leaving the service of Musoni, the employee must handover to the immediate supervisor or designated officer all accounts, contracts, data, records and documents whether in paper, tape, diskette or electronic form related to his /her job. Musoni reserves the right to deduct from the employees&rsquo; final dues any amount equivalent to the value of any property that is not returned or damaged and any other amount due to Musoni Kenya limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3 Staff Exit Interview</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Human Resources Department will normally conduct an exit interview with the resigning employee to obtain a better understanding of his needs to solicit his feedback in Musonis policies and practices so as to improve the overall working environment and conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4 Final Dues</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The final payment including basic salary, job related payments or reimbursements, payments in lieu of accrued annual leave and money due to the employee (if any) will be paid to the resigned employee within 30 days from the effective date of handover and clearance.<br />\r\n14.6 Disciplinary Process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A contract of service may be terminated through the disciplinary process, either by summary dismissal or dismissal with notice. Consequently, if a staff member&#39;s performance does not measure up fully to the requirements of their post at the time of their appraisal for two consecutive appraisal periods, and he/she receives a poor or below average rating, the Supervisor has the option of recommending demotion or termination all of which shall follow the disciplinary procedure. (See Annex 6: Appraisal Form).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.7 Other Instances of termination</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Terminations resulting from Restructuring, Mergers and Acquisitions, downsizing and/or Rightsizing also known as laying off, Retrenchment, Redundancy, Abolition of Office or by whatever technical name that may be used at the time:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Management shall always ensure that the process is carried out in a fair manner and that employees are informed ahead of time. In circumstances where such notification may pause a risk to the company&rsquo;s business, management may opt to notify the Labour Office instead. Musoni shall come up with criteria to determine who shall be affected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Labour Officer shall always be notified of any such layoffs not less than a month prior to the date of the intended date of termination. Such notification shall include the reasons for the terminations,<br />\r\nnumber and categories of the affected employees plus particulars of terminal benefits.<br />\r\n15. Other Obligations at End of Service<br />\r\nBefore ending service with Musoni Keya Limited, a staff member shall return any material, equipment or intellectual property (data, documentation, official papers and reference works whether in printed or electronic form and computer programs belonging to Musoni Kenya Limited in his/her custody, identity card and all keys provided by Musoni Kenya Limited).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.1 Staff clearance</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff will be required to handover and clear with their respective immediate Supervisors and all Heads of Departments before they leave.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.2 Exit Interview</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CHRO or designate will arrange an exit interview for staff member(s) leaving the service of</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.3 Certificate of service</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the termination of a contract of service, Musoni Kenya Limited shall, if so requested by the employee, provide the employee with a certificate indicating-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a) The names and addresses of Musoni Kenya Limited and the employee;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b) The length of the employee&#39;s period of continuous employment with Musoni Kenya Limited;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c) The capacity in which the employee was employed prior to the termination;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>d) The certificate of service shall not contain any judgment or evaluation of the employee&#39;s work but if the employee so requests for it, Musoni Kenya Limited shall provide it in a separate letter of recommendation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.4 Public Notice</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If deemed necessary, Management of Musoni Kenya Limited at its discretion shall have the right to place a public notice in regard to exited staff members.<br />\r\n1.Duncan Goldi<br />\r\nAnnex 1: Sample External job advert</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CAREER OPPORTUNITY<br />\r\nWEALTH CREATION OFFICER / INDIVIDUAL LENDING OFFICER<br />\r\nMusoni is the world&rsquo;s first financial institution to exclusively use mobile money. We aim to be one of the leading providers of mobile microfinance through the use of efficient and seamless technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are looking for suitable and qualified individuals to fill the positions of Wealth Creation Officers and Individual Lending Officers in our various branches. Reporting to the Branch Manager, the Officers will be expected to:<br />\r\nConsistently grow the company&#39;s product portfolio by marketing to individuals and groups.<br />\r\nDevelop plans for growth of the product and identify suitable clients.<br />\r\nConduct client education on the new products features and requirements<br />\r\nConduct loan appraisals<br />\r\nVisit client business premises from time to time during loan assessment and monitoring to ensure the quality of the loan is maintained at the expected level<br />\r\nParticipate in the setting of personal product targets and work toward meeting the same</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Qualifications, skills and experience<br />\r\nDiploma in business related discipline from a recognized college.<br />\r\nA business related degree will be an added advantage<br />\r\nAt least 1 year of relevant experience in Group or Individual Lending from a Microfinance Institution or Commercial Bank.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Competencies and personal attributes<br />\r\nAbility to work with numbers, conduct analysis of information<br />\r\nAbility and willingness to follow up clients personally and with a keen eye on both financial data<br />\r\nAbility to make sound judgment and quick right decisions<br />\r\nAbility to build trust, value others, communicate effectively and drive execution<br />\r\nSelf-motivated and proven ability to motivate others<br />\r\nInitiative, tact and maturity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your career aspirations match the requirements of this exciting career opportunity, please send your CV and cover letter, to careers@musoni.co.ke with the title &ldquo;Wealth Creation Officer&rdquo; or &ldquo;Individual Lending Officer&rdquo; on the subject line not later than Friday 22nd November, 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni Kenya Limited is an equal opportunity Employer<br />\r\nAnnex 2: Interview assessment form<br />\r\nINTERVIEW ASSESSMENT FORM<br />\r\nPOSITION:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CANDIDATE NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INTERVIEWER DATE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SKILL/EXPERIENCE MAX MARKS MARKS AWARDED REMARKS<br />\r\n1. Presentation Skill: capturing the audience, confidence levels, self-presentation, personality, communication skills 10<br />\r\n2. Ability to think on the spot, handle the questions following the presentation 10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Understanding of MFI operations, marketing, portfolio management and arrears. 10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Innovation: ability to go an extra mile and think out of the box. 10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Understanding of Musoni Kenya. 10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Total Marks 50 &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;<br />\r\nPractical Test Results 50 &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;<br />\r\nGrand Total 100 &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;<br />\r\nComments:<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n____________________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\nCurrent Salary<br />\r\nOther Benefits: Medical Pension Bonus<br />\r\nSalary Expectations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notice Period</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recommendation By Interviewer:<br />\r\nHire</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not Hire<br />\r\nReason for (not) hire<br />\r\nInterviewers Signature<br />\r\n73</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 3: Leave Application form</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LEAVE APPLICATION FORM</p>\r\n\r\n<p>STAFF NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<p>STAFF NO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TITLE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DATE<br />\r\nTYPE OF LEAVE FROM (dd/mm/yy) (a) TO (dd/mm/yy) (b) NO. OF LEAVE DAYS (c)= (b-a) LEAVE DAYS BROUGHT FORWARD (d) LEAVE DAYS OUTSTANDING (d-c)<br />\r\nREMARKS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annual Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sick Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maternity/Paternity Leave<br />\r\nCompassionate Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marriage Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No-pay Leave</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DUTIES HANDED OVER TO:<br />\r\nSIGNATURE OF APPLICANT:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MANAGER&#39;S APPROVAL/COMMENTS<br />\r\nANNEX 4: Sample Appraisal Form</p>\r\n\r\n<p>STAFF PERFORMANCE APPRAISAL<br />\r\nUse Arial 10 to complete; expand or contract cells if needed but stay within page limit</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PERIOD: From: July, 2016 To: December, 2016 Date Finalised:&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Name:<br />\r\nXXX<br />\r\nJob Title:<br />\r\nWealth Creation Officer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Department:<br />\r\nOperations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisor:<br />\r\nBranch Manager</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reviewing Supervisor:<br />\r\nChief Operations Officer<br />\r\nSECTION 1: RESULTS RATINGS TO BE COMPLETED BY STAFF MEMBER AND SUPERVISOR.<br />\r\nPERFORMANCE RESULTS FOR THIS SECTION COMPRISES OF 80% OF THE TOTAL SCORE.<br />\r\nThere are 5 - 8 key Performance Indicators for which the staff member is responsible and which can be measured accurately. Ratings to be completed by the staff member and the supervisor. Performance results for this section comprises of 80% of the total score. 50%<br />\r\n75%<br />\r\n100%<br />\r\n101% &amp; above Unsatisfactory<br />\r\nPartly satisfactory<br />\r\nSatisfactory<br />\r\nGood<br />\r\nPERFORMANCE INDICATOR TARGET RESULTS ACHEIVED % RATING<br />\r\nTotal Funded Borrowers<br />\r\nOutstanding Loan Book<br />\r\nPAR Total (including write offs)<br />\r\nNew Groups / Clients<br />\r\nDisbursements<br />\r\nCaseload<br />\r\nRetention Rate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Total Average Score<br />\r\nFormula: Total Rating X 0.8 =<br />\r\nNo. of KPIs<br />\r\nEmployees Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisors Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SECTION 2:<br />\r\nRESULTS RATINGS TO BE COMPLETED BY STAFF MEMBER AND SUPERVISOR.<br />\r\nPERFORMANCE RESULTS FOR THIS SECTION COMPRISES OF 20% OF THE TOTAL SCORE.<br />\r\nTHE RATING SCALE IS BETWEEN UNSATISFACTORY &amp; SATISFACTORY (50% - 100%) Self-Rating<br />\r\n% Supervisors Rating %<br />\r\nClient Orientation: Understands client needs and concerns; responds promptly and effectively to client needs throughout the sales cycle (Marketing, training, disbursement, monitoring and follow up). Also includes the internal clients.<br />\r\nDrive for Results: Makes things happen; is proactive; balances &lsquo;&rsquo;analysis&rdquo; with &ldquo;doing&rdquo;, sets high standards for self, commits to organisation&rsquo;s goals.<br />\r\nTeam work: Collaborates with others within the branch, acknowledges others&rsquo; contributions; works effectively with individuals regardless of their ethnicity and gender, willing to seek help as needed.<br />\r\nLearning and Knowledge Sharing: Open to new ideas, shares own knowledge; applies knowledge in daily work; builds partnerships for learning and sharing<br />\r\nPeople Management (for Managers, SWCO&rsquo;s &amp; Team Leaders only)<br />\r\nPlanning &amp; Managing Staff to Achieve Quality Results<br />\r\nEncouraging an open, team based environment<br />\r\nDelegating skills &amp; Inspiring Trust<br />\r\nCreating an environment for learning and knowledge sharing<br />\r\nTotal Average Score<br />\r\nFormula: Total Supervisors Rating X 0.2 =<br />\r\nNo. of Behaviour KPIs<br />\r\nEmployees Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisor Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SECTION 3: SKILLS PROFILE<br />\r\nSkills in which individual is strong: (To be completed by the employee)<br />\r\n.<br />\r\nFurther Skills and Training needed to enhance effectiveness (To be completed by the employee)<br />\r\nEmployees Comments<br />\r\nSupervisor Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SECTION 4: OVERALL RATING AND COMMENTS including if applicable: (a) noteworthy contributions; (b) areas in need of improvement; (c) request for definition of assignment or tasks in year ahead; and (d) requests for change of assignment<br />\r\nOVERALL RATING: (Supervisor to complete by adding the total % average score in Sections 1 and 2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>101% and above = Good (G)<br />\r\n76% - 100% = Satisfactory (S)<br />\r\n51% - 75% = Partly Satisfactory (PS)<br />\r\n50% and below = Unsatisfactory (U)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-------------------------------------<br />\r\nEmployees Comments<br />\r\nSupervisor Comments</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SECTION 5: PERFORMANCE GOALS FOR NEXT REVIEW PERIOD (agreed between Employee and Supervisor)<br />\r\nKPI TARGET<br />\r\nTotal Funded Borrowers<br />\r\nOutstanding loan book<br />\r\nPAR Total (including write offs)<br />\r\nNew Groups / Clients<br />\r\nDisbursements<br />\r\nCaseload<br />\r\nRetention Rate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SECTION 6: OVERALL COMMENTS AND SIGNATURES<br />\r\nI have discussed this appraisal with my Supervisor<br />\r\nEmployee Signature: &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;. Date:&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisor Signature:&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.. Date:&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;<br />\r\nNAME OF EMPLOYEE FOR SUCCESSION CURRENT POSITION POSITION FOR SUCCESSION MENTOR PERIOD UNDER MENTORSHIP Competencies/<br />\r\nSkills before the job Knowledge which has been acquired. Skills gaps which need training and intervention Targets during the period (PAR, Clients, OLB, disbursements) Actual Performance during the period under review (PAR, Clients, OLP, disbursements) Comments by Immediate Supervisor &amp; HoD<br />\r\n1. Lilian WCO Branch Manager Felix 6 months Group lending Portfolio Management Effective Communication, Staff Appraisals,<br />\r\nTeam dynamics PAR - Below 3%<br />\r\nOLB - 8 Million<br />\r\nDisbursements - 50(pm)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Signed by: _____________________________<br />\r\nDate: _________________________________<br />\r\nAnnex 5: Candidate Profile Template (Succession Planning)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notes:<br />\r\nConfidentiality must be maintained. Only the chosen candidates should know of status.<br />\r\nIn case of critical position not getting vacant, the identified successor must have an alternative career plan.<br />\r\nIn case of critical position getting vacant and no internal successor is identified, recourse should be taken to hire external talent to ensure smooth functioning</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Annex 6: Employee exit form (Form 4.6)<br />\r\nEMPLOYEE EXIT FORM<br />\r\nNAME: EMPLOYEE NO.<br />\r\nDESIGNATION: DEPARTMENT:<br />\r\nDate of Employment: Last Day of Work:<br />\r\nAn employee is required to return the property of Musoni to the respective Department before leaving the service of the Company. He/She is instructed to bring this form to the various Departments as stated below to obtain Clearance before collection of any dues.<br />\r\nPlease tick appropriately<br />\r\nBranch<br />\r\nPortfolio handover Report A duly signed handing over report must be attached to this form.<br />\r\nField Bag<br />\r\nCalculator<br />\r\nLending &amp; Credit Manual<br />\r\nFliers<br />\r\nFiles<br />\r\nBusiness Cards<br />\r\nStaff ID &amp; Medical Cards<br />\r\nAny Registered Group<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (BM):<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finance Department<br />\r\nChief Finance Officer<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (CFO):<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IT Department<br />\r\nIT Manager<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (IT Officer):<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Risk Manager<br />\r\nIT Manager<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (Risk Manager):<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Audit Department<br />\r\nInternal Auditor<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (IA):<br />\r\nDate:<br />\r\nOperations Department<br />\r\nChief Operation Officer<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (COO):<br />\r\nDate:<br />\r\nFor Maisha Bora Sacco members only:-<br />\r\nMaisha Bora Sacco<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Loan Balance<br />\r\nCleared by:<br />\r\nDate &amp; Stamp:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Human Resources Department<br />\r\nChief Human Resources Officer<br />\r\nAny Outstanding Items (state nature)<br />\r\nCleared by (CHRO):<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee comments about their work experience with Musoni<br />\r\nPlease complete this section (Where Applicable). YOUR RESPONSES ARE CONFIDENTIAL.<br />\r\nWhat did you like most about your job?<br />\r\n___________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n___________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\nWhat did you like least about your job?<br />\r\n___________________________________________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>_____________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\nWhat has your new place of employment offered that is more attractive than your present job?<br />\r\n___________________________________________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other remarks<br />\r\n___________________________________________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employer&rsquo;s Comments<br />\r\n______________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\n_______________________________________________________________________________<br />\r\nEmployer&rsquo;s Signature (CEO) Date</p>\r\n\r\n<p>___________________________ _________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employee&#39;s Signature Date_______ ____________________<br />\r\nAnnex 7: Letter of confirmation (Form 4.7)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[INSERT DATE OF CONFIRMATION]<br />\r\n[INSERT NAME OF THE STAFF] P.O. Box 15238 - 00100<br />\r\nNAIROBI</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dear [NAME OF STAFF],<br />\r\nLetter of Confirmation<br />\r\nFollowing completion of your six months&rsquo; probation period at Musoni, we have reviewed your performance and found the same to be satisfactory.<br />\r\nIn view of the above, we are pleased to inform you that you have been confirmed to the position of<br />\r\n[INSERT POSITION] at Musoni Kenya Limited with effect from [INSERT DATE OF CONFIRMATION].<br />\r\nConsequently you will be eligible to participate in the Staff Contributory Pension Scheme. The company will contribute 10% of your basic salary with an additional 5% to be contributed by you as a payroll deduction. This sum is payable to you upon termination of service or upon retirement as per Retirement Benefits Authority (RBA) terms and regulations.<br />\r\nThe company however reserves the right to change the nature, quality or level of these benefits at any time without reference to you.<br />\r\nAll other terms and conditions mentioned in the appointment letter will remain the same.<br />\r\nThis letter is sent to you in duplicate. To confirm acceptance of this position and terms, please sign and return one copy to my attention.<br />\r\nYours sincerely,<br />\r\n[INSERT NAME]<br />\r\nChief Executive Officer<br />\r\nI , hereby confirm having accepted this offer and the conditions stated herein with effect from [INSERT DATE OF CONFIRMATION].<br />\r\nSigned:<br />\r\nDate:</p>\r\n','','2017-03-30 07:03:51','2017-03-30 07:03:51'),(11,1,1,12,2,'Musoni Whistleblowing Policy','musoni-whistleblowing-policy-1490868359','<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PURPOSE</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Musoni is committed to high standards of ethical, moral and legal business conduct. In line with this commitment, and the Board and the management is committed to open communication. This policy aims to provide an avenue for Musoni employees to raise concerns and reassurance that they will be protected from reprisals or victimization for whistleblowing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whistleblowing policies are generally intended to make it easier for members of staff to be able to report irregularities in good faith, without having to fear that their action may have adverse consequences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Whistleblowing Policy is a key element for safeguarding the Musoni&rsquo;s integrity. It is aimed at enhancing transparency and underpinning its system for combating practices that might damage its activities and reputation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Protecting the integrity and reputation of MUSONI requires the active support of all members of MUSONI&rsquo;s staff, who are required to report incidents of suspected fraud, corruption, collusion and coercion, and other serious infringements of the rules and policies in force at MUSONI. Members of staff must also cooperate in investigations into such incidents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By creating an environment of trust and maximum protection for the members of its staff, MUSONI wants to encourage them to cooperate in full. It is putting in place arrangements that will ensure that members of staff who report irregularities in good faith are afforded the utmost confidentiality and greatest degree of and most effective protection possible against any retaliation or reprisals, whether actual or threatened, as a result of their whistleblowing.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BASIC PRINCIPLES</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The basic principles of MUSONI&rsquo;s Whistleblowing Policy are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>the persons concerned must have a choice between a number of channels for whistleblowing and communication; in certain circumstances, they must be able to bypass the main channels for whistleblowing if these prove inappropriate;</li>\r\n	<li>members of staff must not under any circumstances be subject to reprisals for whistleblowing;</li>\r\n	<li>members of staff who report incidents in good faith must be protected and their identity must insofar as possible remain confidential;</li>\r\n	<li>the reported incidents shall be verified in the appropriate manner and, if they are confirmed, MUSONI shall take all necessary steps to identify appropriate remedies;</li>\r\n	<li>the basic rights of any person implicated by the reported incidents must be respected, whilst ensuring that the procedures provided for are effective.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955897\"></a>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SCOPE OF THE POLICY</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>MUSONI&rsquo;s Whistleblowing Policy applies to all permanent staff members and any other person providing MUSONI with services, including consultants and other service providers under contract (grouped together for the purposes of this document under the term &ldquo;staff member(s)&rdquo;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; REPORTING OBLIGATIONS</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Members of staff are required to report any suspected or presumed incidents of illegal behaviour in the activities of MUSONI or of serious misconduct or serious infringement of MUSONI&rsquo;s rules, policies or guidelines, or any action that is or could be harmful to the mission or reputation of MUSONI (hereinafter &ldquo;irregularities&rdquo;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Such incidents may involve members of staff, borrowers, promoters, contractors, suppliers, beneficiaries or any other persons or entities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Members of staff are required to cooperate in any official investigation, audit or similar request.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No members of staff may use their position to prevent other members of staff from exercising their rights or complying with their obligations as indicated above.&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc287955899\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; REPORTING PROCEDURES</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955900\"></a>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reporting of cases of alleged fraud, corruption, money laundering or financing of terrorism<br />\r\n&ndash; or &ndash;<br />\r\nof a serious failure or infringement of ethics or integrity</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>(a) For cases of alleged fraud, corruption, collusion or coercion, money laundering and financing of terrorism, or any other unlawful activity that is detrimental to the financial interests of MUSONI, the member of staff is required to inform the internal auditor through the following contacts:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Email:&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:annemwasi@musoni.eu\">annemwasi@musoni.eu</a></li>\r\n	<li>Cell phone: +254722870101</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>(b) If the event the use of the above reporting procedures is not appropriate in view of the circumstances or nature of the incidents (for instance, if there is a conflict of interest or a risk of reprisals, the intended recipient of the report is personally implicated in the incidents to be reported, or the authority initially alerted fails to take appropriate action), the member of staff may inform Musoni CEO through the following contacts:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Email:&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:jamesonyutta@musoni.eu\">jamesonyutta@musoni.eu</a></li>\r\n	<li>Cell phone: +254716505179</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>(c) In the event of the use of the above reporting procedures is not appropriate in view of the circumstances or nature of the incidents (for instance, if there is a conflict of interest or a risk of reprisals, the intended recipient of the report is personally implicated in the incidents to be reported, or the authority initially alerted fails to take appropriate action), the member of staff may as a last resort, refer the matter to Musoni BOD through the following contacts:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:wambuikyama@gmail.com\">wambuikyama@gmail.com</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Cell phone; 254722643121</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OR</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Email:&nbsp;<a name=\"_Toc287955901\"></a>duncan@musoni.eu</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955902\"></a>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; REPORTING ARRANGEMENTS AND ANONYMITY</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>It is up to staff members to choose the most appropriate channel for reporting incidents which they must disclose. However, if a matter is reported to an authority that is not competent to deal with it, it is up to that authority to transmit, in strictest confidence, the relevant information and documents to the competent authority and to inform the member of staff accordingly.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MAINTAINING CONFIDENTIALITY</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The confidentiality and anonymity of persons making complaints or expressing concerns will be maintained to the fullest extent possible, consistent with the need to conduct an investigation unless required by law to break that confidentiality. The Board encourages you to supply contact information with your submission to facilitate clarification and any assistance with possible investigation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To assist the Board in reviewing and, if necessary, investigating your complaints or concerns, you should provide as much factual, rather than speculative, information as possible. To the extent possible, you should include the following information in your submission:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>the alleged event, matter or issue that is the subject of the complaint or concern;</li>\r\n	<li>the name of each person you believe involved;</li>\r\n	<li>if the complaint or concern involves a specific event or events, the approximate date(s) and location(s) of each event; and</li>\r\n	<li>any additional information, documentation or other evidence you believe support the complaint or concern.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955903\"></a>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PROTECTION OF THE WHISTLEBLOWER</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Any staff member who reports an irregularity, provided that this is done in good faith and in compliance with the provisions of this policy, shall be protected against any acts of retaliation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the purposes of this policy, &quot;retaliation&quot; is defined as any action or threat of action which is unjustly detrimental to the whistleblower because of his/her report, including, but not limited to, harassment, discrimination and acts of vindictiveness, direct or indirect, that are recommended, threatened or taken against the whistleblower.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Good faith&rdquo; can be taken to mean the unequivocal belief in the veracity of the reported incidents, i.e. the fact that the member of staff reasonably believes the transmitted information to be true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff members, who make a report in bad faith, particularly if it is based knowingly on false or misleading information, shall not be protected and shall be subject to disciplinary measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955905\"></a>8.1 Protective measures</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The protection of a person reporting an irregularity shall be guaranteed first of all by the fact that their identity will be treated in confidence. This means that their name will not be revealed, unless the whistleblower personally authorises the disclosure of his/her identity or this is a statutory requirement, particularly if it is essential to ensure that the right of the persons implicated to be given a fair hearing is upheld. In such a case, person handling the report (one of the three persons mentioned above) shall be required to notify the whistleblower before revealing their identity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>8.2 No Retaliation</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>No member of staff who in good faith reports irregularity shall suffer harassment, retaliation or adverse employment consequence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where members of staff consider that they have been the victim of retaliation for reporting an irregularity or have good reason to believe or fear that they are exposed to a risk of retaliation as a result of their reporting an irregularity, they shall be entitled to complain to the any other person mentioned above and request that protective measures be adopted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The authority approached shall assess the circumstances of the case referred to it and may recommend to the BOD that temporary and/or permanent measures that are necessary in the interests of MUSONI be adopted with a view to protecting the staff member in question. The staff member shall be informed in writing of the results of this procedure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; TRAINING OF THE STAFF ON WHISTLEBLOWING</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All Musoni staff will be trained on the whistleblowing at all levels of the organization in relation to whistleblowing law and the organization&rsquo;s policy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>HANDLING REPORTED VIOLATIONS</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>All reports will be promptly investigated and treated consistently and fairly within 60 days from the day of reporting. Appropriate corrective action will be taken if warranted by the investigation. The complainant will be informed that follow-up has or is occurring within two weeks after the Executive Director or board officer has received the complaint or report. The Executive Committee shall be informed of all such complaints or reports</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><a name=\"_Toc287955906\"></a>11.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PENALTIES FOR RETALIATING</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Any form of retaliation undertaken by a staff member against any person for reporting an irregularity in good faith is prohibited and considered to be a serious breach of the loyalty and professional ethics requirements of MUSONI&rsquo;s Code of Conduct. In such a case disciplinary measures shall be taken.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Members of staff will be informed of the measures taken by MUSONI following the discovery of acts of retaliation for reporting an incident. The information provided will not contain any data that will enable the people concerned to be identified.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><a name=\"_Toc287955907\"></a>11.1RIGHTS OF PERSONS IMPLICATED</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Any staff member implicated by reports of irregularities must be notified in good time of the allegations made against them, provided that this notification does not impede the progress of the procedure for establishing the circumstances of the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any event, findings referring to a staff member specifically by name may not be made upon the completion of the above-mentioned procedure, unless that staff member has had the opportunity to put forward their comments in keeping with the principle of respect for the right to be given a fair hearing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After having heard the implicated staff member, or after having requested the latter to put their case in writing if, for objective reasons, it is not possible to hear them directly, the person handling the report (one of the three persons mentioned above) shall decide on the measures required in MUSONI&rsquo;s interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the reporting of irregularities and/or the ensuing procedure will involve dealing with personal data, such data shall be managed in keeping with the principles and rules provided for in the regulations applicable to MUSONI. Those involved in the reporting procedure and in any related procedure, including whistleblowers themselves, may contact the GM at any time in order to check that the rights conferred by the relevant provisions have been respected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>12.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ANNUAL REPORTING</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of each year the Head of Internal Audit shall report on how the organizations reputation has been saved or how it has been saved from making losses by a whistle blower</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>13.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MODIFICATION</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Audit Committee or the Board of Directors of Musoni Kenya can modify this Policy unilaterally at any time without notice. Modification may be necessary, among other reasons, to maintain compliance with local regulations and/or accommodate organizational changes within the Company.</p>\r\n','','2017-03-30 07:05:59','2017-03-30 07:05:59'),(12,1,1,13,2,'Internal Audit Manual','internal-audit-manual-1490868439','<p><strong>Internal Audit Manual</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Version July 2016</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Revised by: Anne Mwasi &amp; Audit Committee Members</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Table of Contents</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.30j0zll\">1.0. Introduction</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.30j0zll\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1fob9te\">1.1 Overview</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1fob9te\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3znysh7\">1.2 Purpose and Scope</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3znysh7\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.2et92p0\">1.3 Applicability</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.2et92p0\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.tyjcwt\">1.4 Business model</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.tyjcwt\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3dy6vkm\">1.5 Audit function</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3dy6vkm\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1t3h5sf\">1.6 Internal Audit Code of Ethics</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1t3h5sf\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.4d34og8\">1.6.1 Integrity</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.4d34og8\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.2s8eyo1\">1.6.2 Objectivity</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.2s8eyo1\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.17dp8vu\">1.6.3 Competence</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.17dp8vu\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3rdcrjn\">1.6.4 Confidentiality</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.3rdcrjn\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.26in1rg\">1.7 Internal Audit Charter</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.26in1rg\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.lnxbz9\">1.8 Zero tolerance policy</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.lnxbz9\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.35nkun2\">2.0 Reporting Lines and Appointment</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.35nkun2\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1ksv4uv\">2.1 Reporting lines of the auditor</a><a href=\"http://documents.musoni.co.ke/wp-admin/post.php?post=30&amp;action=edit#h.1ksv4uv\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n